1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:17,951
A makeover project
for your most unhinged leftovers.

2
00:00:18,018 --> 00:00:21,621
The best chefs in Korea will
turn your fridge inside out.

3
00:00:21,688 --> 00:00:23,790
The classy cooking show has returned.

4
00:00:23,857 --> 00:00:26,926
<i>-Chef & My Fridge!</i>
<i>-My Fridge!</i>

5
00:00:28,595 --> 00:00:29,562
Welcome back.

6
00:00:29,629 --> 00:00:30,930
ALL DRESSED UP

7
00:00:30,997 --> 00:00:34,067
Look at how sharp you're all dressed.

8
00:00:34,134 --> 00:00:36,236
We decided to make this episode
a special occasion

9
00:00:36,302 --> 00:00:39,606
and named the day "Chefs' Party."

10
00:00:39,672 --> 00:00:41,041
CHEFS' PARTY

11
00:00:41,107 --> 00:00:42,442
A party for our chefs.

12
00:00:43,009 --> 00:00:44,744
It's time to party.

13
00:00:44,811 --> 00:00:45,745
ANXIOUS

14
00:00:45,812 --> 00:00:48,415
To begin, we rolled out the red carpet.

15
00:00:48,481 --> 00:00:50,917
ROLLED OUT A RED CARPET
ON THEIR WAY IN

16
00:00:51,651 --> 00:00:53,953
<i>Let's welcome Chef Jung Ho-young!</i>

17
00:00:54,020 --> 00:00:55,855
<i>-Sam Kim.</i>
<i>-Chef Someone.</i>

18
00:00:55,922 --> 00:00:57,824
<i>Will you show us your canine, please?</i>

19
00:00:58,391 --> 00:00:59,692
BANG

20
00:01:00,193 --> 00:01:01,861
WITTY PERFORMANCE
WORTHY OF HIS BUZZ

21
00:01:03,663 --> 00:01:06,499
<i>-He looks sharp in his suit.</i>
<i>-He doesn't seem like a grandpa.</i>

22
00:01:06,566 --> 00:01:07,634
TURNING THE CLOCK BACK

23
00:01:07,700 --> 00:01:10,537
<i>-Who would call him a grandpa?</i>
<i>-I've never seen a grandpa like him.</i>

24
00:01:10,603 --> 00:01:11,571
<i>What a stylish grandpa.</i>

25
00:01:11,638 --> 00:01:13,940
<i>Look who this is! It's Nam-no.</i>

26
00:01:14,007 --> 00:01:17,110
<i>-That's Nam-no. And Chef Kwon Sung-jun.</i>
<i>-Is that really Nam-no?</i>

27
00:01:17,177 --> 00:01:19,245
<i>No one is around,</i>
<i>but he still waves his hand.</i>

28
00:01:19,312 --> 00:01:21,915
<i>He's offering his autograph,</i>
<i>but no one is there.</i>

29
00:01:22,515 --> 00:01:23,683
I'll hold his hand.

30
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:25,585
<i>-Bodyguard.</i>
<i>-Sung-jun the bodyguard.</i>

31
00:01:25,652 --> 00:01:27,120
<i>She's walking in.</i>

32
00:01:27,187 --> 00:01:29,222
<i>She's wearing short sleeves</i>
<i>despite the cold weather.</i>

33
00:01:29,289 --> 00:01:31,391
HER PERSONAL DANCE

34
00:01:31,458 --> 00:01:32,859
<i>-The dancer.</i>
<i>-Here comes Jong-won.</i>

35
00:01:32,926 --> 00:01:33,993
ENTER GOOD VIBES

36
00:01:34,060 --> 00:01:35,528
<i>Look at him.</i>

37
00:01:35,595 --> 00:01:37,831
<i>He kind of resembles Keanu Reeves.</i>

38
00:01:37,897 --> 00:01:39,365
Why are your arms so short?

39
00:01:39,432 --> 00:01:40,934
THE CHEFS HAD A LOT OF FUN

40
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:42,302
<i>-Fridge!</i>
<i>-Fridge!</i>

41
00:01:42,368 --> 00:01:45,071
<i>You all dressed up for today's shoot.</i>

42
00:01:45,138 --> 00:01:48,675
There was something
the chefs were dying to do,

43
00:01:48,741 --> 00:01:51,911
the number one ranking item
on their bucket list.

44
00:01:51,978 --> 00:01:54,514
It's <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Awards.

45
00:01:54,581 --> 00:01:56,649
CHEF & MY FRIDGE AWARDS

46
00:01:56,716 --> 00:02:00,520
But award shows usually wrap up the year.
Don't you think the timing is odd?

47
00:02:00,587 --> 00:02:02,655
-Well, it's not the season.
-No.

48
00:02:02,722 --> 00:02:04,224
No, right now,

49
00:02:04,290 --> 00:02:05,892
it's the year-end on the lunar calendar.

50
00:02:05,959 --> 00:02:08,094
-You're right.
-The elderly are still on that system.

51
00:02:08,161 --> 00:02:10,330
-Our parents are on the lunar calendar.
-He's right.

52
00:02:10,396 --> 00:02:14,434
He began to use the lunar calendar
after he became a grandpa!

53
00:02:14,501 --> 00:02:16,369
-He's going lunar.
-I knew it.

54
00:02:16,436 --> 00:02:18,171
Keeping the good old tradition!

55
00:02:18,238 --> 00:02:19,506
I'll smack you one of these days.

56
00:02:20,073 --> 00:02:21,608
I'm glad you didn't bring your knives.

57
00:02:21,674 --> 00:02:23,143
I don't have them today.

58
00:02:23,209 --> 00:02:26,212
Anyway, it was on your bucket list,

59
00:02:26,279 --> 00:02:29,782
so let us begin
the 2026 <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Awards!

60
00:02:31,518 --> 00:02:35,855
And now, let us begin
the 2026 <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Awards.

61
00:02:35,922 --> 00:02:38,625
We have prepared
three categories of awards.

62
00:02:38,691 --> 00:02:39,792
Three?

63
00:02:39,859 --> 00:02:42,061
-Not everyone can get one.
-So not for everyone.

64
00:02:42,128 --> 00:02:43,263
-Three categories?
-First,

65
00:02:43,329 --> 00:02:45,331
it's the Best Couple Award.

66
00:02:45,398 --> 00:02:46,933
Best Couple Award?

67
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:48,935
Then, followed by
the Best Performance Award.

68
00:02:49,002 --> 00:02:50,703
Performance, I see.

69
00:02:51,404 --> 00:02:52,739
Lastly, the Best Dish Award.

70
00:02:52,805 --> 00:02:54,374
-Best Dish Award. That's the real award.
-That's it.

71
00:02:54,440 --> 00:02:56,209
-I have to win that one.
-We will announce…

72
00:02:56,276 --> 00:02:58,278
-It's all about pride.
-…each winner shortly.

73
00:02:58,344 --> 00:03:01,481
It may be a private celebration,
but the production crew came prepared.

74
00:03:01,548 --> 00:03:03,116
<i>Not only did they prepare plaques,</i>

75
00:03:03,183 --> 00:03:05,385
<i>-but they prepared prizes too.</i>
<i>-That's right.</i>

76
00:03:05,451 --> 00:03:07,120
<i>-Please look forward to it.</i>
<i>-Prizes?</i>

77
00:03:07,187 --> 00:03:10,023
Let us proceed to the first category,

78
00:03:10,089 --> 00:03:11,724
the Best Couple Award.

79
00:03:11,791 --> 00:03:13,660
-Isn't that exciting?
-Best Couple Award.

80
00:03:13,726 --> 00:03:15,695
I'm so nervous… Oh!

81
00:03:16,329 --> 00:03:18,231
Aren't we the hottest new couple?

82
00:03:18,298 --> 00:03:19,933
You two are the <i>Culinary Class War</i> couple.

83
00:03:19,999 --> 00:03:22,202
I think I've seen that moment somewhere.

84
00:03:22,268 --> 00:03:24,504
Let's find out who the nominees are.

85
00:03:25,405 --> 00:03:27,207
LIKE AN ACTUAL AWARDS SHOW

86
00:03:27,273 --> 00:03:28,441
BEST COUPLE AWARD

87
00:03:28,508 --> 00:03:29,809
-What's that?
-What is that?

88
00:03:29,876 --> 00:03:31,244
-It's well-prepared.
-They made this?

89
00:03:31,311 --> 00:03:32,612
<i>How does my sweet and sour beef look?</i>

90
00:03:32,679 --> 00:03:34,514
<i>-How does it look? Yours looks bad too.</i>
<i>-It looks bad.</i>

91
00:03:34,581 --> 00:03:36,216
The first two nominees

92
00:03:36,282 --> 00:03:38,284
grew on each other
after many outrageous fights.

93
00:03:38,351 --> 00:03:40,019
-We had good chemistry.
-The sibling chemistry,

94
00:03:40,086 --> 00:03:43,022
Kwon Sung-jun and Park Eun-yeong.

95
00:03:43,089 --> 00:03:43,923
Dang it.

96
00:03:43,990 --> 00:03:45,458
<i>-You'll do this hair?</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

97
00:03:45,525 --> 00:03:47,260
-Me again?
-What is this?

98
00:03:47,327 --> 00:03:48,428
You're with everyone.

99
00:03:48,494 --> 00:03:49,329
SUNG-JUN & NAM-NO

100
00:03:49,395 --> 00:03:51,698
From the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance
to twins,

101
00:03:51,764 --> 00:03:52,865
the doppelgänger chemistry,

102
00:03:52,932 --> 00:03:54,067
-Sung-jun and Nam-no!
-That's still funny.

103
00:03:54,133 --> 00:03:55,068
Do we count as a couple?

104
00:03:55,568 --> 00:03:57,403
<i>Let's Go, Monkfish!</i>

105
00:03:57,470 --> 00:03:58,738
SON JONG-WON & KIM POONG

106
00:03:58,805 --> 00:03:59,872
The third nominees

107
00:03:59,939 --> 00:04:02,542
are the polished male lead
and the sassy female lead,

108
00:04:02,609 --> 00:04:04,510
showing off
their polar opposite chemistry.

109
00:04:04,577 --> 00:04:06,512
Son Jong-won and Kim Poong.

110
00:04:06,579 --> 00:04:08,648
They're top contenders.

111
00:04:08,715 --> 00:04:09,716
The two buzzworthy guys.

112
00:04:09,782 --> 00:04:10,617
BEST COUPLE AWARD

113
00:04:10,683 --> 00:04:13,353
-We aren't even nominated?
-No, we're with <i>Culinary Class Wars.</i>

114
00:04:13,419 --> 00:04:14,721
We aren't even nominated?

115
00:04:14,787 --> 00:04:17,557
-Your chemistry was on the other show.
-Sam and Ho-young?

116
00:04:17,624 --> 00:04:19,058
Are you talking about the nomination?

117
00:04:19,626 --> 00:04:21,194
IT'D BE NICE IF SOMEONE
SPOKE UP FOR US

118
00:04:21,261 --> 00:04:22,829
Go win the award
on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>, then.

119
00:04:23,563 --> 00:04:24,797
You need to build it up here.

120
00:04:24,864 --> 00:04:25,732
THE SENIOR'S COUPLES ADVICE

121
00:04:25,798 --> 00:04:28,434
-Let's try to win in 2027.
-This is <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Awards.

122
00:04:28,501 --> 00:04:30,236
-I have a chance.
-Sung-jun

123
00:04:30,303 --> 00:04:32,405
-got nominated twice.
-Impressive.

124
00:04:32,472 --> 00:04:33,373
I have a chance.

125
00:04:33,439 --> 00:04:36,776
Which one of the three pairs
will win the Best Couple Award?

126
00:04:36,843 --> 00:04:38,511
-I hope I win one.
-I'll announce the winner.

127
00:04:38,578 --> 00:04:39,979
-What about my speech?
-Now,

128
00:04:40,046 --> 00:04:42,181
the 2026 <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Awards,

129
00:04:42,248 --> 00:04:44,017
the Best Couple Award goes to…

130
00:04:44,617 --> 00:04:46,686
Goodness. I see.

131
00:04:46,753 --> 00:04:48,087
-Oh, no.
-All right.

132
00:04:48,154 --> 00:04:49,589
-I see.
-I'm getting nervous for this?

133
00:04:49,656 --> 00:04:51,624
-The winners.
-The winners are…

134
00:04:51,691 --> 00:04:54,661
Congratulations,
Son Jong-won and Kim Poong!

135
00:04:55,128 --> 00:04:56,129
WHAT A SHAME

136
00:04:56,195 --> 00:04:58,965
-These two were decided as winners.
-Do we have to get up there?

137
00:04:59,032 --> 00:04:59,966
It wasn't me?

138
00:05:00,667 --> 00:05:01,901
Best Couple Award.

139
00:05:02,468 --> 00:05:03,303
There's a heart.

140
00:05:03,369 --> 00:05:05,471
BEST COUPLE AWARD
SON JONG-WON HEARTS KIM POONG

141
00:05:05,538 --> 00:05:08,308
-I think these are matching pajamas.
-Is that so?

142
00:05:08,374 --> 00:05:09,375
Thank you.

143
00:05:09,442 --> 00:05:11,711
In any case, congratulations.

144
00:05:11,778 --> 00:05:13,713
Let's find out what the prizes are.

145
00:05:13,780 --> 00:05:16,182
-Do we have to open them?
-Yes, show us.

146
00:05:16,249 --> 00:05:18,651
-All right.
-Are they really matching pajamas?

147
00:05:18,718 --> 00:05:20,320
-What is it?
-Is that Korean pork?

148
00:05:20,887 --> 00:05:23,022
Now, the prizes for the best couple was…

149
00:05:23,089 --> 00:05:25,091
-Pork cutlets?
-What is it? Why are you laughing?

150
00:05:25,158 --> 00:05:27,293
-What is it?
-Show everyone.

151
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:29,262
A matching T-shirt.

152
00:05:29,329 --> 00:05:31,230
I'm going to wear this. Really.

153
00:05:31,297 --> 00:05:32,365
NOT PAJAMAS, BUT T-SHIRTS

154
00:05:32,432 --> 00:05:33,633
Do you think I won't?

155
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:36,002
A HUGE PICTURE OF SON AND POONG

156
00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:37,537
-It's from the team dinner.
-I'm jealous.

157
00:05:37,603 --> 00:05:39,138
Oh, my.

158
00:05:39,205 --> 00:05:41,107
CONGRATULATIONS ON
THE BEST COUPLE AWARD

159
00:05:41,174 --> 00:05:44,510
And now, let us continue
with the second category.

160
00:05:44,577 --> 00:05:46,579
This next award

161
00:05:47,146 --> 00:05:49,382
is the Best Performance Award.

162
00:05:49,449 --> 00:05:50,383
I might have a chance.

163
00:05:50,450 --> 00:05:52,485
-Let's find out the nominees.
-The nominees.

164
00:05:53,052 --> 00:05:55,355
Next category, Best Performance Award.

165
00:05:56,756 --> 00:05:57,990
NOMINEE 1: CHOI HYUN-SUK

166
00:05:58,057 --> 00:06:01,094
-As expected, Choi Hyun-suk.
-You can't leave him out!

167
00:06:01,160 --> 00:06:03,229
A man who overcame his frozen shoulders,

168
00:06:03,296 --> 00:06:05,431
the salting guy of the show,
Chef Choi Hyun-suk.

169
00:06:05,498 --> 00:06:06,332
He's tough to beat.

170
00:06:07,200 --> 00:06:09,369
-The second nominee.
-Yes, that's right.

171
00:06:09,435 --> 00:06:11,804
-He gives the best vibes in the kitchen…
-The good vibe performance.

172
00:06:11,871 --> 00:06:14,073
-…the good vibes performer.
-Same towel, different moods.

173
00:06:14,140 --> 00:06:15,408
Chef Son Jong-won!

174
00:06:15,475 --> 00:06:17,176
NOMINEE 2: SON JONG-WON

175
00:06:17,243 --> 00:06:18,077
I love that.

176
00:06:18,144 --> 00:06:19,579
<i>Su-Su-Su-Super Udon</i>

177
00:06:19,645 --> 00:06:20,613
NOMINEE 3: JUNG HO-YOUNG

178
00:06:20,680 --> 00:06:23,850
Need I say more?
The show's official dancer,

179
00:06:23,916 --> 00:06:24,851
Chef Jung Ho-young!

180
00:06:26,519 --> 00:06:27,520
He worked super hard.

181
00:06:27,587 --> 00:06:28,621
They're all tough to beat.

182
00:06:28,688 --> 00:06:30,923
<i>Kim Poong, Strikeout!</i>

183
00:06:30,990 --> 00:06:32,825
-You can't beat this.
-She's tough to beat.

184
00:06:32,892 --> 00:06:35,895
A dark horse who'll strike Ho-young out,

185
00:06:35,962 --> 00:06:38,264
the queen of performing,
Chef Park Eun-yeong.

186
00:06:38,331 --> 00:06:40,133
This one played a huge part.

187
00:06:40,700 --> 00:06:41,901
A significant part.

188
00:06:41,968 --> 00:06:43,436
BEST PERFORMANCE AWARD

189
00:06:44,237 --> 00:06:45,071
-How intense.
-It's tough.

190
00:06:45,138 --> 00:06:46,272
Tough competition.

191
00:06:46,339 --> 00:06:47,273
-It is.
-They're all good.

192
00:06:47,340 --> 00:06:50,176
It looks like Chef Hyun-suk
is kind of hoping to win.

193
00:06:50,243 --> 00:06:51,077
Is he about to stand?

194
00:06:51,144 --> 00:06:54,247
-No.
-After all, he's our original performer.

195
00:06:54,313 --> 00:06:56,983
I should've started earlier
instead of winter.

196
00:06:57,049 --> 00:06:58,151
But you have an advantage this way.

197
00:06:58,217 --> 00:07:00,353
MY GOSH

198
00:07:00,420 --> 00:07:02,655
-It's you.
-Must be someone new.

199
00:07:02,722 --> 00:07:04,056
The 2026 <i>Chef & My Fridge </i>Awards.

200
00:07:04,123 --> 00:07:05,992
The winner of Best Performance Award is…

201
00:07:06,058 --> 00:07:06,893
The winner is?

202
00:07:06,959 --> 00:07:07,794
Me?

203
00:07:08,361 --> 00:07:10,129
Chef Hyun-suk did not make it!

204
00:07:10,196 --> 00:07:11,998
Chef Hyun-suk did not make it!

205
00:07:12,064 --> 00:07:12,999
WHOA

206
00:07:13,466 --> 00:07:14,934
WAIT, IS IT REALLY ME?

207
00:07:15,635 --> 00:07:16,502
-You're likely.
-Who is it?

208
00:07:16,569 --> 00:07:18,371
Chef Jung Ho-young!

209
00:07:18,438 --> 00:07:21,307
BEST PERFORMANCE AWARD:
JUNG HO-YOUNG

210
00:07:21,374 --> 00:07:23,109
-Jung Ho-young!
-Give him a standing ovation.

211
00:07:23,676 --> 00:07:25,478
EVERYONE STANDS

212
00:07:25,545 --> 00:07:26,479
Look.

213
00:07:26,546 --> 00:07:28,681
Why won't she get up? Look at her.

214
00:07:28,748 --> 00:07:29,749
She's mad.

215
00:07:30,583 --> 00:07:32,418
WON'T EVEN BUDGE

216
00:07:32,485 --> 00:07:35,822
I mean, how much more
do I have to dance to get that?

217
00:07:35,888 --> 00:07:37,957
-She's too mad to stand up.
-You can do more this year.

218
00:07:38,024 --> 00:07:38,925
PROMISE TO DO BETTER

219
00:07:38,991 --> 00:07:40,927
-Chef Ho-young.
-And you have an important prize.

220
00:07:40,993 --> 00:07:43,095
-It's a present from the fans.
-Really?

221
00:07:43,930 --> 00:07:45,398
It's a present from our fans.

222
00:07:45,465 --> 00:07:46,999
-Let's see it.
-What is it?

223
00:07:47,066 --> 00:07:48,301
Wow.

224
00:07:48,367 --> 00:07:50,036
-It's so cute.
-I see.

225
00:07:50,102 --> 00:07:51,471
<i>It's holding fritters.</i>

226
00:07:51,537 --> 00:07:53,473
<i>-And wearing an apron.</i>
<i>-Fried shrimps.</i>

227
00:07:53,539 --> 00:07:56,609
-This is supposed to be you.
-You're right.

228
00:07:56,676 --> 00:07:59,712
-They sent this because it looks like him.
-"Fry."

229
00:07:59,779 --> 00:08:01,881
THE CELEBRATION

230
00:08:02,715 --> 00:08:03,916
That's why he's the winner.

231
00:08:03,983 --> 00:08:05,651
That's why you won that award.

232
00:08:05,718 --> 00:08:07,787
-Let's give it to him.
-Acknowledged.

233
00:08:07,854 --> 00:08:09,288
I'll try to win next year.

234
00:08:09,355 --> 00:08:11,357
-And now, the Grand Award…
-This is it.

235
00:08:11,424 --> 00:08:14,760
-It's the main category.
-…the Best Dish Award awaits us.

236
00:08:14,827 --> 00:08:16,395
The Best Dish Award?

237
00:08:16,462 --> 00:08:17,296
Before we do that,

238
00:08:17,363 --> 00:08:19,165
let us announce…

239
00:08:19,232 --> 00:08:20,099
Huh?

240
00:08:20,166 --> 00:08:21,701
-…a few special awards.
-Like what?

241
00:08:21,767 --> 00:08:23,503
-There are special awards.
-Special awards?

242
00:08:23,569 --> 00:08:24,604
-That's right.
-What is it?

243
00:08:24,670 --> 00:08:25,805
-Korean pork?
-Special awards.

244
00:08:25,872 --> 00:08:26,706
COMING RIGHT UP

245
00:08:27,306 --> 00:08:30,142
-What?
-Wait, there's one for everyone!

246
00:08:30,209 --> 00:08:32,845
-There's one for everyone!
-Yes, we need the participation award.

247
00:08:32,912 --> 00:08:34,413
-The participation award.
-Special awards.

248
00:08:34,480 --> 00:08:37,850
-There's one for everyone.
-You all get one.

249
00:08:37,917 --> 00:08:39,118
It's like how they do it

250
00:08:39,185 --> 00:08:40,353
at a grade school competition.

251
00:08:40,920 --> 00:08:42,488
YOU GET AT LEAST
A PARTICIPATION AWARD

252
00:08:42,555 --> 00:08:43,789
Everyone gets one.

253
00:08:43,856 --> 00:08:45,558
First, an award for Hyun-suk.

254
00:08:45,625 --> 00:08:47,560
His award

255
00:08:47,627 --> 00:08:48,728
is called…

256
00:08:48,794 --> 00:08:50,630
DRUMROLL

257
00:08:50,696 --> 00:08:53,499
-…Compensation Award.
-What are you saying?

258
00:08:53,566 --> 00:08:54,567
Compensation Award?

259
00:08:54,634 --> 00:08:56,369
-Compensation Award?
-Compensation Award.

260
00:08:56,936 --> 00:08:59,372
COMPENSATION AWARD:
CHOI HYUN-SUK

261
00:08:59,438 --> 00:09:00,273
That's fascinating.

262
00:09:00,339 --> 00:09:02,508
-Come forward for the Compensation Award.
-Come forward.

263
00:09:02,575 --> 00:09:04,777
Will you pull your hands
out of your pockets?

264
00:09:04,844 --> 00:09:05,745
AFTER SEEING THIS?

265
00:09:06,245 --> 00:09:09,348
THIS IS A CLASSY AWARDS SHOW

266
00:09:09,415 --> 00:09:11,250
-Come on.
-Congratulations.

267
00:09:11,317 --> 00:09:12,919
What do you mean, Compensation Award?

268
00:09:12,985 --> 00:09:14,954
Goodness gracious.

269
00:09:15,488 --> 00:09:18,057
-Let us explain.
-Compensation Award.

270
00:09:18,124 --> 00:09:20,026
Whenever Chef Hyun-suk cooked,

271
00:09:20,092 --> 00:09:24,130
he terrorized many other chefs
by bombarding them with salt,

272
00:09:24,196 --> 00:09:27,600
-so many of them demanded compensation.
-I gathered a handful.

273
00:09:27,667 --> 00:09:28,868
We demand compensation.

274
00:09:28,935 --> 00:09:32,405
We ask you to stay with us for a long time
and continue to make great dishes

275
00:09:32,471 --> 00:09:34,707
as a way to compensate for the damage…

276
00:09:34,774 --> 00:09:36,275
-It was meaningful.
-…as we award you.

277
00:09:36,342 --> 00:09:38,511
Please share a few words.

278
00:09:38,578 --> 00:09:40,079
CHOI HYUN-SUK'S
ACCEPTANCE SPEECH

279
00:09:40,146 --> 00:09:44,216
I've worked my fingers to the bone
for the sake of <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>

280
00:09:44,283 --> 00:09:46,719
and you give me an award like this?
Thanks, I guess.

281
00:09:46,786 --> 00:09:49,055
-I'd like to leave you with one thing.
-Yes?

282
00:09:49,121 --> 00:09:50,890
Do you all think you'll never age?

283
00:09:51,390 --> 00:09:53,426
HE'LL CONTINUE TO MISS THE POT
WITH SALT

284
00:09:53,492 --> 00:09:55,595
Next, an award for Chef Eun-yeong.

285
00:09:55,661 --> 00:09:57,396
She already looks so happy.

286
00:09:58,998 --> 00:10:00,866
-A huge smile.
-Yes.

287
00:10:00,933 --> 00:10:02,468
-You're so transparent.
-Which award

288
00:10:02,535 --> 00:10:04,770
will Chef Eun-yeong receive?

289
00:10:04,837 --> 00:10:06,272
It's Personal Award.

290
00:10:06,339 --> 00:10:09,642
-Personal Award.
-Personal Award?

291
00:10:09,709 --> 00:10:10,910
I didn't expect this.

292
00:10:10,977 --> 00:10:13,412
-I thought it'd be Maniac Award.
-You've created

293
00:10:13,479 --> 00:10:15,915
<i>the best buzzword of the show,</i>
<i>"a personal creation."</i>

294
00:10:16,482 --> 00:10:20,319
You have risen high
as a successful maniac on this show,

295
00:10:20,386 --> 00:10:22,622
so we hereby present you with this award.

296
00:10:22,688 --> 00:10:23,522
She's a big shot now.

297
00:10:23,589 --> 00:10:25,424
The 2026 Chef & My Fridge Awards,
Special Awards.

298
00:10:25,491 --> 00:10:26,826
For Webtoon Artist Poong,

299
00:10:26,892 --> 00:10:30,162
Bizarre Dish Award.

300
00:10:30,229 --> 00:10:31,964
Next, an award for Chef Sam,

301
00:10:32,031 --> 00:10:33,866
Someone's So Nice Award.

302
00:10:33,933 --> 00:10:35,635
Congratulations. And the fan's present.

303
00:10:35,701 --> 00:10:38,337
-Someone's So Nice Award.
-Thank you. Goodness.

304
00:10:38,404 --> 00:10:39,338
SOMEONE'S SO NICE AWARD

305
00:10:39,405 --> 00:10:40,973
An award for Chef Nam-no,

306
00:10:41,040 --> 00:10:43,809
-Extreme Job Satisfaction Award.
-Congratulations.

307
00:10:43,876 --> 00:10:46,379
EXTREME JOB SATISFACTION AWARD:
YOON NAM-NO

308
00:10:46,445 --> 00:10:48,547
The 2026 Chef & My Fridge Awards,
Special Awards.

309
00:10:48,614 --> 00:10:50,750
-This is for Chef Jong-won.
-What is it?

310
00:10:50,816 --> 00:10:51,851
-What is it?
-It's called

311
00:10:51,917 --> 00:10:53,152
the Peddler Award.

312
00:10:53,219 --> 00:10:54,954
-The Peddler Award?
-The Peddler Award.

313
00:10:55,021 --> 00:10:57,456
-Peddler Award.
-He always brings lots of stuff.

314
00:10:57,523 --> 00:10:59,759
-He always has lots of luggage.
-He carries a huge bag.

315
00:10:59,825 --> 00:11:03,462
Chef Jong-won always brings
all kinds of cooking equipment

316
00:11:03,529 --> 00:11:07,767
on his way to the shoot
to make the show better,

317
00:11:07,833 --> 00:11:10,569
and was even called
the domestic uncle buyer.

318
00:11:11,137 --> 00:11:14,974
He is hereby awarded
for bringing up the quality

319
00:11:15,041 --> 00:11:16,475
of the dishes on this show.

320
00:11:17,043 --> 00:11:18,944
I'll continue to bring lots of stuff.

321
00:11:20,613 --> 00:11:23,215
And now, the last special award.

322
00:11:23,282 --> 00:11:25,751
-It's for Chef Sung-jun.
-What is it?

323
00:11:25,818 --> 00:11:26,686
The Slyness Award.

324
00:11:26,752 --> 00:11:28,621
-Emergency Award.
-What's his special award?

325
00:11:28,688 --> 00:11:30,056
-It's Emergency Award.
-The award is…

326
00:11:30,122 --> 00:11:31,390
It's Emergency Award.

327
00:11:31,457 --> 00:11:32,558
…Emergency Award!

328
00:11:32,625 --> 00:11:34,727
JUST AS EVERYONE EXPECTED

329
00:11:34,794 --> 00:11:35,695
It's an emergency.

330
00:11:35,761 --> 00:11:38,931
It'll be an emergency
for us to do the show without him.

331
00:11:38,998 --> 00:11:40,533
-Congratulations.
-"It's an emergency."

332
00:11:40,599 --> 00:11:44,570
For the last year,
I had to do my best to survive

333
00:11:44,637 --> 00:11:47,707
through studying and creating
many different characters.

334
00:11:47,773 --> 00:11:49,375
Why would a chef study characters?

335
00:11:49,442 --> 00:11:51,310
But everyone, it's an emergency.

336
00:11:51,377 --> 00:11:54,113
Currently, <i>Culinary Class Wars 2</i> is out,

337
00:11:54,180 --> 00:11:56,082
and many people are after our spots.

338
00:11:56,148 --> 00:11:59,919
That's your concern, not all of us.

339
00:11:59,985 --> 00:12:01,253
He's the most anxious.

340
00:12:01,320 --> 00:12:02,621
-It's an emergency.
-Of losing his job?

341
00:12:02,688 --> 00:12:07,159
Let us do our best
to keep our position here on the show.

342
00:12:07,727 --> 00:12:10,596
-You get another prize.
-All right. Yes, he gets a present.

343
00:12:10,663 --> 00:12:12,531
He gets another present
with Emergency Award.

344
00:12:12,598 --> 00:12:13,799
What is it?

345
00:12:13,866 --> 00:12:14,700
A siren light?

346
00:12:14,767 --> 00:12:16,535
What is it? I see.

347
00:12:16,602 --> 00:12:18,571
-It's an emergency.
-It's a beacon light.

348
00:12:20,673 --> 00:12:22,708
-Put it on your head.
-Like this?

349
00:12:22,775 --> 00:12:25,811
-And turn it on.
-You get a beacon light as a present.

350
00:12:25,878 --> 00:12:28,781
And now, the final award of the day,

351
00:12:28,848 --> 00:12:31,150
it's the Grand Award
of the 2026 <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Awards.

352
00:12:31,717 --> 00:12:33,385
It's the winner of the Best Dish Award.

353
00:12:33,452 --> 00:12:35,187
Right, we had this one.

354
00:12:35,254 --> 00:12:37,022
-This is the real deal.
-Yes.

355
00:12:37,089 --> 00:12:41,861
It's even more meaningful
because you voted for this yourselves.

356
00:12:41,927 --> 00:12:43,829
We received votes from you.

357
00:12:43,896 --> 00:12:46,265
Now, here are the nominees
for the Best Dish Award.

358
00:12:49,168 --> 00:12:50,536
-There's mine.
-Choi-mpion.

359
00:12:50,603 --> 00:12:51,570
The first nominee

360
00:12:52,138 --> 00:12:55,374
<i>is the very dish that made Hyun-suk</i>
<i>the champion of the 2025 season,</i>

361
00:12:55,441 --> 00:12:57,810
abalone Wellington, Choi-mpion.

362
00:12:58,544 --> 00:13:02,248
The second nominee captured
Ryu Hyun-jin's appetite and Kim Poong.

363
00:13:02,314 --> 00:13:04,550
Kim Poong, Strikeout by Park Eun-yeong.

364
00:13:04,617 --> 00:13:05,451
NOMINEE 2: PARK EUN-YEONG

365
00:13:05,518 --> 00:13:09,688
<i>The third nominee is the dish that opened</i>
<i>the second glory days of the show,</i>

366
00:13:09,755 --> 00:13:12,191
<i>Kim Poong's dung loach.</i>

367
00:13:12,258 --> 00:13:13,826
That was good, though.

368
00:13:14,293 --> 00:13:17,263
NOMINEE 3: C-C-C-C-C-C-C-CRAZY
SOUP BY KIM POONG

369
00:13:17,329 --> 00:13:19,965
-It isn't actually called Dung Loach.
-No, it isn't.

370
00:13:20,032 --> 00:13:21,233
People are mistaken.

371
00:13:21,300 --> 00:13:23,769
Everyone thinks it's called Dung Loach,
but that's not the name.

372
00:13:23,836 --> 00:13:24,804
The fourth nominee

373
00:13:24,870 --> 00:13:27,640
<i>comes in with the flashy cuts</i>
<i>on a bigfin reef squid.</i>

374
00:13:27,706 --> 00:13:29,175
FLASHY CUTS
ON A BIGFIN REEF SQUID!

375
00:13:30,075 --> 00:13:33,546
NOMINEE 4: MR. CHOO, SHOT OF
SOJU, CHOO BY JUNG HO-YOUNG

376
00:13:33,612 --> 00:13:35,114
-Shall we announce the winner?
-Okay.

377
00:13:35,781 --> 00:13:37,583
The 2026 <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Awards.

378
00:13:37,650 --> 00:13:40,119
<i>This is the Best Dish Award</i>
<i>as voted by the chefs.</i>

379
00:13:40,186 --> 00:13:42,688
<i>The honor goes to…</i>

380
00:13:43,255 --> 00:13:44,857
DRUMROLL

381
00:13:44,924 --> 00:13:45,791
Tensions are high.

382
00:13:45,858 --> 00:13:48,694
-You cast your votes for this award.
-Who will it be?

383
00:13:49,695 --> 00:13:52,264
SOMEONE UNEXPECTED?

384
00:13:52,331 --> 00:13:53,799
It must be the dung loach.

385
00:13:53,866 --> 00:13:54,867
ME?

386
00:13:54,934 --> 00:13:56,869
-This is unexpected.
-Who is it?

387
00:13:56,936 --> 00:13:58,704
-I think I know who.
-Who is it?

388
00:13:58,771 --> 00:14:00,639
Chefs.

389
00:14:00,706 --> 00:14:03,309
The winner of the Best Dish Award is…

390
00:14:03,375 --> 00:14:05,077
-It's…
-It's…

391
00:14:05,644 --> 00:14:08,314
It's Chef Choi Hyun-suk's Choi-mpion!

392
00:14:08,380 --> 00:14:11,083
It's Chef Choi Hyun-suk's Choi-mpion!

393
00:14:11,150 --> 00:14:12,284
TRYING NOT TO SMILE…

394
00:14:12,618 --> 00:14:14,653
"A DISH THAT CHALLENGED
THE LIMITS" - SON JONG-WON

395
00:14:14,987 --> 00:14:17,223
"WORTHY OF THE FINALS! I GET
WHY I LOST" - PARK EUN-YEONG

396
00:14:17,556 --> 00:14:19,491
"I THOUGHT IT'D BE IMPOSSIBLE
IN 15 MINUTES" - JUNG HO-YOUNG

397
00:14:19,758 --> 00:14:20,759
"SHOWED THE CLASS OF 1ST PLACE

398
00:14:20,826 --> 00:14:22,461
AND WRAPPED THE YEAR
WITH A WELLINGTON"

399
00:14:22,528 --> 00:14:23,662
Congratulations.

400
00:14:23,729 --> 00:14:26,298
He didn't seem too happy
when he got the Compensation Award.

401
00:14:26,799 --> 00:14:29,301
THE GRANDPA
LOST ALL HIS WRINKLES

402
00:14:29,869 --> 00:14:31,303
A CLEAR DIFFERENCE

403
00:14:31,370 --> 00:14:33,005
He's smiling now.

404
00:14:33,072 --> 00:14:35,541
He's so easy to read.

405
00:14:35,608 --> 00:14:37,176
Please share your speech.

406
00:14:37,243 --> 00:14:38,210
WHAT WILL HE SAY?

407
00:14:38,978 --> 00:14:41,614
CHOKING UP…

408
00:14:41,680 --> 00:14:43,048
I understand the tears.

409
00:14:43,115 --> 00:14:44,950
-He's choking up.
-Of course.

410
00:14:45,017 --> 00:14:46,352
-Everyone.
-He almost cried.

411
00:14:46,418 --> 00:14:48,354
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>

412
00:14:48,420 --> 00:14:51,190
is a fun variety show and all.

413
00:14:51,257 --> 00:14:52,291
But fundamentally,

414
00:14:52,358 --> 00:14:53,592
this is a cooking program.

415
00:14:53,659 --> 00:14:54,760
IMPRESSED

416
00:14:54,827 --> 00:14:57,363
So instead of coveting after stars,
let's get cooking.

417
00:14:58,063 --> 00:14:59,565
FINISHING HIS SPEECH
BY REPRIMANDING

418
00:14:59,632 --> 00:15:01,000
-He reprimanded everyone.
-Rebuked.

419
00:15:01,066 --> 00:15:03,335
BOO

420
00:15:03,402 --> 00:15:05,738
You were supposed to be funny.
What are you saying?

421
00:15:06,305 --> 00:15:07,706
PLEASE CONTINUE
TO BE SALTY AND FUNNY

422
00:15:07,773 --> 00:15:09,675
-Congratulations.
-Congratulations.

423
00:15:10,175 --> 00:15:11,243
THE AWARDS WERE A SUCCESS

424
00:15:11,310 --> 00:15:15,514
We gave out plushies
along with the plaques, right?

425
00:15:15,581 --> 00:15:17,483
However, we have one more here.

426
00:15:17,549 --> 00:15:19,418
-There's more?
-There's one more.

427
00:15:19,485 --> 00:15:20,920
-It's an emergency.
-Let's see it

428
00:15:20,986 --> 00:15:22,655
-and figure out who it is.
-What emergency?

429
00:15:22,721 --> 00:15:25,324
The fan asked us to relay this to him.

430
00:15:27,326 --> 00:15:29,228
-It's Kang-rok.
-Yes, it's him.

431
00:15:29,295 --> 00:15:32,097
-Anyone can tell.
-"You must keep braising."

432
00:15:32,164 --> 00:15:33,265
"And!"

433
00:15:33,332 --> 00:15:35,801
-He left the show to write a book, but…
-He wrote history.

434
00:15:35,868 --> 00:15:37,336
Yes, we found out much later.

435
00:15:37,403 --> 00:15:40,039
-He won <i>Culinary Class Wars 2.</i>
-He's the winner.

436
00:15:40,105 --> 00:15:42,174
Come back, Kang-rok.

437
00:15:42,241 --> 00:15:43,442
I personally wish to see

438
00:15:43,509 --> 00:15:46,445
a round between the two winners
of <i>Culinary Class Wars 1 </i>and <i>2</i>.

439
00:15:46,512 --> 00:15:48,147
I want to see that too.

440
00:15:48,213 --> 00:15:50,916
Actually, we've already fought twice.

441
00:15:50,983 --> 00:15:53,352
I won the convenience store mission
in the first season,

442
00:15:53,919 --> 00:15:56,055
and I won once here on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

443
00:15:56,121 --> 00:15:58,657
Would he think
it would be a shame to leave it at that?

444
00:15:59,224 --> 00:16:02,127
IT SOUNDS LIKE
HE WANTS TO LEAVE IT THIS WAY

445
00:16:02,194 --> 00:16:05,531
<i>Chef Kang-rok, you should visit the show</i>
<i>and pick up this plushie.</i>

446
00:16:05,597 --> 00:16:07,900
<i>We'll be waiting.</i>

447
00:16:07,967 --> 00:16:11,370
And now, let me present
today's fridge owners.

448
00:16:11,437 --> 00:16:14,673
Since today is our chefs' party,
we have very special guests

449
00:16:14,740 --> 00:16:18,844
-waiting for us back there.
-Who are they?

450
00:16:18,911 --> 00:16:21,747
Please welcome today's fridge owners!

451
00:16:21,814 --> 00:16:22,915
Seriously?

452
00:16:23,482 --> 00:16:24,483
Who are they?

453
00:16:25,417 --> 00:16:27,119
-Come on!
-What?

454
00:16:27,186 --> 00:16:28,020
IT'S US

455
00:16:28,520 --> 00:16:30,856
A COOL POSE

456
00:16:30,923 --> 00:16:32,257
SEEING MY COLLEAGUES AS GUESTS

457
00:16:32,324 --> 00:16:33,592
The winners of the Best Couple Award,

458
00:16:33,659 --> 00:16:36,695
Chef Son Jong-won
and Webtoon Artist Kim Poong!

459
00:16:37,196 --> 00:16:39,031
LOOKING GREAT, SON-POONG

460
00:16:39,098 --> 00:16:40,699
Hey, look. Celebrities.

461
00:16:40,766 --> 00:16:42,968
Please come and say hello to our viewers.

462
00:16:43,035 --> 00:16:44,236
-They're like celebrities.
-Yes.

463
00:16:44,303 --> 00:16:45,871
He's a famous webtoon artist.

464
00:16:45,938 --> 00:16:47,573
I always wanted to be here

465
00:16:47,639 --> 00:16:50,642
as a guest for <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>

466
00:16:50,709 --> 00:16:52,544
-Please sit before you continue.
-Should I?

467
00:16:52,611 --> 00:16:54,313
We must treat you as a guest.

468
00:16:54,380 --> 00:16:57,049
After all, you are one.
Let me get your chair.

469
00:16:57,116 --> 00:16:58,884
May I shake your hands?

470
00:16:58,951 --> 00:17:00,452
Nice to meet you.

471
00:17:00,519 --> 00:17:03,088
-I enjoyed your show.
-Nice to meet you. Thank you.

472
00:17:03,155 --> 00:17:04,490
-I've heard a lot about you.
-Hello.

473
00:17:04,556 --> 00:17:06,625
It feels like I'm meeting celebrities.

474
00:17:06,692 --> 00:17:08,060
-He is a celebrity.
-You're all celebrities.

475
00:17:08,127 --> 00:17:10,062
-Are you nervous?
-I am. I'm really nervous.

476
00:17:10,129 --> 00:17:11,697
You were with us just a while ago.

477
00:17:12,831 --> 00:17:14,600
We all had <i>gimbap</i> together back there.

478
00:17:15,167 --> 00:17:17,269
Can you stop me?

479
00:17:17,336 --> 00:17:20,272
A man who becomes a big issue
every moment he breathes.

480
00:17:20,339 --> 00:17:22,307
-I'm jealous.
-The epitome of good vibes

481
00:17:22,374 --> 00:17:24,109
birthed and raised by <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,

482
00:17:24,176 --> 00:17:27,346
A double Michelin-star chef, Son Jong-won!

483
00:17:28,247 --> 00:17:30,149
Hello, I'm Son Jong-won,

484
00:17:30,215 --> 00:17:32,484
a chef raised by <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>…

485
00:17:32,551 --> 00:17:34,086
-So you agree.
-He's nervous.

486
00:17:34,153 --> 00:17:35,854
-Let me introduce this man.
-Sure.

487
00:17:35,921 --> 00:17:37,523
It feels weird.

488
00:17:37,589 --> 00:17:40,526
This man also became
the hottest potato along with Jong-won.

489
00:17:40,592 --> 00:17:43,362
The epitome of bootleg cooking
birthed by <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>

490
00:17:43,429 --> 00:17:45,497
Cook of the Darkness,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong!

491
00:17:45,564 --> 00:17:47,766
Cook of the Darkness!

492
00:17:47,833 --> 00:17:48,967
HERE AS A FRIDGE OWNER!

493
00:17:49,034 --> 00:17:51,703
We had neglected him all along,
yet he turned out so well.

494
00:17:51,770 --> 00:17:53,839
We birthed him, let him graze,

495
00:17:53,906 --> 00:17:57,443
so he nibbled on the weeds to survive
and got to where he is now.

496
00:17:57,509 --> 00:17:59,611
-We just left him here.
-He's like Tarzan.

497
00:17:59,678 --> 00:18:00,579
I'm proud of him.

498
00:18:00,646 --> 00:18:04,750
We've been receiving so much love
from our viewers lately,

499
00:18:04,817 --> 00:18:07,986
and of our entire cast,
these two are the most buzzworthy people.

500
00:18:08,053 --> 00:18:12,424
<i>There's a heightened interest</i>
<i>in these two.</i>

501
00:18:12,491 --> 00:18:14,093
You've only been here as a chef,

502
00:18:14,159 --> 00:18:15,894
but you're now a guest.
How does that feel?

503
00:18:15,961 --> 00:18:19,064
I remembered something
as I stood behind the screens.

504
00:18:19,131 --> 00:18:21,166
I stood there
for the first time a year ago.

505
00:18:22,134 --> 00:18:23,102
HE FIRST CAME A YEAR AGO

506
00:18:23,168 --> 00:18:24,436
Son Jong-won!

507
00:18:24,503 --> 00:18:26,672
-Chef Son Jong-won.
-It's great to have you.

508
00:18:26,738 --> 00:18:28,807
-You were presented as the new chef.
-That's right.

509
00:18:28,874 --> 00:18:31,677
-A year later, we're like family now<i>…</i>
-It's already been a year?

510
00:18:31,743 --> 00:18:33,545
-<i>…</i>so I'm grateful for that.
-I see.

511
00:18:33,612 --> 00:18:35,481
Do you plan to wear your prize?

512
00:18:35,547 --> 00:18:37,583
-I will wear it.
-Really?

513
00:18:37,649 --> 00:18:39,852
I'm curious to find out
what other people will say.

514
00:18:39,918 --> 00:18:41,553
THE MOST BUZZWORTHY MAN
IS CURIOUS

515
00:18:41,620 --> 00:18:43,355
He has changed since his first appearance.

516
00:18:43,422 --> 00:18:46,125
At first, he was shy and reserved.

517
00:18:46,191 --> 00:18:48,760
-I had shaky hands too.
-Yes.

518
00:18:48,827 --> 00:18:50,796
But now, what I'm concerned more about

519
00:18:50,863 --> 00:18:51,964
being funny.

520
00:18:53,132 --> 00:18:55,267
-Listen to this guy.
-This is bad.

521
00:18:55,334 --> 00:18:58,270
-He's getting ambitious.
-He's addicted to the variety show life.

522
00:18:58,337 --> 00:19:00,572
It's not that.
I want to let people enjoy the show.

523
00:19:00,639 --> 00:19:03,408
There aren't many programs
you can enjoy with your entire family.

524
00:19:03,475 --> 00:19:04,510
That's true.

525
00:19:04,576 --> 00:19:07,913
But this is something grade school kids
and their parents can watch together.

526
00:19:07,980 --> 00:19:09,148
HOPING TO MAKE MANY LAUGH

527
00:19:09,214 --> 00:19:11,583
The thing is, Chef Jong-won

528
00:19:11,650 --> 00:19:14,853
had been attending
a good university in America,

529
00:19:15,420 --> 00:19:19,158
-but he suddenly quit to start cooking.
-That's right.

530
00:19:19,224 --> 00:19:22,060
-He studied engineering.
-Yes, I did.

531
00:19:22,127 --> 00:19:24,696
So? Are your parents happy these days?

532
00:19:24,763 --> 00:19:26,899
I'm so grateful for the show

533
00:19:26,965 --> 00:19:30,202
because they didn't really care
even when I got the Michelin stars,

534
00:19:30,269 --> 00:19:33,105
-yet one appearance on TV did it for them.
-Not even the stars?

535
00:19:33,172 --> 00:19:35,073
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> is the best
for the parents!

536
00:19:35,140 --> 00:19:36,642
For them, a TV appearance is the best.

537
00:19:36,708 --> 00:19:39,511
Showing yourself on the telly
is the best you can do!

538
00:19:39,578 --> 00:19:42,314
They kept getting calls from friends
and had to treat them to meals.

539
00:19:42,381 --> 00:19:44,183
-Of course.
-They were thrilled.

540
00:19:44,249 --> 00:19:45,250
It makes our parents happy.

541
00:19:45,317 --> 00:19:47,386
Do you live with your parents?

542
00:19:47,452 --> 00:19:48,921
I live alone.

543
00:19:48,987 --> 00:19:52,791
What does the chef who has
double Michelin stars keep in his fridge?

544
00:19:52,858 --> 00:19:55,861
-I'm curious to see a chef's fridge.
-I'm curious.

545
00:19:55,928 --> 00:19:57,095
What does he eat?

546
00:19:57,162 --> 00:19:58,397
-Right?
-What does he keep?

547
00:19:58,463 --> 00:19:59,765
-What kind of ingredients?
-Yes.

548
00:19:59,831 --> 00:20:00,999
-I'm curious too.
-Right?

549
00:20:01,066 --> 00:20:04,036
And now, for the first time in the world
and on <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>

550
00:20:04,102 --> 00:20:07,172
we will open up
and present Chef Jong-won's fridge.

551
00:20:07,239 --> 00:20:09,041
Before we open it up,

552
00:20:09,107 --> 00:20:11,610
I see some letters here.

553
00:20:11,677 --> 00:20:13,845
-It's from Eun-bi.
-Yes, Eun-bi.

554
00:20:13,912 --> 00:20:16,415
"I am Kim Eun-bi, a second-grader."

555
00:20:16,481 --> 00:20:20,285
"I thought you were a chef
from <i>Culinary Class Wars 1.</i>"

556
00:20:20,352 --> 00:20:23,155
"But you weren't,
and you were in the second one."

557
00:20:24,389 --> 00:20:27,192
-"It's okay to lose."
-How cute.

558
00:20:27,259 --> 00:20:29,127
"You lost much later than Sam Kim."

559
00:20:29,995 --> 00:20:32,231
-Why is she bringing me up?
-On <i>Culinary Class Wars.</i>

560
00:20:32,297 --> 00:20:35,033
"Instead, keep coming
to <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>"

561
00:20:35,100 --> 00:20:37,402
-That's so cute.
-"Also, please tell Chef Choi

562
00:20:37,469 --> 00:20:38,670
that he talks too much."

563
00:20:40,672 --> 00:20:41,974
GRATIFYING

564
00:20:42,040 --> 00:20:43,909
That young girl is right on.

565
00:20:44,509 --> 00:20:47,412
-Elementary school kids can't lie.
-Yes, she had to complain.

566
00:20:47,479 --> 00:20:49,748
It's not me. It's Chef Kang-rok.

567
00:20:49,815 --> 00:20:51,250
-Come on.
-Come on.

568
00:20:51,316 --> 00:20:53,185
-He never talks.
-He doesn't talk.

569
00:20:53,252 --> 00:20:55,153
Kang-rok never says anything.

570
00:20:55,220 --> 00:20:56,788
-I'll try to talk less.
-Wait a minute.

571
00:20:56,855 --> 00:20:58,624
Who's this? Actor Kim Bo-sung?

572
00:20:59,291 --> 00:21:00,826
-Kim Bo-sung?
-It's Poong!

573
00:21:00,892 --> 00:21:02,427
Why is he here?

574
00:21:02,494 --> 00:21:03,962
-That's…
-Wasn't it on his social media?

575
00:21:04,029 --> 00:21:05,264
-That's it.
-Reggaeman?

576
00:21:05,330 --> 00:21:07,733
It was from a customer who came to dine,

577
00:21:07,799 --> 00:21:09,835
but I don't understand
why they gave it to me.

578
00:21:10,702 --> 00:21:13,005
That one's actually not easy to get.

579
00:21:13,071 --> 00:21:14,840
-It's a rare one.
-It is.

580
00:21:14,906 --> 00:21:17,509
So I left it up there like a charm
to ward off bad luck.

581
00:21:17,576 --> 00:21:18,710
When you get stressed out,

582
00:21:18,777 --> 00:21:20,012
use it as a dart board.

583
00:21:20,078 --> 00:21:21,146
SAME CARD, DIFFERENT USE

584
00:21:21,213 --> 00:21:22,581
"Jong-won's 400th time."

585
00:21:22,648 --> 00:21:25,784
"You never forget to come and work out
despite your busy schedule, Jong-won."

586
00:21:25,851 --> 00:21:27,619
-"Congratulations on your 400th time."
-From a trainer?

587
00:21:27,686 --> 00:21:29,588
Does this mean
you worked out there 400 times?

588
00:21:29,655 --> 00:21:31,623
There's this workout I do in the morning,

589
00:21:31,690 --> 00:21:35,627
<i>and they give me a T-shirt to celebrate</i>
<i>every 100th time,</i>

590
00:21:35,694 --> 00:21:38,864
-as well as trial vouchers for my friends.
-Vouchers.

591
00:21:38,930 --> 00:21:41,900
I hope the chefs will start working out,
so I'll give it to today's winners.

592
00:21:41,967 --> 00:21:42,868
The vouchers?

593
00:21:42,934 --> 00:21:45,937
This means you went and worked out
all 400 times without skipping a day.

594
00:21:46,004 --> 00:21:48,006
-That's amazing.
-That's incredible.

595
00:21:48,073 --> 00:21:48,974
Four hundred times?

596
00:21:49,041 --> 00:21:52,311
-I haven't exercised 400 times in my life.
-I can eat that often, but not that.

597
00:21:52,377 --> 00:21:56,214
So what does the chef who has
double Michelin stars keep in his fridge?

598
00:21:56,281 --> 00:21:58,984
-We present Jong-won's fridge!
-Fridge!

599
00:21:59,051 --> 00:22:00,118
-Fridge!
-Fridge!

600
00:22:00,819 --> 00:22:01,720
What?

601
00:22:01,787 --> 00:22:03,588
-Come on.
-Wait, what?

602
00:22:03,655 --> 00:22:04,756
-Fridge!
-Fridge!

603
00:22:04,823 --> 00:22:06,425
PRESENTING JONG-WON'S FRIDGE

604
00:22:08,260 --> 00:22:09,795
Why do you have more water than food?

605
00:22:09,861 --> 00:22:11,863
-All he has is water.
-What is this?

606
00:22:11,930 --> 00:22:13,432
There's not enough stuff.

607
00:22:13,498 --> 00:22:15,367
He seems to be obsessed with organizing.

608
00:22:15,434 --> 00:22:17,636
It doesn't portray him as human.

609
00:22:17,703 --> 00:22:18,637
That fridge is beyond hope.

610
00:22:18,704 --> 00:22:21,340
-He lined these up like a machine.
-It's making me tired.

611
00:22:21,406 --> 00:22:23,208
Wait a second.

612
00:22:23,275 --> 00:22:24,710
It's another fridge to whip us.

613
00:22:24,776 --> 00:22:26,945
Well, the top two shelves,

614
00:22:27,012 --> 00:22:30,282
-these shelves are both filled with water.
-It's just water.

615
00:22:30,349 --> 00:22:31,383
-Man.
-Right?

616
00:22:31,450 --> 00:22:32,651
-Do you need this much?
-No way.

617
00:22:32,718 --> 00:22:34,386
They're different types of water.

618
00:22:34,453 --> 00:22:36,655
I drink carbonated water
when I want something spicy.

619
00:22:36,722 --> 00:22:38,090
-What?
-But usually, regular water.

620
00:22:38,156 --> 00:22:39,791
-Isn't chili spicy?
-Spicy?

621
00:22:39,858 --> 00:22:41,326
<i>Malatang</i> soup is what's spicy.

622
00:22:41,393 --> 00:22:43,662
And I choose different temperatures
depending on my mood.

623
00:22:43,729 --> 00:22:45,430
What's spicy to us is <i>yukgaejang</i>, right?

624
00:22:45,497 --> 00:22:47,499
-Like <i>Malatang </i>soup.
-<i>Malatang.</i>

625
00:22:47,566 --> 00:22:49,735
-Do you drink lots of water?
-Yes, about 4 to 5 L.

626
00:22:49,801 --> 00:22:51,703
-What?
-Between 4 to 5 L?

627
00:22:51,770 --> 00:22:54,239
-Let's look at the next one.
-These are tightly aligned.

628
00:22:54,306 --> 00:22:55,540
Right?

629
00:22:55,607 --> 00:22:58,944
I see different soy milk here
standing in perfect lines.

630
00:22:59,010 --> 00:23:01,913
There's a protein shake I can eat
just by mixing soy milk, so I do that.

631
00:23:01,980 --> 00:23:04,649
When I crave something sweet,
I drink the one on the left.

632
00:23:04,716 --> 00:23:05,917
-This?
-The protein drink?

633
00:23:05,984 --> 00:23:08,253
-The protein drink?
-It comes in different flavors.

634
00:23:08,320 --> 00:23:11,390
He drinks a flavored protein drink
when he craves something sweet.

635
00:23:11,957 --> 00:23:12,958
He's losing his human touch.

636
00:23:13,024 --> 00:23:15,160
It's like a kitchen
with everything lined up.

637
00:23:15,727 --> 00:23:17,329
PERFECTLY ALIGNED

638
00:23:17,396 --> 00:23:19,264
-January 15th, 16th.
-Look at the labels.

639
00:23:19,331 --> 00:23:21,533
-January 17th.
-They're kitchen labels.

640
00:23:21,600 --> 00:23:23,969
Why do you label your food?

641
00:23:24,035 --> 00:23:26,304
I have to use what I bought earlier first.

642
00:23:26,371 --> 00:23:28,306
-That's amazing.
-That green tape<i>…</i>

643
00:23:28,373 --> 00:23:30,609
-Yes.
-<i>…</i>is something often used in the kitchen.

644
00:23:30,675 --> 00:23:31,777
-This one.
-Really?

645
00:23:31,843 --> 00:23:33,645
I've used it for over a decade,

646
00:23:33,712 --> 00:23:36,515
so I feel more at ease
when I see those labels.

647
00:23:36,581 --> 00:23:37,883
FEELING UNEASY HERE

648
00:23:37,949 --> 00:23:39,918
Do all chefs do this at home?

649
00:23:39,985 --> 00:23:41,720
I've never seen it.

650
00:23:42,721 --> 00:23:44,122
I've never seen that tape, period.

651
00:23:44,189 --> 00:23:46,024
He hasn't seen this tape before.

652
00:23:46,091 --> 00:23:48,126
Chef Ho-young
doesn't need to label anything.

653
00:23:48,193 --> 00:23:49,461
He eats everything anyway.

654
00:23:49,528 --> 00:23:50,929
The turnover is quick.

655
00:23:50,996 --> 00:23:53,532
-Take a look.
-Tofu and meat.

656
00:23:53,598 --> 00:23:55,400
-What's this?
-Tofu and meat?

657
00:23:55,467 --> 00:23:58,670
-I boil water and blanch broccoli.
-Okay.

658
00:23:58,737 --> 00:24:00,772
In that same water,
I add a drop of soy sauce

659
00:24:00,839 --> 00:24:03,041
and lightly cook some thinly sliced meat.

660
00:24:03,108 --> 00:24:06,211
After that, I add tofu
and that's my go-to meal.

661
00:24:06,278 --> 00:24:07,946
What is this? A snack or a meal?

662
00:24:08,013 --> 00:24:08,880
It's a meal substitute.

663
00:24:08,947 --> 00:24:10,749
-A meal?
-I usually eat that

664
00:24:10,816 --> 00:24:13,285
-with some veggies.
-That's what he packs to the studio.

665
00:24:13,351 --> 00:24:15,854
-That's the kind of snack he brings.
-He brings it?

666
00:24:15,921 --> 00:24:18,857
-He brings containers of fruit and bread.
-Like this?

667
00:24:18,924 --> 00:24:21,293
-Look. That's how everything is.
-Pull everything out.

668
00:24:21,359 --> 00:24:24,229
-Look at this. Bell peppers.
-Bell peppers.

669
00:24:24,296 --> 00:24:25,831
-What's that?
-Apple.

670
00:24:25,897 --> 00:24:27,532
-And this is one?
-Veggies.

671
00:24:27,599 --> 00:24:29,334
Is that cabbage?

672
00:24:29,401 --> 00:24:31,436
-You and I are doomed.
-Cucumber.

673
00:24:31,503 --> 00:24:32,604
I don't want to eat that.

674
00:24:32,671 --> 00:24:34,072
-We're done.
-I'm out.

675
00:24:34,139 --> 00:24:36,308
-What's this? Broccoli.
-They fit so perfectly.

676
00:24:36,374 --> 00:24:38,243
-Broccoli.
-That's so awful. What is that?

677
00:24:38,310 --> 00:24:39,344
You should eat some.

678
00:24:39,411 --> 00:24:40,445
Next, tomato.

679
00:24:40,512 --> 00:24:41,513
UGH

680
00:24:41,580 --> 00:24:43,915
This one has napa cabbage.

681
00:24:43,982 --> 00:24:46,184
Is that a fridge for a rabbit?

682
00:24:46,251 --> 00:24:48,453
-Do you eat all this?
-A rabbit's fridge.

683
00:24:48,520 --> 00:24:50,555
We should throw all that into <i>malatang.</i>

684
00:24:50,622 --> 00:24:52,424
Yes, drop everything in.

685
00:24:52,491 --> 00:24:54,826
It's not that
I'm trying to watch my shape.

686
00:24:54,893 --> 00:24:56,761
I feel much better at work
when I eat like this.

687
00:24:56,828 --> 00:24:58,196
I need to feel lighter to cook.

688
00:24:58,263 --> 00:24:59,931
Do you feel uneasy when you're full?

689
00:24:59,998 --> 00:25:00,866
It bothers me.

690
00:25:00,932 --> 00:25:03,435
Then what about Ho-young or Nam-no…

691
00:25:03,502 --> 00:25:05,537
That must be why I have a difficult time.

692
00:25:05,604 --> 00:25:07,806
I become anemic when I don't eat. Really.

693
00:25:07,873 --> 00:25:09,107
These are something

694
00:25:09,174 --> 00:25:10,642
I eat as a late-night snack.

695
00:25:10,709 --> 00:25:12,277
-These? Broccoli and…
-A late-night snack?

696
00:25:12,344 --> 00:25:13,845
-A late-night snack?
-How are those snacks?

697
00:25:13,912 --> 00:25:14,913
…bell peppers.

698
00:25:14,980 --> 00:25:15,881
Late-night snack?

699
00:25:15,947 --> 00:25:18,216
I crave something
with a crunch at night, so…

700
00:25:18,283 --> 00:25:20,452
-What?
-They're for when I crave that crunch.

701
00:25:20,519 --> 00:25:22,287
You can see the stems here,

702
00:25:22,354 --> 00:25:24,623
and the two parts have different textures.

703
00:25:24,689 --> 00:25:27,859
When I want to chew on something,
I grab these.

704
00:25:27,926 --> 00:25:29,160
He must enjoy the texture.

705
00:25:29,227 --> 00:25:31,062
-It's his snack.
-I'll just live as a fatty.

706
00:25:31,129 --> 00:25:32,531
This is a culture shock.

707
00:25:32,597 --> 00:25:34,699
What do you eat for late-night snacks?

708
00:25:34,766 --> 00:25:36,434
I like to have pork belly.

709
00:25:36,501 --> 00:25:37,435
-Or <i>daechang.</i>
-I want it now.

710
00:25:37,502 --> 00:25:39,704
-Grilled large intestine? Cooked crunchy.
-<i>Daechang.</i>

711
00:25:39,771 --> 00:25:41,673
-That's what you need.
-And you finish off

712
00:25:41,740 --> 00:25:43,074
with <i>gopchang-jeongol.</i>

713
00:25:43,141 --> 00:25:44,276
That's not a bad idea.

714
00:25:44,342 --> 00:25:46,845
-Even raw cucumbers.
-He's so meticulous.

715
00:25:46,912 --> 00:25:49,581
-These look different.
-They're mini cucumbers.

716
00:25:49,648 --> 00:25:51,383
-Where did you…
-They're richer and delicious.

717
00:25:51,449 --> 00:25:52,717
-Really?
-I've never seen it.

718
00:25:52,784 --> 00:25:54,085
THEN LET ME HAVE A BITE

719
00:25:54,152 --> 00:25:54,986
It's good.

720
00:25:55,053 --> 00:25:56,855
Really? Give me one.

721
00:25:56,922 --> 00:25:58,924
Wait, what if we need more?

722
00:25:58,990 --> 00:26:00,825
Stop! He doesn't have many ingredients.

723
00:26:00,892 --> 00:26:03,428
It feels much crunchier.

724
00:26:03,495 --> 00:26:05,897
It's different from the longer ones.

725
00:26:05,964 --> 00:26:07,899
The skin has more of a bite to it.

726
00:26:07,966 --> 00:26:09,568
-It must be great in the morning.
-Try some.

727
00:26:09,634 --> 00:26:10,468
THE TWINS GET SOME

728
00:26:13,171 --> 00:26:14,072
FROWN

729
00:26:14,139 --> 00:26:15,807
When do you eat your meals?

730
00:26:15,874 --> 00:26:17,909
I wouldn't say I eat actual "meals."

731
00:26:17,976 --> 00:26:21,012
Before I open, I make
every single menu on the course

732
00:26:21,079 --> 00:26:25,116
and have to taste all 11 or so dishes
in under 5 minutes.

733
00:26:25,183 --> 00:26:27,852
-I probably get enough calories there.
-You do that at work.

734
00:26:27,919 --> 00:26:30,288
-Isn't that a separate deal?
-That's when you eat.

735
00:26:30,355 --> 00:26:31,756
You probably have no time to eat.

736
00:26:31,823 --> 00:26:34,359
I often go to Chef Ho-young's restaurant,

737
00:26:34,426 --> 00:26:36,394
and he does a lot of tasting.

738
00:26:36,461 --> 00:26:38,663
I start my day with a bowl of udon.

739
00:26:38,730 --> 00:26:40,131
It's for tasting.

740
00:26:40,198 --> 00:26:42,467
-I check the noodles and the soup.
-To taste it.

741
00:26:42,534 --> 00:26:45,270
-You can eat just one strand, right? No?
-The thing is,

742
00:26:45,337 --> 00:26:48,073
-it's hard to stop after one bite.
-That's true.

743
00:26:48,139 --> 00:26:50,342
You can't spit it out.
You swallow it right away.

744
00:26:50,408 --> 00:26:53,078
You don't taste the whole bowl,
but that's what he does.

745
00:26:53,144 --> 00:26:56,481
I have 23 different udon on the menu.

746
00:26:56,548 --> 00:26:58,984
What's down here? Various fruits.

747
00:26:59,050 --> 00:27:01,019
They're way too aligned.

748
00:27:01,086 --> 00:27:02,320
-Watermelon.
-He has watermelon.

749
00:27:02,387 --> 00:27:03,955
-Did it come like that?
-He cut it.

750
00:27:04,022 --> 00:27:05,724
-I cut it myself.
-You did?

751
00:27:05,790 --> 00:27:08,360
And a tub of strawberries.

752
00:27:08,426 --> 00:27:10,161
Blueberries.

753
00:27:10,228 --> 00:27:11,563
Do you like fruit?

754
00:27:11,630 --> 00:27:13,264
I like fruit that are in season,

755
00:27:13,331 --> 00:27:14,933
and I always keep some at home.

756
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:17,235
We just received a tip.

757
00:27:17,302 --> 00:27:19,437
Chef Jong-won loves strawberries,

758
00:27:19,504 --> 00:27:20,605
so his staff call him

759
00:27:20,672 --> 00:27:23,274
-Strawberry Prince.
-Is that so?

760
00:27:23,341 --> 00:27:24,809
Is that true, Strawberry Prince?

761
00:27:24,876 --> 00:27:27,979
I sometimes get two packs of strawberries
on my way to work,

762
00:27:28,046 --> 00:27:30,715
and eat all of that as I work
throughout the day.

763
00:27:30,782 --> 00:27:34,619
-I would've been the Strawberry Boomer.
-Do you not eat what you have at work?

764
00:27:34,686 --> 00:27:37,222
Whatever I keep at work
belongs to the restaurant.

765
00:27:37,288 --> 00:27:38,957
I have to eat my personal strawberries.

766
00:27:39,024 --> 00:27:41,059
-Personal strawberries.
-Keep them separate.

767
00:27:41,126 --> 00:27:42,327
THE PRINCE EATS PERSONAL BERRIES

768
00:27:42,394 --> 00:27:44,896
Chef Ho-young,
what do your staff members call you?

769
00:27:44,963 --> 00:27:46,998
-I'm the Udon Prince.
-Udon Prince?

770
00:27:47,932 --> 00:27:49,367
HAPPY STRAWBERRY PRINCE

771
00:27:49,434 --> 00:27:52,037
Wait a second.
Didn't you give that to him, Chef Sam?

772
00:27:52,103 --> 00:27:53,304
-Which one?
-The olive oil?

773
00:27:53,371 --> 00:27:55,407
-This one?
-You're right.

774
00:27:55,473 --> 00:27:57,142
Me too. I have that too.

775
00:27:57,208 --> 00:27:59,644
He said this when he gave them to us.

776
00:27:59,711 --> 00:28:02,881
That he has his own olive farm in Italy.

777
00:28:02,947 --> 00:28:04,249
He really said that.

778
00:28:04,315 --> 00:28:06,584
OLIVE PRINCE

779
00:28:06,651 --> 00:28:08,119
I pressed some and gave them out.

780
00:28:08,186 --> 00:28:10,121
BRAGGING

781
00:28:10,188 --> 00:28:13,324
Look at his hairstyle today.

782
00:28:13,391 --> 00:28:15,627
-He's like a farm owner.
-Look at him.

783
00:28:15,694 --> 00:28:18,063
-Did you use olive oil on your hair?
-The oil's really tasty.

784
00:28:18,129 --> 00:28:19,731
-Your hair looks greasy.
-It's really good.

785
00:28:19,798 --> 00:28:22,200
What's this? "Oriental dressing."

786
00:28:22,267 --> 00:28:24,302
-Yes.
-He has just one bottle of it.

787
00:28:24,369 --> 00:28:27,539
I like to eat salads,
and when I crave something strong,

788
00:28:27,605 --> 00:28:29,007
I use that.

789
00:28:29,074 --> 00:28:31,176
How is oriental dressing strong?

790
00:28:31,242 --> 00:28:34,345
It's rather strong,
so a nice dose of that is quite pleasing.

791
00:28:36,715 --> 00:28:38,817
I can drink that thing.

792
00:28:38,883 --> 00:28:41,152
And that's the man
that ate Poong's dishes.

793
00:28:41,219 --> 00:28:44,122
If you make the sauce with chili oil,

794
00:28:44,189 --> 00:28:46,024
-it's really good.
-It sounds good.

795
00:28:46,091 --> 00:28:48,560
-You can eat it forever.
-That's a different level of "strong."

796
00:28:48,626 --> 00:28:51,162
-This must be wine.
-Wine?

797
00:28:51,229 --> 00:28:53,031
-Do you like to drink?
-He has alcohol?

798
00:28:53,098 --> 00:28:55,934
-My father made that.
-Korean wild grape wine?

799
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:57,235
Do you not drink often?

800
00:28:57,302 --> 00:28:59,037
-I drink with my friends.
-After work?

801
00:28:59,104 --> 00:29:01,005
-Yes, or at team dinners.
-With your staff.

802
00:29:01,072 --> 00:29:03,374
I hear you binge eat when you get drunk.

803
00:29:03,441 --> 00:29:05,777
There comes a time once in a while

804
00:29:05,844 --> 00:29:08,146
when I end up letting myself go.

805
00:29:08,213 --> 00:29:11,216
Then I go to a convenience store
and buy everything I want.

806
00:29:11,282 --> 00:29:14,285
After I get everything,
I plan out the order I'll eat them in.

807
00:29:15,153 --> 00:29:16,721
You plan out your snacks?

808
00:29:16,788 --> 00:29:18,523
When I eat something sweet,
I crave saltiness.

809
00:29:18,590 --> 00:29:20,525
And after a salty snack, something sweet.

810
00:29:20,592 --> 00:29:23,161
I begin with basic potato chips

811
00:29:23,228 --> 00:29:25,463
followed by a tiny <i>yakgwa.</i>

812
00:29:25,530 --> 00:29:27,699
After that, I move on
to something stronger like nachos.

813
00:29:27,766 --> 00:29:31,136
So I plan out everything in my head
when I get my haul.

814
00:29:31,202 --> 00:29:34,472
-And he considers the textures too.
-You don't buy things randomly.

815
00:29:34,539 --> 00:29:37,108
-Well, it's a drunken haul.
-You should down everything at once.

816
00:29:37,175 --> 00:29:39,177
-He calls that "letting go"?
-That's incredible.

817
00:29:39,244 --> 00:29:40,578
Oh, marsh snail!

818
00:29:40,645 --> 00:29:43,248
-Marsh snail juice.
-Park Ji-hwan had this.

819
00:29:43,314 --> 00:29:45,250
-Yes, it was Ji-hwan.
-Right?

820
00:29:45,316 --> 00:29:46,985
I like to listen attentively.

821
00:29:47,051 --> 00:29:49,687
-You're just easily convinced.
-You're easily convinced.

822
00:29:49,754 --> 00:29:50,588
He's easily convinced.

823
00:29:50,655 --> 00:29:51,990
How does he smile like that?

824
00:29:52,056 --> 00:29:54,058
When I see something that looks healthy

825
00:29:54,125 --> 00:29:57,562
-or delicious during a shoot here…
-It was convincing, though.

826
00:29:57,629 --> 00:29:58,696
-Did you order these?
-Yes.

827
00:29:58,763 --> 00:29:59,831
-You did?
-Yes.

828
00:29:59,898 --> 00:30:01,566
What else have you bought?

829
00:30:01,633 --> 00:30:04,035
I bought a pack of seasoned eels
Choo Sung-hoon had.

830
00:30:04,102 --> 00:30:06,204
-You mean this one?
-Yes.

831
00:30:06,271 --> 00:30:09,574
-You'll also find Joo Woo-jae's stuff.
-This one?

832
00:30:09,641 --> 00:30:12,177
<i>I had a rough time</i>
<i>because that was all I had to work with,</i>

833
00:30:12,243 --> 00:30:14,112
-but it was good.
-This rice cake!

834
00:30:14,679 --> 00:30:17,682
-The one with red bean paste.
-The ones Woo-jae had?

835
00:30:17,749 --> 00:30:19,484
I bought it but rarely eat them.

836
00:30:19,551 --> 00:30:21,820
Let's go through his freezer.

837
00:30:21,886 --> 00:30:24,189
-Bread. He wrote something here too.
-Bread?

838
00:30:24,255 --> 00:30:25,557
Sourdough.

839
00:30:25,623 --> 00:30:27,826
-Country-style and multigrain.
-Multigrain?

840
00:30:27,892 --> 00:30:30,195
I used to work in San Francisco,

841
00:30:30,261 --> 00:30:31,596
which is famous for sourdough.

842
00:30:31,663 --> 00:30:34,465
It's a fermented, healthy bread.

843
00:30:34,532 --> 00:30:35,767
EASY TO DIGEST

844
00:30:35,834 --> 00:30:36,935
How do you eat this?

845
00:30:37,001 --> 00:30:40,338
I heat up a pan and toast it as is.

846
00:30:40,405 --> 00:30:42,607
Or when I feel like
having something stronger,

847
00:30:42,674 --> 00:30:45,009
-I throw in some olive oil.
-Something stronger?

848
00:30:45,076 --> 00:30:47,212
-How is olive oil strong?
-Olive oil?

849
00:30:47,278 --> 00:30:48,746
-Not chili oil?
-Or sesame oil?

850
00:30:48,813 --> 00:30:49,681
Not even butter?

851
00:30:49,747 --> 00:30:51,416
IS THIS A GOOD VIBES JOKE?

852
00:30:51,482 --> 00:30:53,918
I found some beef brisket.

853
00:30:53,985 --> 00:30:55,620
-Brisket, January 16th.
-Finally.

854
00:30:55,687 --> 00:30:57,388
-We found meat.
-We found something.

855
00:30:57,455 --> 00:30:59,324
That's a fatty cut, yet you eat that?

856
00:30:59,390 --> 00:31:01,226
I usually have the leaner flank.

857
00:31:01,292 --> 00:31:03,962
But that's for when I want
something stronger.

858
00:31:04,028 --> 00:31:06,164
He eats brisket for a stronger taste.

859
00:31:06,231 --> 00:31:08,132
You're determined to be funny, aren't you?

860
00:31:08,700 --> 00:31:11,369
HIS NEW YEAR'S RESOLUTION

861
00:31:11,436 --> 00:31:12,904
A pack of dumplings.

862
00:31:12,971 --> 00:31:15,707
I got that as a freebie

863
00:31:15,773 --> 00:31:18,576
when I ordered over 70,000 won of veggies.

864
00:31:18,643 --> 00:31:20,411
Please use it today.

865
00:31:20,478 --> 00:31:22,547
You must not cook much at home?

866
00:31:22,614 --> 00:31:24,015
I do it all day at work,

867
00:31:24,082 --> 00:31:25,750
-so I don't want to do it at home.
-That's why.

868
00:31:25,817 --> 00:31:27,652
Do you get food delivered?

869
00:31:27,719 --> 00:31:29,020
-I rarely get food delivered.
-No?

870
00:31:29,087 --> 00:31:31,522
-Do you eat <i>ramyeon?</i>
-I rarely eat <i>ramyeon.</i>

871
00:31:32,257 --> 00:31:34,192
-I can't date Chef Jong-won.
-One second.

872
00:31:34,259 --> 00:31:37,395
I would feel so depressed
if my fridge looked like that.

873
00:31:37,462 --> 00:31:39,063
You aren't a light eater, though.

874
00:31:39,130 --> 00:31:41,566
You sometimes binge eat
when you let go of yourself.

875
00:31:41,633 --> 00:31:44,702
If I want to,
I can eat four to five servings of meat.

876
00:31:44,769 --> 00:31:45,670
Really?

877
00:31:45,737 --> 00:31:48,573
-<i>Jjigae</i> on top of that as well.
-So you do.

878
00:31:48,640 --> 00:31:49,974
Room temperature ingredients.

879
00:31:50,041 --> 00:31:51,709
What are these black beans?

880
00:31:51,776 --> 00:31:53,111
A snack. A late-night snack.

881
00:31:53,177 --> 00:31:54,846
-As a late-night snack?
-A late-night snack?

882
00:31:54,913 --> 00:31:55,747
It's good.

883
00:31:55,813 --> 00:31:58,716
-Is this <i>miyeok</i>?
-Actually,

884
00:31:58,783 --> 00:32:00,985
they're leftovers from my last birthday
after making <i>miyeok-guk.</i>

885
00:32:01,052 --> 00:32:03,054
-What? Why?
-Alone?

886
00:32:03,121 --> 00:32:04,355
Do you miss home-cooked meals?

887
00:32:04,422 --> 00:32:06,624
I miss my mom's food.

888
00:32:06,691 --> 00:32:09,527
What's your favorite dish
among what she makes?

889
00:32:09,594 --> 00:32:12,163
I always loved <i>dak-gangjeong,</i>
Korean crispy chicken.

890
00:32:12,230 --> 00:32:14,399
Also, <i>doenjang-jjigae</i> with blue crab.

891
00:32:14,465 --> 00:32:16,768
Now we're talking.

892
00:32:16,834 --> 00:32:17,802
That's more human.

893
00:32:17,869 --> 00:32:19,804
-What's this? Saffron?
-Saffron?

894
00:32:19,871 --> 00:32:21,406
-You have saffron?
-Saffron.

895
00:32:21,472 --> 00:32:22,740
-Saffron.
-Why does he have that?

896
00:32:22,807 --> 00:32:23,975
-To do laundry?
-Really?

897
00:32:24,042 --> 00:32:25,777
-Really?
-Who said laundry?

898
00:32:25,843 --> 00:32:27,178
It was a gift from a long time ago.

899
00:32:27,245 --> 00:32:29,647
-I once made risotto with it.
-While doing laundry?

900
00:32:29,714 --> 00:32:31,049
It's gold dust.

901
00:32:31,115 --> 00:32:32,350
-Edible gold?
-Why do you have this?

902
00:32:32,417 --> 00:32:33,551
-Gold dust.
-He has gold dust?

903
00:32:33,618 --> 00:32:35,987
I warm up instant rice,
top it with canned tuna,

904
00:32:36,054 --> 00:32:38,089
and garnish with gold dust.

905
00:32:38,156 --> 00:32:40,325
-You went too far.
-Sounds suspicious.

906
00:32:40,391 --> 00:32:42,093
That was so staged.

907
00:32:42,160 --> 00:32:44,629
-It was staged.
-Those were left over after an event.

908
00:32:44,696 --> 00:32:46,197
It somehow ended up at home.

909
00:32:46,764 --> 00:32:47,598
Is it an investment?

910
00:32:47,665 --> 00:32:49,834
-Investment?
-Not a bad idea. Gold dust.

911
00:32:49,901 --> 00:32:50,835
Look. Glass noodles.

912
00:32:50,902 --> 00:32:52,737
-He has some glass noodles.
-Glass noodles.

913
00:32:52,804 --> 00:32:56,674
That was all for Chef Jong-won's fridge.

914
00:32:57,842 --> 00:32:58,910
He doesn't even have kimchi.

915
00:32:59,477 --> 00:33:02,280
Now, what does he want to eat today?

916
00:33:02,347 --> 00:33:04,682
Please show us his orders.

917
00:33:05,350 --> 00:33:06,284
I'm curious.

918
00:33:07,051 --> 00:33:10,588
Mission Son-Possible: Mirror Match.

919
00:33:10,655 --> 00:33:11,756
-Mirror Match?
-What do you mean?

920
00:33:11,823 --> 00:33:13,591
-What?
-There's no one to mirror.

921
00:33:13,658 --> 00:33:15,159
I want two chefs

922
00:33:15,226 --> 00:33:16,794
to cook with the same ingredients

923
00:33:16,861 --> 00:33:20,365
and see the kind of creativity
they'll come up with.

924
00:33:20,431 --> 00:33:22,333
I have chosen
five of my favorite ingredients.

925
00:33:22,400 --> 00:33:23,701
Oh, just using five ingredients?

926
00:33:23,768 --> 00:33:26,904
-Five ingredients have been decided.
-That sounds fun.

927
00:33:26,971 --> 00:33:29,340
-It sounds fun.
-The same ingredients?

928
00:33:29,407 --> 00:33:31,309
Please announce the ingredients.

929
00:33:31,376 --> 00:33:33,144
-Eel.
-Eel sounds good.

930
00:33:33,211 --> 00:33:34,846
-Strawberries.
-Strawberries.

931
00:33:34,912 --> 00:33:36,681
-Cucumbers.
-Cucumbers.

932
00:33:36,748 --> 00:33:38,850
-Watermelon.
-Watermelon.

933
00:33:38,916 --> 00:33:41,252
-And Woo-jae's <i>tteok.</i>
-Woo-jae's <i>tteok.</i>

934
00:33:42,153 --> 00:33:43,388
That's a crazy mix.

935
00:33:43,454 --> 00:33:46,157
-The one with red bean paste.
-It's crazy.

936
00:33:46,224 --> 00:33:47,492
That sounds hard.

937
00:33:47,558 --> 00:33:49,160
Are we not allowed to use anything else?

938
00:33:49,227 --> 00:33:50,228
You may.

939
00:33:50,294 --> 00:33:53,031
-But the five are a must.
-A must?

940
00:33:53,097 --> 00:33:54,365
What's the second order?

941
00:33:54,899 --> 00:33:57,568
I'm Letting Myself Go Today.

942
00:33:57,635 --> 00:33:59,303
I'm Letting Myself Go.

943
00:33:59,370 --> 00:34:01,539
When I feel like eating,
I can eat a lot too.

944
00:34:01,606 --> 00:34:03,808
As I mentioned,
I can eat four to five servings of meat.

945
00:34:03,875 --> 00:34:07,545
Also, I have a favorite dumpling place,
and they have ten pieces per pack.

946
00:34:07,612 --> 00:34:09,580
I can sometimes finish the whole pack,

947
00:34:09,647 --> 00:34:11,516
and I've once had 2 packs,
so 20 dumplings.

948
00:34:11,582 --> 00:34:13,217
THAT CERTAINLY IS A LOT

949
00:34:13,284 --> 00:34:15,553
-He controls himself.
-So if the chefs

950
00:34:15,620 --> 00:34:18,890
make something delicious for me,
I'll let myself go and eat it all.

951
00:34:18,956 --> 00:34:21,859
-He wants to let himself go today.
-Letting go.

952
00:34:21,926 --> 00:34:24,062
Now, let's fill up the contenders

953
00:34:24,128 --> 00:34:25,563
and decide the matches.

954
00:34:25,630 --> 00:34:26,931
-After seeing the ingredients,
-Yes?

955
00:34:26,998 --> 00:34:30,234
I thought about it and realized that
birds of a feather should stay together.

956
00:34:30,301 --> 00:34:31,769
How are you two birds of a feather?

957
00:34:31,836 --> 00:34:35,506
I'll take ingredients from his fridge
and take on the Son-Possible challenge.

958
00:34:35,573 --> 00:34:37,208
-So you're like Jong-won?
-Yes.

959
00:34:37,275 --> 00:34:39,410
The ingredients were familiar.
I always eat those.

960
00:34:39,977 --> 00:34:41,145
Always?

961
00:34:41,212 --> 00:34:42,880
It's a mirror match,
so what do you say, twin?

962
00:34:42,947 --> 00:34:44,182
The twin?

963
00:34:44,248 --> 00:34:46,417
Yes, I'm in.
Him and Jong-won are not mirror images,

964
00:34:46,484 --> 00:34:47,618
it's us two.

965
00:34:47,685 --> 00:34:49,353
No, it's Jong-won and me.

966
00:34:49,420 --> 00:34:51,089
No! Don't make me angry.

967
00:34:51,155 --> 00:34:52,256
It's him and me.

968
00:34:52,590 --> 00:34:54,358
MISSION SON-POSSIBLE
HAS BEEN DECIDED

969
00:34:54,425 --> 00:34:57,795
Sung-jun and Nam-no's round
has been sealed.

970
00:34:57,862 --> 00:34:59,931
Now, who'll help him let himself go?

971
00:34:59,997 --> 00:35:01,299
-Should I try?
-Ho-young?

972
00:35:01,365 --> 00:35:03,201
-Letting go.
-Are you sure?

973
00:35:03,267 --> 00:35:05,503
I've never had to hold myself tightly.

974
00:35:05,570 --> 00:35:08,039
-Not ever.
-No, never. I think I can make him let go.

975
00:35:08,106 --> 00:35:10,875
Chef Ho-young will
help Jong-won let go of himself.

976
00:35:10,942 --> 00:35:12,977
ONE LAST SPOT

977
00:35:13,044 --> 00:35:15,880
You can join if you want to.

978
00:35:15,947 --> 00:35:17,882
Poong, you can cook in this round too.

979
00:35:17,949 --> 00:35:21,018
-He can?
-He's one of the contenders who can cook.

980
00:35:21,085 --> 00:35:24,622
-Aren't you good at letting yourself go?
-Well, you know.

981
00:35:24,689 --> 00:35:27,458
I can make him let himself go
and even make his belt loose.

982
00:35:27,525 --> 00:35:28,860
I'LL MAKE YOU LET GO
OF EVERYTHING

983
00:35:28,926 --> 00:35:30,995
-You make it too loose.
-I think I should do it.

984
00:35:31,062 --> 00:35:34,232
I'll make sure
I make Jong-won let himself go.

985
00:35:35,233 --> 00:35:37,802
-Poong joins the round
-That's nice.

986
00:35:37,869 --> 00:35:39,904
-knowing he can cook for Jong-won.
-Yes.

987
00:35:39,971 --> 00:35:42,840
Then, let us begin the first round,
Mission Son-Possible: Mirror Match

988
00:35:42,907 --> 00:35:44,742
between the first two chefs!

989
00:35:48,079 --> 00:35:52,416
<i>This is the first round of the cook-off</i>
<i>with Chef Jong-won's ingredients.</i>

990
00:35:52,483 --> 00:35:54,619
The former point person
of the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance,

991
00:35:54,685 --> 00:35:56,888
but a current member
of Son Jong-won's fan club,

992
00:35:56,954 --> 00:35:58,523
Chef Yoon Nam-no is here.

993
00:35:58,589 --> 00:36:00,324
The former chair
of the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance,

994
00:36:00,391 --> 00:36:02,059
but a current Son Jong-won copycat,

995
00:36:02,126 --> 00:36:04,061
Chef Kwon Sung-jun is also here.

996
00:36:05,129 --> 00:36:07,298
That apron. How are you doing?

997
00:36:07,365 --> 00:36:09,901
This is tougher to stand in
than the suit I was in.

998
00:36:09,967 --> 00:36:11,335
No, he's asking the apron.

999
00:36:11,903 --> 00:36:13,004
How are you doing, apron?

1000
00:36:13,070 --> 00:36:14,138
It's like, "Help!"

1001
00:36:14,205 --> 00:36:16,707
I'm sorry, but did you pull it off
from the plushie?

1002
00:36:18,342 --> 00:36:21,212
-Hang in there for just 15 minutes.
-I hope it does.

1003
00:36:21,279 --> 00:36:23,981
He wanted to borrow it from me.

1004
00:36:24,048 --> 00:36:26,083
It's the one you use, right?

1005
00:36:26,150 --> 00:36:27,919
He said he envied his Michelin star,

1006
00:36:27,985 --> 00:36:29,687
so he became the Michelin Man.

1007
00:36:29,754 --> 00:36:32,757
-The character for the tire company?
-Yes.

1008
00:36:33,925 --> 00:36:35,893
Chef Nam-no, your hairstyle is…

1009
00:36:35,960 --> 00:36:37,929
-The good vibes hair.
-Yes, the good vibes hair.

1010
00:36:37,995 --> 00:36:39,797
For the next 15 minutes,

1011
00:36:39,864 --> 00:36:41,699
I wish to resemble him.

1012
00:36:41,999 --> 00:36:43,167
PFFT

1013
00:36:43,234 --> 00:36:44,936
He looks way too cool

1014
00:36:45,002 --> 00:36:48,172
<i>when his hair flutters,</i>
<i>and it's enticing even to a man like me.</i>

1015
00:36:48,239 --> 00:36:49,774
Also, that smile in his eyes.

1016
00:36:49,840 --> 00:36:52,543
-He smiles like this.
-Yes, that smile.

1017
00:36:52,610 --> 00:36:55,279
-Aren't you just nearsighted?
-Nearsighted?

1018
00:36:55,546 --> 00:36:56,981
SMILE IN HIS EYES?

1019
00:36:57,048 --> 00:37:01,185
Chef Sung-jun, are you also wearing
Chef Jong-won's apron?

1020
00:37:01,252 --> 00:37:02,687
Yes, doesn't it look good on me?

1021
00:37:02,753 --> 00:37:03,955
-It does.
-I warned you to stop.

1022
00:37:04,021 --> 00:37:06,791
The two are doing their best

1023
00:37:06,857 --> 00:37:09,460
-to win a star from Jong-won.
-This isn't easy.

1024
00:37:09,527 --> 00:37:14,165
They once wished to take Jong-won down
as the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance,

1025
00:37:14,232 --> 00:37:17,535
but they're now dying
to jump on the Jong-won bandwagon.

1026
00:37:17,602 --> 00:37:19,136
LET'S GET ON HIS BANDWAGON!

1027
00:37:19,203 --> 00:37:22,940
And Chef Nam-no always asks Jong-won
to eat pork belly with him.

1028
00:37:23,007 --> 00:37:24,375
Every time we shoot, I ask,

1029
00:37:24,442 --> 00:37:26,644
"Chef Jong-won, how about pork belly?"

1030
00:37:26,711 --> 00:37:28,779
But he always shakes his head.

1031
00:37:28,846 --> 00:37:30,448
I do like pork belly, though.

1032
00:37:30,514 --> 00:37:33,017
But I can't eat it every single day
as he asks.

1033
00:37:33,084 --> 00:37:34,218
How can he eat it daily?

1034
00:37:34,285 --> 00:37:35,753
But you still have a feeling, right?

1035
00:37:35,820 --> 00:37:38,956
He may say those words,
but does it seem like he likes you?

1036
00:37:39,023 --> 00:37:41,692
I'm not delusional
when I say that he really likes me.

1037
00:37:42,093 --> 00:37:43,127
NODS

1038
00:37:43,194 --> 00:37:46,464
-Does this mean you take me as a pet pig?
-Pet pig?

1039
00:37:46,530 --> 00:37:48,266
Will you be my master?

1040
00:37:48,332 --> 00:37:51,402
If Nam-no is the pet pig,
then what are you, Sung-jun?

1041
00:37:51,469 --> 00:37:53,104
I can be the fat cat.

1042
00:37:53,170 --> 00:37:54,205
Fat cat?

1043
00:37:54,272 --> 00:37:56,874
-I'm the fat cat.
-I can totally see it.

1044
00:37:56,941 --> 00:37:59,877
After you two have become
Jong-won's fanboys,

1045
00:37:59,944 --> 00:38:03,881
there's now a new chairperson
for the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance.

1046
00:38:03,948 --> 00:38:06,484
It wasn't just me
who held Chef Jong-won in check.

1047
00:38:06,550 --> 00:38:08,319
These days, my mother has joined me.

1048
00:38:08,386 --> 00:38:10,121
-Even your mother?
-She's doing it too.

1049
00:38:10,187 --> 00:38:11,355
I see.

1050
00:38:11,422 --> 00:38:12,690
She called me two days ago

1051
00:38:12,757 --> 00:38:14,425
and told me about Jong-won's ad gig.

1052
00:38:14,492 --> 00:38:17,461
She relays everything
about what Jong-won does.

1053
00:38:17,528 --> 00:38:19,263
She's been holding him in check too.

1054
00:38:19,330 --> 00:38:20,865
You must take after her.

1055
00:38:20,931 --> 00:38:22,566
HE WAS BORN(?)
WITH THIS CHARACTER

1056
00:38:23,401 --> 00:38:25,503
CHEF NAM-NO'S INGREDIENTS: EEL, TTEOK,
STRAWBERRY, WATERMELON, CUCUMBER

1057
00:38:25,569 --> 00:38:27,571
WALNUT, TOASTED BLACK BEAN, BELL PEPPER,
CHERRY TOMATO, HONEY, MILK, AND MORE

1058
00:38:27,638 --> 00:38:29,206
The name of my dish is

1059
00:38:29,273 --> 00:38:30,841
"Eatanic Maniac."

1060
00:38:30,908 --> 00:38:32,476
-Eatanic Maniac.
-Eatanic Maniac.

1061
00:38:32,543 --> 00:38:33,911
-Eatanic Maniac.
-Eatanic Maniac.

1062
00:38:33,978 --> 00:38:35,946
-Eatanic Maniac.
-Eatanic Maniac.

1063
00:38:36,013 --> 00:38:38,749
I named it after his restaurant,
Eatanic Garden.

1064
00:38:38,816 --> 00:38:40,751
GOT THE IDEA FROM HIS RESTAURANT

1065
00:38:40,818 --> 00:38:42,887
I want to recreate
the pine nut cream salad you made

1066
00:38:42,953 --> 00:38:44,622
in maniac style.

1067
00:38:44,689 --> 00:38:46,590
Is that a dish at Eatanic Garden?

1068
00:38:46,657 --> 00:38:48,893
-Yes, it was on the menu.
-One of his dishes?

1069
00:38:48,959 --> 00:38:53,364
The salad is made with crab meat
with slices of vegetables piled up on it.

1070
00:38:53,431 --> 00:38:55,399
And it's topped with pine nut sauce.

1071
00:38:55,466 --> 00:38:56,434
It looks good.

1072
00:38:56,500 --> 00:38:57,802
But he doesn't have pine nuts,

1073
00:38:57,868 --> 00:39:01,806
so I'll use walnuts
to make walnut cream sauce.

1074
00:39:01,872 --> 00:39:04,508
And then I'll pile up the pieces
of eel and cucumber,

1075
00:39:05,142 --> 00:39:07,011
although I'm not sure
if I can make that shape.

1076
00:39:07,078 --> 00:39:09,647
-That shape?
-That dish takes a lot of work.

1077
00:39:09,714 --> 00:39:12,616
As for the watermelon,
I'll whip it up into pickles.

1078
00:39:12,683 --> 00:39:14,618
-Pickles?
-Yes.

1079
00:39:14,685 --> 00:39:16,187
-And I'll coat the <i>tteok…</i>
-Pickled watermelon?

1080
00:39:16,253 --> 00:39:17,888
<i>…</i>with balsamic vinegar and toast it.

1081
00:39:18,856 --> 00:39:23,160
So you plan to pay homage to a dish
he makes at his Korean restaurant?

1082
00:39:23,227 --> 00:39:25,329
Yes, I'm paying homage,

1083
00:39:25,396 --> 00:39:26,897
though I'm not sure if it's possible.

1084
00:39:27,732 --> 00:39:29,767
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS: EEL, TTEOK,
STRAWBERRY, WATERMELON, CUCUMBER

1085
00:39:29,834 --> 00:39:31,902
APPLE, WALNUT, SOURDOUGH, MILK,
WILD GRAPE WINE, SAFFRON, AND MORE

1086
00:39:31,969 --> 00:39:34,739
Fighting against Nam-no is Sung-jun.
What are you making?

1087
00:39:34,805 --> 00:39:36,607
The name of my dish is

1088
00:39:37,174 --> 00:39:39,877
"Your Son's Not as Hot as Jong-won,
Sorry Mom's Tart."

1089
00:39:39,944 --> 00:39:42,346
-"Not as hot"?
-Your Son's Not as Hot as Jong-won,

1090
00:39:42,413 --> 00:39:43,914
-Sorry Mom's Tart.
-Sorry Mom's Tart.

1091
00:39:43,981 --> 00:39:45,449
That's how I name my dishes.

1092
00:39:45,516 --> 00:39:48,652
Your Son's Too Hot, Sorry Mom's Lunch Box.

1093
00:39:48,719 --> 00:39:51,188
He's paying homage
to the name of Jong-won's dish.

1094
00:39:51,255 --> 00:39:52,923
THE FAT CAT GOES FOR THE NAME

1095
00:39:52,990 --> 00:39:55,760
-That was witty.
-Also, my mom holds you in check,

1096
00:39:55,826 --> 00:39:57,194
so I wanted to apologize for that

1097
00:39:57,261 --> 00:39:58,629
and make a tart with good vibes.

1098
00:39:58,696 --> 00:40:00,064
A tart with good vibes.

1099
00:40:00,131 --> 00:40:02,199
I plan to make two kinds of tarts,

1100
00:40:02,266 --> 00:40:05,970
and one of them
is a refreshing appetizer tart

1101
00:40:06,036 --> 00:40:09,407
made with eel, cucumber, and apple.

1102
00:40:09,473 --> 00:40:11,008
The other one is a dessert,

1103
00:40:11,075 --> 00:40:13,344
which will be challenging,
because I'll make <i>crème pâtissière.</i>

1104
00:40:13,411 --> 00:40:15,913
I'll make pastry cream with saffron

1105
00:40:15,980 --> 00:40:19,150
and use Woo-jae's <i>tteok</i>
as a nice addition to the cream.

1106
00:40:19,216 --> 00:40:21,452
I see. On top of the pastry cream?

1107
00:40:21,519 --> 00:40:23,020
And I'll add watermelon and strawberry.

1108
00:40:23,087 --> 00:40:25,689
They'll both pay homage to Chef Jong-won.

1109
00:40:25,756 --> 00:40:27,124
We will begin the round,

1110
00:40:27,191 --> 00:40:30,661
"Mission Son-Possible: Mirror Match."

1111
00:40:31,228 --> 00:40:33,130
A man who loves Jong-won,

1112
00:40:33,197 --> 00:40:36,901
-Jong-won's pet pig, Chef Yoon Nam-no.
-Oink.

1113
00:40:36,967 --> 00:40:38,869
A man who's jealous of Jong-won,

1114
00:40:38,936 --> 00:40:42,239
Jong-won's fat cat, Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

1115
00:40:42,306 --> 00:40:45,810
Who will Chef Jong-won choose?

1116
00:40:45,876 --> 00:40:49,246
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1117
00:40:50,881 --> 00:40:51,949
FULFILL JONG-WON'S MISSION

1118
00:40:52,016 --> 00:40:53,684
Begin!

1119
00:40:55,286 --> 00:40:57,421
They're both moving swiftly.

1120
00:40:57,922 --> 00:40:59,657
1. BOIL MILK AND SAFFRON

1121
00:40:59,723 --> 00:41:00,925
Is that milk and saffron?

1122
00:41:01,492 --> 00:41:02,760
He's using bread.

1123
00:41:02,827 --> 00:41:04,562
To use as the tart shell?

1124
00:41:04,628 --> 00:41:07,465
Chef Jong-won often made
tart shells with plain bread,

1125
00:41:07,531 --> 00:41:09,900
-but sourdough has bigger air pockets.
-Yes, can he do that?

1126
00:41:09,967 --> 00:41:12,603
If things don't go well,
the shape may not turn out nicely.

1127
00:41:12,670 --> 00:41:15,239
-It's not as dense as plain bread.
-It's not.

1128
00:41:15,306 --> 00:41:17,575
We may not catch a mistake you make,

1129
00:41:17,641 --> 00:41:20,978
-but Chef Jong-won can.
-Of course.

1130
00:41:21,045 --> 00:41:23,080
It's not going too well.

1131
00:41:23,147 --> 00:41:25,916
You're right. The bread is too moist,
so it's getting stuck.

1132
00:41:25,983 --> 00:41:28,519
The air pockets create those holes.

1133
00:41:28,586 --> 00:41:30,421
The edges won't flatten well.

1134
00:41:30,921 --> 00:41:31,755
AGENT PET PIG BOILS EGGS

1135
00:41:31,822 --> 00:41:35,059
-He's boiling eggs?
-Nam-no boils eggs first.

1136
00:41:35,125 --> 00:41:37,428
What's he doing now?

1137
00:41:37,495 --> 00:41:40,498
-What is that?
-He coated Woo-jae's <i>tteok</i> with something.

1138
00:41:40,564 --> 00:41:42,733
It must be balsamic sauce.

1139
00:41:42,800 --> 00:41:44,101
Balsamic sauce.

1140
00:41:44,168 --> 00:41:47,104
-Just balsamic sauce?
-Olive oil and balsamic sauce.

1141
00:41:47,171 --> 00:41:50,374
The addition of olive oil
makes the food seem very rich.

1142
00:41:50,441 --> 00:41:53,410
Since he uses olive oil
when he wants a stronger taste.

1143
00:41:54,578 --> 00:41:55,646
-Does it flatten okay?
-Yes.

1144
00:41:55,980 --> 00:41:56,981
KITTY KNEADING

1145
00:41:57,047 --> 00:42:00,184
Sung-jun flattens the pieces of bread.

1146
00:42:00,251 --> 00:42:02,152
A rolling pin should work well.

1147
00:42:02,219 --> 00:42:03,320
2. CUT THE BREAD OUT WITH A MOLD

1148
00:42:03,387 --> 00:42:04,989
The texture will turn out like rice cake.

1149
00:42:05,055 --> 00:42:07,091
APPLY BUTTER

1150
00:42:07,491 --> 00:42:09,126
SUGAR

1151
00:42:09,693 --> 00:42:12,730
AND INTO THE TART MOLD

1152
00:42:12,796 --> 00:42:13,831
Isn't it too thick?

1153
00:42:13,898 --> 00:42:15,099
I doubt it'll get thinner.

1154
00:42:15,165 --> 00:42:17,067
You should push it down harder.

1155
00:42:17,134 --> 00:42:18,836
FIXED WITH PRESSING STONES

1156
00:42:18,903 --> 00:42:20,871
The mold keeps rising back up.

1157
00:42:20,938 --> 00:42:23,941
He may not end up making the right shape.

1158
00:42:24,008 --> 00:42:25,376
Yes, they seem…

1159
00:42:25,442 --> 00:42:27,444
Sourdough pieces are rather thick.

1160
00:42:27,511 --> 00:42:28,612
MM-HMM

1161
00:42:30,180 --> 00:42:31,849
Walnuts and milk?

1162
00:42:31,916 --> 00:42:33,884
-What's that?
-Water.

1163
00:42:33,951 --> 00:42:35,452
Why did you add water?

1164
00:42:35,519 --> 00:42:37,655
It'll get too sticky with just milk.

1165
00:42:37,721 --> 00:42:38,989
-Salt.
-Salt.

1166
00:42:39,056 --> 00:42:39,890
Salt and sugar.

1167
00:42:39,957 --> 00:42:41,892
-Vinegar.
-Lemon juice?

1168
00:42:41,959 --> 00:42:45,195
He's supposed to make that with pine nuts,

1169
00:42:45,262 --> 00:42:46,964
but he's substituting them with walnuts.

1170
00:42:47,031 --> 00:42:47,965
GRINDING IN THE BLENDER

1171
00:42:48,032 --> 00:42:49,433
What's that?

1172
00:42:51,101 --> 00:42:52,336
What's he grinding?

1173
00:42:52,403 --> 00:42:53,771
-Black beans.
-Black beans?

1174
00:42:53,837 --> 00:42:55,339
It's great for hair loss prevention.

1175
00:42:55,406 --> 00:42:56,974
Why are you using that?

1176
00:42:57,041 --> 00:42:59,810
I wanted to use breadcrumbs,
but he didn't have any.

1177
00:43:00,377 --> 00:43:02,079
It turned into a purée.

1178
00:43:02,146 --> 00:43:03,547
He'll need more water.

1179
00:43:03,614 --> 00:43:06,083
-Yes, you do. It looks sticky.
-It's too thick.

1180
00:43:06,150 --> 00:43:07,484
Wait, let me check.

1181
00:43:09,286 --> 00:43:10,955
Again? He has to do it over!

1182
00:43:11,021 --> 00:43:12,756
SAUCE THICKNESS UNSUITABLE

1183
00:43:12,823 --> 00:43:14,358
Was it too thick?

1184
00:43:14,425 --> 00:43:16,393
He already made one mistake.

1185
00:43:16,460 --> 00:43:18,429
He lost at least a minute from that.

1186
00:43:18,495 --> 00:43:21,131
-One more try.
-Nam-no looks flustered.

1187
00:43:21,198 --> 00:43:22,399
It's an emergency.

1188
00:43:22,466 --> 00:43:23,901
Wee-oo, wee-oo.

1189
00:43:23,968 --> 00:43:25,836
The fridge owner is a chef,

1190
00:43:25,903 --> 00:43:28,639
-so the two look quite nervous.
-They do.

1191
00:43:28,706 --> 00:43:31,308
Of course, it's nerve-racking.
I could never.

1192
00:43:31,375 --> 00:43:32,876
Eleven minutes.

1193
00:43:32,943 --> 00:43:33,978
SECOND TRY WITH MORE WATER

1194
00:43:35,346 --> 00:43:36,914
THIS TIME,
THE VISCOSITY IS PERFECT

1195
00:43:37,247 --> 00:43:39,483
AGENT FAT CAT
SEPARATES EGG YOLKS

1196
00:43:40,150 --> 00:43:43,654
He's mixing egg yolks with sugar.

1197
00:43:43,721 --> 00:43:47,124
WHIPPING LIKE CRAZY!

1198
00:43:48,192 --> 00:43:49,026
Sugar powder.

1199
00:43:49,093 --> 00:43:50,794
-Sugar powder.
-That's sugar powder? You had that?

1200
00:43:50,861 --> 00:43:52,262
-It's starch.
-Starch.

1201
00:43:53,297 --> 00:43:55,499
AGAIN, WHIPPING
UNTIL HIS ARM FALLS OFF

1202
00:43:56,066 --> 00:43:56,934
PHEW

1203
00:43:57,434 --> 00:43:59,036
ADDING BOILED MILK
AND SAFFRON MIX

1204
00:43:59,803 --> 00:44:02,906
THE MOTOR IS BACK ON

1205
00:44:03,607 --> 00:44:04,441
BOILING AGAIN

1206
00:44:04,508 --> 00:44:06,276
It goes back into the pan.

1207
00:44:06,343 --> 00:44:08,012
Is he making custard?

1208
00:44:08,078 --> 00:44:11,115
It's pastry cream, a basic French custard.

1209
00:44:11,181 --> 00:44:12,349
Pastry cream.

1210
00:44:12,416 --> 00:44:14,218
Hey, that looks nice.

1211
00:44:14,785 --> 00:44:16,286
-He'll use it later.
-Pastry cream.

1212
00:44:16,353 --> 00:44:18,022
You have ten minutes left.

1213
00:44:18,088 --> 00:44:19,123
What?

1214
00:44:19,189 --> 00:44:20,924
Time's flying. Already?

1215
00:44:20,991 --> 00:44:22,893
THIS IS BAD

1216
00:44:23,160 --> 00:44:25,396
UNLEASHING THE FAT CAT POWER

1217
00:44:25,462 --> 00:44:26,630
Argh.

1218
00:44:26,697 --> 00:44:29,900
If the yolk gets cooked,
he gets cooked too.

1219
00:44:29,967 --> 00:44:31,969
The moment the egg yolk
begins to form clumps,

1220
00:44:32,036 --> 00:44:35,039
it'll just taste like eggs.

1221
00:44:35,105 --> 00:44:37,007
That's why he's working hard on it.

1222
00:44:37,074 --> 00:44:38,142
It's a delicate process.

1223
00:44:38,208 --> 00:44:41,578
Jong-won has his eyes on you, Sung-jun.

1224
00:44:41,645 --> 00:44:43,947
-You should cool the butter.
-You're trying hard today.

1225
00:44:45,182 --> 00:44:46,650
A GRUMPY FAT CAT…

1226
00:44:46,717 --> 00:44:49,019
He clenches his teeth and whips.

1227
00:44:49,086 --> 00:44:50,521
Do not let it harden.

1228
00:44:50,587 --> 00:44:52,656
Is the texture all right
with the egg yolk?

1229
00:44:52,723 --> 00:44:54,258
Seven minutes left.

1230
00:44:54,324 --> 00:44:55,426
What? You must be kidding.

1231
00:44:56,126 --> 00:44:58,362
Yes, you have nine minutes left.

1232
00:44:58,429 --> 00:44:59,797
I was lying.

1233
00:44:59,863 --> 00:45:01,065
-I almost fell for it.
-He lied.

1234
00:45:01,131 --> 00:45:03,133
-I almost fell for it.
-That was a first.

1235
00:45:03,200 --> 00:45:05,469
-Bell pepper.
-Is the cream okay?

1236
00:45:05,536 --> 00:45:07,805
-It's good.
-It's good.

1237
00:45:08,572 --> 00:45:10,340
It turned out like custard.

1238
00:45:10,407 --> 00:45:11,241
VISCOSITY QUALIFIED

1239
00:45:11,308 --> 00:45:12,142
That looks good.

1240
00:45:12,710 --> 00:45:14,044
That was rough.

1241
00:45:14,111 --> 00:45:15,679
He's using Woo-jae's <i>tteok.</i>

1242
00:45:15,746 --> 00:45:17,781
-It's one of the requirements.
-Woo-jae's <i>tteok.</i>

1243
00:45:17,848 --> 00:45:21,452
-He mixes the red bean paste with cream.
-With that cream.

1244
00:45:21,518 --> 00:45:23,320
-They'll go well together.
-Red bean paste.

1245
00:45:23,654 --> 00:45:25,222
WHAT'S AGENT PET PIG UP TO?

1246
00:45:25,289 --> 00:45:27,858
That's another requirement, watermelon.

1247
00:45:27,925 --> 00:45:29,593
-It does have lots of seeds.
-I see.

1248
00:45:29,660 --> 00:45:31,628
There are too many seeds. I can't do this.

1249
00:45:32,029 --> 00:45:33,597
GIVES UP ON REMOVING THE SEEDS

1250
00:45:34,098 --> 00:45:36,233
2. CHOP CHERRY TOMATOES
AND WATERMELON INTO BITE SIZES

1251
00:45:36,300 --> 00:45:37,835
Do you eat watermelon seeds?

1252
00:45:37,901 --> 00:45:40,137
I get too lazy to remove them,
so yes, I do.

1253
00:45:40,204 --> 00:45:42,806
-He's adding something…
-What's that?

1254
00:45:42,873 --> 00:45:45,242
-Watermelon juice.
-Watermelon.

1255
00:45:45,309 --> 00:45:47,678
3. MIX WATERMELON JUICE, LEMON
JUICE, OLIVE OIL, HONEY, SUGAR

1256
00:45:47,745 --> 00:45:51,915
He's mixing watermelon juice
with olive oil, sugar, and salt.

1257
00:45:52,416 --> 00:45:54,351
PUT WATERMELON AND TOMATO
INTO A PLASTIC BAG

1258
00:45:54,418 --> 00:45:56,320
AND ADD WATERMELON DRESSING

1259
00:45:58,522 --> 00:46:01,091
WHAT'S THIS?

1260
00:46:01,658 --> 00:46:02,893
A vacuum machine.

1261
00:46:02,960 --> 00:46:05,129
He's trying to season it quickly.

1262
00:46:05,896 --> 00:46:08,966
He's boiling the Korean wild grape wine
your father made.

1263
00:46:09,032 --> 00:46:11,235
I see. Is he boiling it down?

1264
00:46:11,301 --> 00:46:13,904
Eel. He's using the eel now.

1265
00:46:13,971 --> 00:46:16,607
He's chopping the fish into large pieces.

1266
00:46:17,574 --> 00:46:21,779
-It'll now…
-He's boiling it in the wild grape wine.

1267
00:46:21,845 --> 00:46:24,181
He's boiling the eel down
in the wild grape wine.

1268
00:46:24,248 --> 00:46:26,884
Just like how you use
black raspberry wine.

1269
00:46:26,950 --> 00:46:28,919
-He added balsamic vinegar.
-Balsamic vinegar.

1270
00:46:28,986 --> 00:46:32,055
Just like how I made eel using balsamic
vinegar with Lee Young-ae's fridge.

1271
00:46:32,122 --> 00:46:34,792
-I remember that.
-It's similar to that.

1272
00:46:34,858 --> 00:46:36,894
Is he copying Chef Ho-young?

1273
00:46:37,928 --> 00:46:40,430
-He copies anyone he can.
-It's so hard.

1274
00:46:40,497 --> 00:46:41,498
Right.

1275
00:46:42,332 --> 00:46:43,333
Bell pepper.

1276
00:46:43,400 --> 00:46:46,403
He's chopping bell peppers
into thin slices.

1277
00:46:46,804 --> 00:46:47,638
YUM

1278
00:46:48,572 --> 00:46:51,375
That's the bell peppers Jong-won eats
as a late-night snack.

1279
00:46:51,441 --> 00:46:54,044
-Yes.
-I think he'll need a lot more.

1280
00:46:54,111 --> 00:46:55,646
He grabs a cucumber.

1281
00:46:55,712 --> 00:46:57,181
A must-use ingredient, cucumber.

1282
00:46:57,681 --> 00:46:59,483
4. REMOVE SEEDS,
CUT THE SKIN INTO THIN SLICES

1283
00:46:59,550 --> 00:47:02,519
-The veggie slices.
-The dish had thin slices too.

1284
00:47:02,586 --> 00:47:04,254
I think he'll form
some sort of shape later.

1285
00:47:04,321 --> 00:47:05,522
Nam-no grabs strawberries.

1286
00:47:06,156 --> 00:47:07,524
These are all requirements.

1287
00:47:08,292 --> 00:47:11,261
5. SLICE STRAWBERRIES INTO THIN
SLICES AND DRIZZLE OLIVE OIL AND SALT

1288
00:47:11,762 --> 00:47:12,729
HE GRABS A TORCH

1289
00:47:12,796 --> 00:47:14,464
-Are you broiling the strawberry?
-Yes.

1290
00:47:14,531 --> 00:47:16,900
-With a torch?
-Otherwise, it'll feel like a dessert.

1291
00:47:16,967 --> 00:47:18,535
What's that sauce? Sugar?

1292
00:47:18,602 --> 00:47:19,903
-Olive oil.
-Salt.

1293
00:47:19,970 --> 00:47:22,172
-Salt on strawberries?
-And olive oil.

1294
00:47:22,239 --> 00:47:23,340
Sam's olive oil.

1295
00:47:23,407 --> 00:47:25,175
The olive oil from Sam's farm.

1296
00:47:25,242 --> 00:47:27,044
Do strawberries go well with olive oil?

1297
00:47:27,110 --> 00:47:29,079
-Have you ever had toasted strawberries?
-No.

1298
00:47:29,146 --> 00:47:30,347
BROILING THEM SEEMS UNFAMILIAR

1299
00:47:30,848 --> 00:47:32,282
GRABS THE BOILED EGGS

1300
00:47:32,349 --> 00:47:35,919
He's taking out the boiled eggs.

1301
00:47:35,986 --> 00:47:37,187
One of them cracked.

1302
00:47:37,254 --> 00:47:39,022
-It won't matter.
-I see.

1303
00:47:39,456 --> 00:47:44,161
GRABS THE TTEOK AND EEL
HE HAD BEEN TOASTING

1304
00:47:44,228 --> 00:47:46,129
PEELING BOILED EGGS

1305
00:47:46,196 --> 00:47:47,531
I love boiled eggs.

1306
00:47:47,598 --> 00:47:49,099
He likes boiled eggs.

1307
00:47:49,166 --> 00:47:51,335
He's blending the eggs anyway.

1308
00:47:51,401 --> 00:47:53,437
Then it's fine.
It doesn't matter if it's cracked.

1309
00:47:53,503 --> 00:47:56,173
-This is bad.
-One of the requirements, watermelon.

1310
00:47:56,240 --> 00:47:57,474
THIRD REQUIREMENT: WATERMELON

1311
00:47:57,541 --> 00:47:59,543
5. CHOP WATERMELON TO SMALL
PIECES AND ROAST WITH SUGAR

1312
00:47:59,610 --> 00:48:01,812
Sung-jun grabs a cucumber now.

1313
00:48:01,879 --> 00:48:03,547
He's adding apple to the cucumber.

1314
00:48:03,614 --> 00:48:05,082
MINI CUCUMBER AND APPLE

1315
00:48:05,148 --> 00:48:07,017
Five minutes and thirty seconds.

1316
00:48:07,084 --> 00:48:08,785
-No!
-What do you mean?

1317
00:48:08,852 --> 00:48:10,854
-Somebody, stop the time.
-It'll be five minutes soon.

1318
00:48:10,921 --> 00:48:13,690
-You have 5 minutes and 30 seconds.
-Yes, 30 seconds.

1319
00:48:13,757 --> 00:48:15,158
He has a long way to go.

1320
00:48:15,225 --> 00:48:16,326
Stop the time.

1321
00:48:16,827 --> 00:48:18,395
JULIENNING QUICKLY

1322
00:48:18,462 --> 00:48:21,999
-He's julienning the cucumber.
-Into thin slices.

1323
00:48:22,065 --> 00:48:23,066
To do what?

1324
00:48:23,133 --> 00:48:25,002
-Five minutes.
-Please report from the kitchen.

1325
00:48:25,068 --> 00:48:27,004
-Five minutes remain.
-All right, then.

1326
00:48:27,070 --> 00:48:29,640
You must use
all five mandatory ingredients.

1327
00:48:29,706 --> 00:48:30,807
You're using eel,

1328
00:48:30,874 --> 00:48:32,509
watermelon,

1329
00:48:32,576 --> 00:48:34,611
and of course, cucumber.

1330
00:48:34,678 --> 00:48:36,813
-Olive oil!
-Olive oil!

1331
00:48:36,880 --> 00:48:38,081
-Olive oil!
-I'm a thief!

1332
00:48:38,148 --> 00:48:41,585
-The progress seems…
-I need it! Give it back.

1333
00:48:41,652 --> 00:48:43,553
BUSY ADDING WHOLE GRAIN MUSTARD

1334
00:48:44,054 --> 00:48:45,756
BURGLAR ALARM GOES OFF

1335
00:48:45,822 --> 00:48:47,424
RUNS OVER TO CATCH THE THIEF

1336
00:48:47,491 --> 00:48:49,226
Hurry up. How much do you need?

1337
00:48:49,293 --> 00:48:50,961
HAD TO RETURN IT IN 3 SECONDS

1338
00:48:51,028 --> 00:48:52,930
I see. The olive oil.

1339
00:48:52,996 --> 00:48:54,831
What's this process?

1340
00:48:54,898 --> 00:48:57,034
-It looks good.
-It's called sauce gribiche.

1341
00:48:57,100 --> 00:49:00,037
It's pretty much mayonnaise
made with boiled eggs.

1342
00:49:00,103 --> 00:49:01,371
A Western sauce, so let me try this.

1343
00:49:01,438 --> 00:49:03,473
-It's called sauce gribiche.
-Yes, gribiche.

1344
00:49:03,540 --> 00:49:05,275
-Can I try this, then?
-One second.

1345
00:49:05,342 --> 00:49:06,877
He's seasoning the sauce.

1346
00:49:06,944 --> 00:49:08,378
Sauce gribiche.

1347
00:49:08,445 --> 00:49:09,279
Yum!

1348
00:49:09,346 --> 00:49:12,649
Is he Eatanic Maniac or just a maniac?

1349
00:49:12,716 --> 00:49:14,351
It's too salty!

1350
00:49:14,418 --> 00:49:15,852
-It's salty.
-Really?

1351
00:49:15,919 --> 00:49:17,554
-No way. Really?
-Yes.

1352
00:49:17,621 --> 00:49:19,690
-He means it.
-It's true.

1353
00:49:19,756 --> 00:49:22,125
Yes, it's salty. It's too salty.

1354
00:49:22,192 --> 00:49:23,527
Too much mustard?

1355
00:49:23,593 --> 00:49:25,395
Olive oil from Sam Kim.

1356
00:49:25,462 --> 00:49:27,864
6. SEASON APPLE CUCUMBER SALAD
WITH SALT AND PEPPER

1357
00:49:28,298 --> 00:49:30,767
HIS NEXT ULTIMATE MOVE

1358
00:49:30,834 --> 00:49:33,303
-That's what Jong-won does.
-Three knives!

1359
00:49:33,370 --> 00:49:35,439
-That's what Jong-won does.
-Three knives!

1360
00:49:36,440 --> 00:49:38,976
-That's what Jong-won does.
-Three knives!

1361
00:49:39,643 --> 00:49:41,378
THE THREE SHORT'N'FAT KNIVES

1362
00:49:41,445 --> 00:49:43,046
-Three knives?
-Three.

1363
00:49:43,347 --> 00:49:44,781
CLATTER

1364
00:49:44,848 --> 00:49:46,416
-He's using three knives.
-Sorry, Mom!

1365
00:49:47,250 --> 00:49:48,852
MOM, THIS WILL SURELY GO VIRAL

1366
00:49:48,919 --> 00:49:50,420
Sung-jun.

1367
00:49:51,121 --> 00:49:52,656
The thing is,

1368
00:49:52,723 --> 00:49:55,692
there aren't a lot of walnut pieces
left on the board.

1369
00:49:55,759 --> 00:49:57,127
Everything is on the floor.

1370
00:49:57,194 --> 00:49:58,595
They're all over the floor.

1371
00:49:58,662 --> 00:50:00,731
-That was meaningless.
-Meaningless.

1372
00:50:00,797 --> 00:50:02,966
Try that custard cream he made.

1373
00:50:03,033 --> 00:50:04,534
He worked very hard on this.

1374
00:50:04,601 --> 00:50:06,470
It looks pretty thick.

1375
00:50:06,536 --> 00:50:08,005
HOW'S THE CREAM HE WORKED HARD ON?

1376
00:50:08,071 --> 00:50:11,608
Does it taste like something
even Sung-jun's mother will be happy with?

1377
00:50:11,675 --> 00:50:12,943
…be happy with?

1378
00:50:13,010 --> 00:50:14,745
His mother will love it!

1379
00:50:16,146 --> 00:50:17,180
This is so good.

1380
00:50:17,247 --> 00:50:19,116
Is it supposed to be this thick?

1381
00:50:19,182 --> 00:50:20,350
It probably is. He used starch.

1382
00:50:20,417 --> 00:50:22,019
The cream doesn't melt away.

1383
00:50:22,085 --> 00:50:25,222
The cream doesn't just melt away.
It's a bit thick.

1384
00:50:26,056 --> 00:50:27,224
CHECKING THE TIME IN GOOD VIBES

1385
00:50:27,290 --> 00:50:30,427
Sung-jun checks for time.
There are 2 minutes and 17 seconds left.

1386
00:50:30,494 --> 00:50:32,129
THE NEXT GOOD VIBES MOVE

1387
00:50:32,195 --> 00:50:34,431
-Right now, Nam-no is…
-Fwip!

1388
00:50:35,699 --> 00:50:36,666
SHORT'N'FAT TOWEL TWIRL

1389
00:50:36,733 --> 00:50:38,702
YOU GOT SHORT LIMBS, SUNG-JUN…

1390
00:50:38,769 --> 00:50:41,004
-He's grilling eel.
-The tart shells.

1391
00:50:41,071 --> 00:50:43,607
Those. Do those look okay?

1392
00:50:43,673 --> 00:50:45,242
I doubt it's crispy.

1393
00:50:45,308 --> 00:50:48,111
-Does it look okay?
-At least it maintained its shape.

1394
00:50:48,712 --> 00:50:50,614
The tart shells. How are they?

1395
00:50:50,680 --> 00:50:52,315
-They look good.
-Do they?

1396
00:50:52,516 --> 00:50:53,617
THE TART SHELLS LOOK NICE

1397
00:50:53,683 --> 00:50:55,685
The tart shells look nice.

1398
00:50:55,752 --> 00:50:57,587
Put them together now! Hurry up!

1399
00:50:57,654 --> 00:50:59,890
You only have a minute and 30 seconds!

1400
00:50:59,956 --> 00:51:01,158
What are you waiting for?

1401
00:51:01,224 --> 00:51:03,260
You're supposed to be chefs!

1402
00:51:03,927 --> 00:51:04,761
Go to sleep.

1403
00:51:04,828 --> 00:51:06,997
THE BEAUTIFUL SPY TAKES HIM DOWN

1404
00:51:07,397 --> 00:51:09,466
HE'S FINALLY QUIET…

1405
00:51:10,033 --> 00:51:13,904
PLATING THE VACUUM-SEALED
TOMATO AND WATERMELON

1406
00:51:14,171 --> 00:51:15,906
TOP WITH TOASTED WOO-JAE'S TTEOK!

1407
00:51:16,106 --> 00:51:17,941
FINISHING OFF
WITH BROILED STRAWBERRY

1408
00:51:18,008 --> 00:51:19,743
Is this done?

1409
00:51:19,810 --> 00:51:21,178
STRAWBERRY, TTEOK, WATERMELON

1410
00:51:21,878 --> 00:51:23,814
FOLLOWED BY THE NEXT DISH!

1411
00:51:23,880 --> 00:51:25,415
You need the eel.

1412
00:51:25,482 --> 00:51:26,850
It's so good for you.

1413
00:51:26,917 --> 00:51:28,018
ON TOP OF SAUCE GRIBICHE

1414
00:51:28,085 --> 00:51:31,088
-The eel goes between the sauce.
-It looks good.

1415
00:51:31,588 --> 00:51:33,190
PILING CHOPPED CUCUMBER
AND BELL PEPPER ON IT

1416
00:51:33,256 --> 00:51:36,593
My gosh! How do you do this?

1417
00:51:36,660 --> 00:51:38,762
-This?
-Just pile them up somehow.

1418
00:51:38,829 --> 00:51:40,697
-Pile everything on it.
-Make it look similar.

1419
00:51:40,764 --> 00:51:43,600
He puts the eel in the center
and piles the veggies on top.

1420
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:46,069
AGENT FAT CAT BEGINS
TO PLATE HIS FOOD TOO

1421
00:51:46,369 --> 00:51:49,106
APPLE CUCUMBER SALAD
ON TOP OF THE EEL

1422
00:51:50,173 --> 00:51:52,509
THE FIRST TART IS READY

1423
00:51:52,576 --> 00:51:53,910
EEL, MINI CUCUMBER

1424
00:51:54,111 --> 00:51:55,145
NEXT, PASTRY CREAM

1425
00:51:55,212 --> 00:51:58,181
Sung-jun looks busy. He is in a rush.

1426
00:51:58,248 --> 00:51:59,616
Thirty seconds.

1427
00:52:00,350 --> 00:52:03,186
TOPPED WITH PREPPED STRAWBERRY

1428
00:52:03,987 --> 00:52:05,555
AND DICED WATERMELON!

1429
00:52:05,622 --> 00:52:08,859
-You don't have more time! It's over!
-Ten.

1430
00:52:09,226 --> 00:52:11,661
AGENT PET PIG ADDS HIS KICK!

1431
00:52:12,028 --> 00:52:13,697
THE WALNUT SAUCE
HE WORKED HARD ON

1432
00:52:13,930 --> 00:52:14,965
WHAT'S AGENT FAT CAT'S KICK?

1433
00:52:15,265 --> 00:52:16,800
LASTLY, DECORATE WITH GOLD DUST

1434
00:52:16,867 --> 00:52:18,869
-Ring the bell!
-Time's up!

1435
00:52:18,935 --> 00:52:20,837
-Ring the bell!
-Time's up!

1436
00:52:20,904 --> 00:52:22,973
-Ring the bell!
-Ring the bell!

1437
00:52:23,039 --> 00:52:24,908
-Goodness.
-Ring the bell!

1438
00:52:24,975 --> 00:52:26,543
AGENT FAT CAT FINISHES TOO

1439
00:52:26,610 --> 00:52:29,346
-You made it look similar.
-Yes, it looks like it.

1440
00:52:29,412 --> 00:52:31,114
-What about the cooked watermelon?
-It's on top of that.

1441
00:52:31,181 --> 00:52:33,483
FIVE-INGREDIENT MISSION, CLEAR

1442
00:52:33,550 --> 00:52:35,285
The dishes are finished.

1443
00:52:35,352 --> 00:52:37,454
IT WAS POSSIBLE
WITHIN 15 MINUTES

1444
00:52:37,521 --> 00:52:39,222
How did you do this?

1445
00:52:39,289 --> 00:52:40,891
THE AGENTS ARE EXHAUSTED

1446
00:52:40,957 --> 00:52:46,229
And now, we have the dishes
made just for Chef Jong-won.

1447
00:52:46,296 --> 00:52:47,464
You made it look similar.

1448
00:52:47,531 --> 00:52:50,167
That was
Mission Son-Possible: Mirror Match.

1449
00:52:50,233 --> 00:52:52,235
I always cooked for the guests,

1450
00:52:52,302 --> 00:52:55,138
so it was my first time
having the chefs cook for me.

1451
00:52:55,205 --> 00:52:56,206
It was very touching,

1452
00:52:56,273 --> 00:52:58,508
and I was also nervous
as I watched them cook.

1453
00:52:58,575 --> 00:53:00,544
Chef Nam-no finished first,

1454
00:53:00,610 --> 00:53:02,679
so please try his dishes first.

1455
00:53:02,746 --> 00:53:04,114
Sit down. You're the guest.

1456
00:53:04,181 --> 00:53:06,016
You should stay seated.

1457
00:53:06,283 --> 00:53:08,485
A REFRESHING AND SWEET APPETIZER
TO STIMULATE YOUR PALATE

1458
00:53:09,486 --> 00:53:13,023
CRUNCHY VEGGIES,
SOFT EGG SAUCE, AND EEL

1459
00:53:14,124 --> 00:53:18,094
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S
EATANIC MANIAC

1460
00:53:18,161 --> 00:53:21,598
When you visit Eatanic Garden
or L’Amant Secret,

1461
00:53:21,665 --> 00:53:24,334
he always serves the main sauce

1462
00:53:24,401 --> 00:53:25,569
with a smile in his eyes.

1463
00:53:25,635 --> 00:53:27,037
With a smile in my eyes?

1464
00:53:27,103 --> 00:53:29,673
-May I try doing that?
-With a smile in his eyes?

1465
00:53:30,240 --> 00:53:31,741
You got it all wrong.

1466
00:53:31,808 --> 00:53:33,310
You two are built different.

1467
00:53:33,376 --> 00:53:34,611
You need to think wisely

1468
00:53:34,678 --> 00:53:36,112
because that might make me mad.

1469
00:53:36,546 --> 00:53:38,215
CAN YOU HANDLE IT?

1470
00:53:38,281 --> 00:53:39,382
Well, you know,

1471
00:53:40,450 --> 00:53:42,285
there was one thing I missed.

1472
00:53:42,352 --> 00:53:44,054
May I ask Sung-jun for his understanding?

1473
00:53:44,120 --> 00:53:45,288
You left something out again?

1474
00:53:45,355 --> 00:53:48,658
You'll need permission from Chef Sung-jun.

1475
00:53:48,725 --> 00:53:50,427
I forgot to add the black beans.

1476
00:53:50,961 --> 00:53:52,028
THE BREADCRUMB SUBSTITUTE

1477
00:53:52,095 --> 00:53:54,798
-You were grinding it.
-You worked hard on it.

1478
00:53:54,864 --> 00:53:56,533
In my case,

1479
00:53:56,600 --> 00:53:59,769
-I do come with a bit of a kind heart.
-Okay.

1480
00:53:59,836 --> 00:54:01,037
I'll let him do it.

1481
00:54:01,104 --> 00:54:02,973
The good vibes have a big heart.

1482
00:54:03,039 --> 00:54:05,475
-All right, then.
-He's opening up.

1483
00:54:05,542 --> 00:54:08,044
Chef Nam-no will come by
and sprinkle some black bean powder.

1484
00:54:08,111 --> 00:54:10,280
But you need to show a good smile.

1485
00:54:10,347 --> 00:54:12,282
Show a good smile.

1486
00:54:12,349 --> 00:54:13,416
That's not how Jong-won smiles!

1487
00:54:14,017 --> 00:54:16,186
-That's not how he smiles!
-I'm sorry.

1488
00:54:16,253 --> 00:54:18,221
I'm starting to feel unpleasant.

1489
00:54:18,288 --> 00:54:20,857
-Try not to make him mad.
-Are you mocking him?

1490
00:54:20,924 --> 00:54:23,360
I always thought he looked the coolest
when he comes and asks,

1491
00:54:23,426 --> 00:54:24,461
"Did you enjoy your meal?"

1492
00:54:24,527 --> 00:54:26,896
Can you recreate the experience
for Jong-won?

1493
00:54:26,963 --> 00:54:28,565
Think of him as your customer.

1494
00:54:28,632 --> 00:54:29,833
Did you enjoy your meal?

1495
00:54:31,534 --> 00:54:32,369
That's how he does it?

1496
00:54:33,603 --> 00:54:35,305
He's mocking me!

1497
00:54:35,372 --> 00:54:37,107
"Did you enjoy your meal?"

1498
00:54:37,173 --> 00:54:38,275
I'll take some points off.

1499
00:54:38,341 --> 00:54:40,577
-Are you serious?
-I'm kidding.

1500
00:54:40,644 --> 00:54:44,481
Nam-no reinterpreted the pine nut dish
Jong-won serves

1501
00:54:44,547 --> 00:54:48,351
at his Korean cuisine restaurant.

1502
00:54:48,418 --> 00:54:52,422
-And he broiled the strawberries earlier.
-He did.

1503
00:54:52,489 --> 00:54:53,356
I'll try it.

1504
00:54:53,423 --> 00:54:54,557
FINALLY, THE FIRST BITE

1505
00:54:54,624 --> 00:54:56,926
That's not the main dish, but the salad.

1506
00:54:57,527 --> 00:54:59,796
I'll try it with the <i>tteok.</i>

1507
00:55:00,764 --> 00:55:02,532
It's difficult to eat.

1508
00:55:02,599 --> 00:55:03,667
OH, NO…

1509
00:55:03,733 --> 00:55:04,968
The pieces are too big.

1510
00:55:05,035 --> 00:55:08,238
-We were surprised.
-Check if you got something on your shirt.

1511
00:55:08,305 --> 00:55:10,273
You should've made
the watermelon pieces smaller.

1512
00:55:10,340 --> 00:55:12,709
Yes, or used a bigger bowl.

1513
00:55:12,776 --> 00:55:14,411
LAUGHING

1514
00:55:14,477 --> 00:55:15,745
I was catering to my bite.

1515
00:55:15,812 --> 00:55:17,380
Or given him a bigger spoon.

1516
00:55:17,447 --> 00:55:19,115
-Right?
-Huh?

1517
00:55:19,182 --> 00:55:21,418
-I like this mix.
-You do?

1518
00:55:21,484 --> 00:55:23,520
What does broiled strawberry taste like?

1519
00:55:23,586 --> 00:55:28,124
Broiling the strawberry
turns its dessert-like flavor into a dish.

1520
00:55:28,358 --> 00:55:30,460
STRAWBERRY AND WATERMELON

1521
00:55:30,960 --> 00:55:32,996
STARTING TO DIG IN

1522
00:55:33,063 --> 00:55:35,065
-It must be good.
-He tries a piece of <i>tteok.</i>

1523
00:55:35,131 --> 00:55:36,866
You covered it with balsamic sauce,
then toasted it.

1524
00:55:36,933 --> 00:55:37,967
Yes.

1525
00:55:38,034 --> 00:55:40,103
I used <i>tteok</i> instead of cheese,

1526
00:55:40,170 --> 00:55:42,772
accompanied by some watermelon,

1527
00:55:42,839 --> 00:55:46,643
to make it feel like tomato and cheese
in balsamic sauce.

1528
00:55:46,710 --> 00:55:49,879
I feel like I'm somewhere in Ikseon-dong,

1529
00:55:50,447 --> 00:55:51,781
eating a bowl

1530
00:55:52,582 --> 00:55:54,384
of warm red bean <i>bingsu</i> without ice.

1531
00:55:54,451 --> 00:55:56,786
-Warm red bean <i>bingsu</i> without ice?
-Warm red bean <i>bingsu?</i>

1532
00:55:56,853 --> 00:55:58,555
Is that a good thing?

1533
00:55:58,621 --> 00:55:59,723
You mean, red bean porridge?

1534
00:55:59,789 --> 00:56:02,058
The broiled strawberry plays a huge role.

1535
00:56:02,125 --> 00:56:03,360
I see. The broiled strawberry.

1536
00:56:03,426 --> 00:56:04,327
STRAWBERRY PRINCE APPROVES

1537
00:56:04,394 --> 00:56:05,795
It must be good.

1538
00:56:05,862 --> 00:56:09,432
At first, I thought
it'd only be sweet like dessert.

1539
00:56:09,499 --> 00:56:11,501
But it was a refreshing appetizer.

1540
00:56:11,568 --> 00:56:12,569
Thank you.

1541
00:56:12,635 --> 00:56:15,805
But this is it.
This dish will decide everything.

1542
00:56:15,872 --> 00:56:18,007
-It's the main dish.
-That's the main dish.

1543
00:56:18,074 --> 00:56:20,877
Please have it
with the egg sauce on the inside,

1544
00:56:20,944 --> 00:56:22,979
and you must eat it with the veggies.

1545
00:56:23,046 --> 00:56:26,750
-The mayo sauce.
-And the sauce that came with a smile.

1546
00:56:26,816 --> 00:56:28,785
Of course. Yes.

1547
00:56:28,852 --> 00:56:31,454
Let's see if the dish
is worthy of his smile.

1548
00:56:32,122 --> 00:56:33,289
GLARING

1549
00:56:34,424 --> 00:56:35,625
One look at Nam-no.

1550
00:56:35,692 --> 00:56:39,596
That was the eel he had toasted.

1551
00:56:39,662 --> 00:56:42,632
-Mmm.
-Some veggies, the sauce, and the eel.

1552
00:56:42,699 --> 00:56:43,633
A LOOK

1553
00:56:44,167 --> 00:56:45,301
A DOUBLE TAKE

1554
00:56:45,368 --> 00:56:47,604
-He keeps looking.
-A smile in his eyes.

1555
00:56:47,670 --> 00:56:49,172
Is he smiling with his eyes?

1556
00:56:49,439 --> 00:56:51,674
HAPPY PIG, SAD FAT CAT

1557
00:56:51,908 --> 00:56:52,909
JUMPY

1558
00:56:52,976 --> 00:56:54,444
He's showing his smile.

1559
00:56:54,711 --> 00:56:56,179
YAY, HEHEHE

1560
00:56:56,246 --> 00:56:58,481
He really seems like a pet pig.

1561
00:56:59,883 --> 00:57:03,119
It tastes like a very luxurious egg salad.

1562
00:57:03,186 --> 00:57:05,488
It's like the egg salad your mom makes,

1563
00:57:05,555 --> 00:57:06,923
but served with eel.

1564
00:57:06,990 --> 00:57:08,758
With the added crunchiness of bell pepper,

1565
00:57:08,825 --> 00:57:10,126
it's so good.

1566
00:57:10,193 --> 00:57:11,428
-He says it's so good.
-"So good."

1567
00:57:11,494 --> 00:57:12,996
An emergency for Sung-jun.

1568
00:57:13,163 --> 00:57:14,564
HAPPY NAM-NO

1569
00:57:14,631 --> 00:57:16,299
Well, you must bring out your strengths.

1570
00:57:16,366 --> 00:57:18,668
Nam-no continues to watch him eat
with a smile in his eyes.

1571
00:57:18,735 --> 00:57:20,403
TREMBLE

1572
00:57:21,037 --> 00:57:23,039
What if he…

1573
00:57:23,106 --> 00:57:26,943
He's turning into a whole
different character. It's hard to follow.

1574
00:57:27,010 --> 00:57:28,144
HALF OF IT IS GONE ALREADY

1575
00:57:28,211 --> 00:57:29,846
-You're enjoying it a lot.
-It's so good.

1576
00:57:29,913 --> 00:57:31,481
Is it that good?

1577
00:57:31,548 --> 00:57:35,618
Also, the black beans he sprinkled
with that smile adds a nice texture.

1578
00:57:36,386 --> 00:57:39,756
-It was a good call.
-I didn't think he'd need it,

1579
00:57:39,823 --> 00:57:40,857
but that's a nice kick.

1580
00:57:40,924 --> 00:57:42,325
It was for the texture.

1581
00:57:42,392 --> 00:57:46,029
-Sung-jun should've stopped him.
-Good job.

1582
00:57:46,095 --> 00:57:48,431
-He should've said no.
-He allowed this

1583
00:57:48,498 --> 00:57:50,266
and let it become a kick.

1584
00:57:50,934 --> 00:57:51,768
MMM

1585
00:57:51,835 --> 00:57:53,570
-Is the eel cooked nicely?
-It is.

1586
00:57:53,636 --> 00:57:54,604
My master.

1587
00:57:54,671 --> 00:57:56,039
It goes well with the walnut.

1588
00:57:56,105 --> 00:57:58,341
It should've been made with pine nuts,

1589
00:57:58,408 --> 00:57:59,976
but he had to resort to walnuts.

1590
00:58:00,043 --> 00:58:03,480
I love a touch of a acidity,
and he added that in here,

1591
00:58:03,546 --> 00:58:05,048
so the overall balance is great.

1592
00:58:05,114 --> 00:58:07,617
-Things are looking up for Nam-no.
-Yes.

1593
00:58:07,684 --> 00:58:10,954
-I can reach it.
-Next, Chef Kwon Sung-jun's dish,

1594
00:58:11,020 --> 00:58:14,991
Your Son's Not as Hot as Jong-won,
Sorry Mom's Tart.

1595
00:58:15,258 --> 00:58:17,560
THE MAIN TART
WITH CUCUMBER, APPLE, AND EEL

1596
00:58:18,695 --> 00:58:21,431
AND A FRUIT TART WITH THICK PASTRY
CREAM MADE FROM SCRATCH

1597
00:58:22,131 --> 00:58:25,969
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S YOUR SON'S NOT
AS HOT AS JONG-WON, SORRY MOM'S TART

1598
00:58:26,035 --> 00:58:28,037
Sorry Mom's Tart.

1599
00:58:28,104 --> 00:58:29,305
It's Sorry Mom's Tart.

1600
00:58:29,372 --> 00:58:32,242
Please try the eel, cucumber,
and apple tart first.

1601
00:58:32,308 --> 00:58:33,877
You topped it with too much gold.

1602
00:58:33,943 --> 00:58:35,512
Do people usually use that much?

1603
00:58:35,578 --> 00:58:37,347
You might get heavy metal poisoning.

1604
00:58:37,413 --> 00:58:40,650
-The gold price went up, so…
-The gold price has skyrocketed.

1605
00:58:40,717 --> 00:58:43,953
Chef Sung-jun served the dish
on the perfect plate to go with it.

1606
00:58:44,020 --> 00:58:46,155
-I've been enjoying it with my eyes.
-You're right.

1607
00:58:46,222 --> 00:58:49,259
He's taking his time
to enjoy it with his eyes.

1608
00:58:49,325 --> 00:58:50,894
-Should he eat it in a bite?
-I'll try it.

1609
00:58:51,461 --> 00:58:54,264
Chef Sung-jun used eel in this tart.

1610
00:58:54,797 --> 00:58:55,632
IN ONE BITE

1611
00:58:55,698 --> 00:58:56,900
-In one bite.
-In one bite?

1612
00:58:59,802 --> 00:59:00,670
MMM!

1613
00:59:00,737 --> 00:59:02,772
Jong-won said he liked acidity.

1614
00:59:02,839 --> 00:59:05,975
He braised the eel
in wild grape wine and balsamic vinegar.

1615
00:59:06,042 --> 00:59:10,446
It was made with cucumber, eel, and…

1616
00:59:10,513 --> 00:59:11,714
Wow.

1617
00:59:11,781 --> 00:59:13,850
WHAT DOES HE MEAN BY THAT?

1618
00:59:13,917 --> 00:59:16,386
-He looks serious.
-He's deep in thought.

1619
00:59:16,619 --> 00:59:17,620
NERVOUS

1620
00:59:17,687 --> 00:59:18,988
GULP

1621
00:59:19,055 --> 00:59:23,493
Actually, eel and cucumber
are a great mix,

1622
00:59:23,560 --> 00:59:26,796
so I thought
he might have taken an easier approach.

1623
00:59:26,863 --> 00:59:29,299
But the way he used alcohol
to add acidity to this dish

1624
00:59:29,365 --> 00:59:30,867
brought out many more flavors.

1625
00:59:30,934 --> 00:59:32,068
THE WILD GRAPE WINE ADDED FLAVOR

1626
00:59:32,135 --> 00:59:35,238
It's like eating
a very classy eel sandwich.

1627
00:59:35,305 --> 00:59:37,273
-An eel sandwich.
-An eel sandwich.

1628
00:59:37,340 --> 00:59:40,243
Sung-jun made something
right up Jong-won's alley.

1629
00:59:40,310 --> 00:59:41,678
That was a success.

1630
00:59:43,479 --> 00:59:45,315
-The next one.
-That one

1631
00:59:45,381 --> 00:59:48,551
was made with pastry cream
mixed with a touch of saffron,

1632
00:59:48,618 --> 00:59:51,588
topped with strawberry
and slightly caramelized watermelon.

1633
00:59:51,654 --> 00:59:53,456
-These tiny pieces?
-Yes.

1634
00:59:53,523 --> 00:59:54,357
They're the toppings.

1635
00:59:54,424 --> 00:59:58,661
May I try just the watermelon?
I love how pretty the color is.

1636
00:59:58,728 --> 00:59:59,729
Yes, sure.

1637
00:59:59,796 --> 01:00:01,097
Can he try it separately?

1638
01:00:01,164 --> 01:00:03,967
-Should I eat it together?
-That's better, balance-wise.

1639
01:00:04,033 --> 01:00:06,436
The fridge owner wanted
to try it on its own,

1640
01:00:06,502 --> 01:00:07,470
but you stopped him.

1641
01:00:07,537 --> 01:00:08,972
-Did it go wrong?
-No.

1642
01:00:09,038 --> 01:00:10,340
Try it together. It'll taste good.

1643
01:00:10,406 --> 01:00:12,342
EXAMINES CLOSELY

1644
01:00:12,408 --> 01:00:14,477
First, he gives a good look at it.

1645
01:00:15,445 --> 01:00:17,614
-Strawberry…
-There was a heart.

1646
01:00:17,680 --> 01:00:19,515
-I see.
-It was underneath the tart.

1647
01:00:19,582 --> 01:00:21,117
I like these little details.

1648
01:00:21,184 --> 01:00:23,252
-Was it intentional?
-My hidden feelings.

1649
01:00:23,319 --> 01:00:25,755
-That was his heart.
-Tugging at his heartstrings.

1650
01:00:25,822 --> 01:00:27,957
Do not let something like that
sway your decision.

1651
01:00:28,524 --> 01:00:31,260
WILL HE SHAKE JONG-WON'S HEART
WITH THE TASTE TOO?

1652
01:00:31,694 --> 01:00:33,096
A FULL BITE

1653
01:00:33,162 --> 01:00:34,797
He knew what Sung-jun had intended,

1654
01:00:34,864 --> 01:00:36,699
so he had everything in one bite.

1655
01:00:36,766 --> 01:00:39,035
That was too big.
His mouth isn't that huge.

1656
01:00:39,102 --> 01:00:40,403
No, he eats well.

1657
01:00:40,470 --> 01:00:43,206
He's savoring every flavor
with a serious face.

1658
01:00:43,272 --> 01:00:44,374
TILTING HEAD

1659
01:00:44,440 --> 01:00:45,308
Hmm?

1660
01:00:45,375 --> 01:00:46,476
-A head tilt?
-A head tilt?

1661
01:00:46,542 --> 01:00:47,844
That was unexpected.

1662
01:00:47,910 --> 01:00:49,278
What does he mean by this?

1663
01:00:49,345 --> 01:00:50,580
What does it mean?

1664
01:00:50,647 --> 01:00:52,548
-It can't be bad.
-It's an emergency.

1665
01:00:52,615 --> 01:00:53,583
It's an emergency.

1666
01:00:53,650 --> 01:00:54,951
It's an emergency, Sung-jun.

1667
01:00:55,018 --> 01:00:57,620
-Wee-oo, wee-oo.
-What is it?

1668
01:00:57,687 --> 01:00:58,888
It's the saffron.

1669
01:00:58,955 --> 01:00:59,889
Saffron?

1670
01:00:59,956 --> 01:01:03,126
I wasn't sure
if it would be suitable for dessert.

1671
01:01:03,192 --> 01:01:04,661
-Yes?
-Usually,

1672
01:01:04,727 --> 01:01:06,863
-it's used for dishes, not desserts.
-Right.

1673
01:01:06,929 --> 01:01:09,532
It seems he used only
a tiny bit of saffron,

1674
01:01:09,599 --> 01:01:11,134
and the subtle fragrance

1675
01:01:11,200 --> 01:01:13,670
bring out the flavor toward the end.

1676
01:01:13,736 --> 01:01:15,805
-I knew he'd notice.
-So you enjoyed it until the end.

1677
01:01:15,872 --> 01:01:18,241
That kind of flavor was unexpected.

1678
01:01:18,307 --> 01:01:20,143
-This is good.
-He kept wondering

1679
01:01:20,209 --> 01:01:22,812
why he used saffron
and continued to chew on it.

1680
01:01:22,879 --> 01:01:25,148
-He even takes the last piece.
-It must be good.

1681
01:01:25,214 --> 01:01:26,349
He left a piece of watermelon.

1682
01:01:26,416 --> 01:01:29,185
-He said no, so I wanted to try it later.
-To try it separately.

1683
01:01:29,252 --> 01:01:32,522
<i>-It didn't just fall off?</i>
<i>-No, he left it out.</i>

1684
01:01:32,588 --> 01:01:34,123
It was intentional.

1685
01:01:34,190 --> 01:01:36,092
This had unexpected flavors,

1686
01:01:36,159 --> 01:01:37,293
and I loved the harmony.

1687
01:01:37,360 --> 01:01:38,828
Like a breaking ball.

1688
01:01:38,895 --> 01:01:40,897
It's time to decide.

1689
01:01:40,963 --> 01:01:42,298
Please make a decision.

1690
01:01:42,365 --> 01:01:44,167
THE MOMENT OF TRUTH

1691
01:01:44,233 --> 01:01:47,103
-This is it.
-Without any personal feelings.

1692
01:01:47,170 --> 01:01:49,138
-Whose heart will he break?
-Yes, really.

1693
01:01:49,205 --> 01:01:51,140
I'm already heartbroken.

1694
01:01:51,207 --> 01:01:53,342
<i>Press one for Yoon Nam-no</i>

1695
01:01:53,409 --> 01:01:55,044
<i>and two for Kwon Sung-jun.</i>

1696
01:01:56,212 --> 01:01:59,048
This will be an objective decision
made as a chef.

1697
01:01:59,115 --> 01:02:01,084
And by a chef with double Michelin stars.

1698
01:02:01,150 --> 01:02:03,786
They're getting seriously evaluated
by the dishes they made.

1699
01:02:04,253 --> 01:02:05,388
LOTS OF PRESSURE

1700
01:02:05,455 --> 01:02:06,689
If you think about it…

1701
01:02:06,756 --> 01:02:08,991
Why are you making this even harder?

1702
01:02:09,058 --> 01:02:12,361
This is a round they played
with their pride as a chef at stake.

1703
01:02:12,428 --> 01:02:14,897
-Yes.
-It's a whole different matter.

1704
01:02:14,964 --> 01:02:19,001
Will it be the pet pig or the fat cat?

1705
01:02:19,068 --> 01:02:22,171
I really want to win this round.

1706
01:02:22,238 --> 01:02:23,539
Please make your decision

1707
01:02:23,606 --> 01:02:25,341
and press the button!

1708
01:02:25,842 --> 01:02:27,143
This is so hard.

1709
01:02:27,210 --> 01:02:28,411
Of course.

1710
01:02:28,478 --> 01:02:31,481
This is how the fridge owners always feel.

1711
01:02:31,547 --> 01:02:34,016
Please press the button.

1712
01:02:34,083 --> 01:02:35,218
The pet pig or the fat cat?

1713
01:02:35,284 --> 01:02:38,321
-Please!
-Please!

1714
01:02:38,387 --> 01:02:39,989
-He has made his choice.
-He did it.

1715
01:02:40,056 --> 01:02:41,457
Did you? He pressed it.

1716
01:02:41,524 --> 01:02:45,128
Let's find out the result. Show us!

1717
01:02:45,194 --> 01:02:46,996
This is Chef Son Jong-won's decision.

1718
01:02:47,063 --> 01:02:49,565
-Mission Son-Possible: Mirror Match.
-Mirror Match.

1719
01:02:49,632 --> 01:02:52,168
They had to cook
using five mandatory ingredients.

1720
01:02:52,235 --> 01:02:56,372
Whoever wins this round
will earn their first star of 2026.

1721
01:02:56,439 --> 01:02:58,574
Which one of them won Jong-won's heart?

1722
01:02:58,641 --> 01:03:00,209
Who is it?

1723
01:03:00,276 --> 01:03:02,178
Sung-jun? Nam-no?

1724
01:03:02,245 --> 01:03:04,113
Which little bro did he choose?

1725
01:03:06,749 --> 01:03:07,884
Which little bro did he choose?

1726
01:03:07,950 --> 01:03:09,652
KWON SUNG-JUN WINS

1727
01:03:09,719 --> 01:03:11,320
YOUR SON'S NOT AS HOT AS
JONG-WON, SORRY MOM'S TART WINS

1728
01:03:11,387 --> 01:03:13,289
Kwon Sung-jun!

1729
01:03:13,356 --> 01:03:15,424
THE TWINS HAD
A FIERCE MIRROR MATCH

1730
01:03:15,491 --> 01:03:17,360
Sung-jun wins.

1731
01:03:17,426 --> 01:03:19,562
It's my third loss in a row.
This is a first for me.

1732
01:03:19,629 --> 01:03:22,465
-You chose the fat cat.
-The fat cat.

1733
01:03:22,532 --> 01:03:26,135
That was the first time
Sung-jun won against Nam-no.

1734
01:03:26,202 --> 01:03:27,637
And it's your first star this year.

1735
01:03:27,703 --> 01:03:28,905
CONGRATS, LITTLE BRO

1736
01:03:28,971 --> 01:03:31,374
That was
Nam-no's third loss in a row this year.

1737
01:03:31,440 --> 01:03:32,775
He was so desperate today.

1738
01:03:32,842 --> 01:03:35,945
This isn't the time
to have that smile in your eyes.

1739
01:03:36,012 --> 01:03:38,381
If only Chef Nam-no
didn't come with that smile…

1740
01:03:40,550 --> 01:03:42,418
That was a joke.

1741
01:03:42,485 --> 01:03:45,688
The theme was Mission Son-Possible,

1742
01:03:45,755 --> 01:03:47,523
where they had to cook

1743
01:03:47,590 --> 01:03:49,926
with ingredients
that seem impossible to mix.

1744
01:03:49,992 --> 01:03:52,995
And Sung-jun challenged himself
by trying many new things

1745
01:03:53,062 --> 01:03:54,730
that were not within his usual style

1746
01:03:54,797 --> 01:03:56,999
and made such a wonderful dish.

1747
01:03:57,066 --> 01:03:59,035
Also, it was such an unlikely mix,

1748
01:03:59,101 --> 01:04:02,405
so it was a pleasant surprise
in the aspect of creativity.

1749
01:04:02,471 --> 01:04:03,840
LOTS OF POINTS FOR CREATIVITY

1750
01:04:03,906 --> 01:04:05,374
Actually, I expected this.

1751
01:04:05,441 --> 01:04:06,909
-Expected what?
-What?

1752
01:04:06,976 --> 01:04:08,644
May I change my decision?

1753
01:04:08,711 --> 01:04:09,979
Did you expect to win?

1754
01:04:10,046 --> 01:04:11,981
Because he and I share

1755
01:04:12,048 --> 01:04:13,015
a bit of similarities.

1756
01:04:13,082 --> 01:04:15,117
-Come on.
-Good grief.

1757
01:04:15,184 --> 01:04:17,587
-That must've been why he chose me.
-Seriously.

1758
01:04:17,653 --> 01:04:18,921
Stop annoying me, okay?

1759
01:04:18,988 --> 01:04:20,356
He thinks you two are similar.

1760
01:04:20,423 --> 01:04:23,526
For the first time on the show,
Sung-jun wins against Nam-no

1761
01:04:23,593 --> 01:04:25,795
and takes his first star of the season!

1762
01:04:25,862 --> 01:04:26,996
Congratulations.

1763
01:04:27,663 --> 01:04:28,497
Thank you.

1764
01:04:28,564 --> 01:04:29,565
THE TWINS HUG

1765
01:04:29,632 --> 01:04:31,601
He was chosen by Jong-won.

1766
01:04:31,667 --> 01:04:34,670
-It's an honor.
-He says Jong-won is just like him.

1767
01:04:34,737 --> 01:04:36,105
Congratulations!

1768
01:04:36,172 --> 01:04:37,940
Sung-jun takes his first victory.

1769
01:04:38,007 --> 01:04:42,345
<i>Let us begin the second cook-off</i>
<i>played with Jong-won's ingredients.</i>

1770
01:04:42,411 --> 01:04:45,381
<i>A man who has</i>
<i>never made leftovers in his life,</i>

1771
01:04:45,448 --> 01:04:47,617
the binge eater, Chef Jung Ho-young,

1772
01:04:47,683 --> 01:04:50,486
<i>versus a man who has</i>
<i>never refused to try whatever's edible,</i>

1773
01:04:50,553 --> 01:04:53,656
the bizarre eater,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1774
01:04:53,723 --> 01:04:55,992
I hear that
Chef Ho-young went around saying,

1775
01:04:56,058 --> 01:04:58,527
"I feel like
I'm fighting with sandbag weights on,"

1776
01:04:58,594 --> 01:05:01,664
and it wasn't just to one person,
but to everyone he could find.

1777
01:05:01,731 --> 01:05:03,833
I have a bit of a disadvantage

1778
01:05:03,900 --> 01:05:07,904
because Chef Jong-won adores Poong,
no matter what he does.

1779
01:05:07,970 --> 01:05:10,273
They won the Best Couple Award.

1780
01:05:10,339 --> 01:05:13,342
It's like having a bowl of poke
in sunny California.

1781
01:05:13,409 --> 01:05:15,044
He reminded me of a peacock.

1782
01:05:15,111 --> 01:05:17,113
A peacock?
He's way too smitten with Poong.

1783
01:05:17,179 --> 01:05:18,881
-We say he's blinded by love.
-You're right.

1784
01:05:18,948 --> 01:05:22,318
That's why this is a bigger burden for me.

1785
01:05:22,385 --> 01:05:25,655
Because both Chef Jong-won
and I can feel it.

1786
01:05:25,721 --> 01:05:28,791
-So I know I must show something more.
-Feel what?

1787
01:05:28,858 --> 01:05:31,294
For me, it's not just sandbag weights.

1788
01:05:31,360 --> 01:05:33,763
I feel like I'm even dragging
weights tied to my body.

1789
01:05:33,829 --> 01:05:34,764
That's how I feel.

1790
01:05:34,830 --> 01:05:36,699
So is it because he's in your favor?

1791
01:05:36,766 --> 01:05:38,234
Honestly speaking,

1792
01:05:38,301 --> 01:05:41,070
I usually do come with biases
when I see whatever he does.

1793
01:05:41,137 --> 01:05:44,340
But after all, this is a competition.

1794
01:05:44,407 --> 01:05:45,675
-So I'll drop my biases.
-Yes.

1795
01:05:45,741 --> 01:05:49,078
-Well, there's a tip from the green room.
-There is?

1796
01:05:49,145 --> 01:05:51,881
"Even if Jong-won lets loose,
he can't eat much anyway."

1797
01:05:51,948 --> 01:05:54,650
"He has no idea
what binge eating really is."

1798
01:05:54,717 --> 01:05:56,886
-He said something like that.
-I see.

1799
01:05:56,953 --> 01:05:59,121
-Are you looking down on him?
-That was harsh.

1800
01:05:59,188 --> 01:06:03,092
To be honest, the green room
is practically a zoo.

1801
01:06:03,159 --> 01:06:04,293
-A zoo?
-Yes.

1802
01:06:04,360 --> 01:06:06,562
When you go to a zoo at lunchtime,

1803
01:06:06,629 --> 01:06:09,131
you'll see that each animal prefers
a different kind of feed.

1804
01:06:09,198 --> 01:06:11,934
For example, Chef Ho-young likes chips

1805
01:06:12,001 --> 01:06:14,070
and other snacks,
so he always keeps lots of those.

1806
01:06:14,136 --> 01:06:16,439
Chef Hyun-suk is into <i>ramyeon.</i>

1807
01:06:16,505 --> 01:06:18,674
We all have different feeds.

1808
01:06:18,741 --> 01:06:21,243
-Then one day…
-"Feeds."

1809
01:06:21,310 --> 01:06:23,279
…I saw a banana and boiled eggs.

1810
01:06:23,346 --> 01:06:25,481
-Yes.
-They suddenly showed up.

1811
01:06:25,548 --> 01:06:28,884
-In the green room?
-But none of the animals eat that feed.

1812
01:06:28,951 --> 01:06:31,020
I thought it was odd,

1813
01:06:31,087 --> 01:06:34,123
then realized Chef Jong-won
was the one who ate it.

1814
01:06:34,190 --> 01:06:36,459
I once watched
what he ate for an entire day,

1815
01:06:36,525 --> 01:06:39,795
and it was either one egg or one banana.

1816
01:06:39,862 --> 01:06:43,099
I wasn't sure if he knew
what binge eating actually meant.

1817
01:06:43,165 --> 01:06:44,266
Is this true?

1818
01:06:44,333 --> 01:06:45,868
It is, but it's a bit unfair.

1819
01:06:45,935 --> 01:06:48,337
Just before this, I went to the green room

1820
01:06:48,404 --> 01:06:51,140
to eat one boiled egg as I always did.

1821
01:06:51,207 --> 01:06:53,676
But the tub that had the eggs was empty.

1822
01:06:53,743 --> 01:06:55,711
-Who ate it all?
-Who was it?

1823
01:06:55,778 --> 01:06:58,080
-Who ate his feed?
-Some people put it in <i>ramyeon.</i>

1824
01:06:58,147 --> 01:06:59,048
Who ate it?

1825
01:06:59,115 --> 01:07:00,549
-Who is it?
-I didn't eat it today.

1826
01:07:01,117 --> 01:07:03,252
I had two eggs this morning.

1827
01:07:03,319 --> 01:07:04,587
ADMITS TO HIS CRIME

1828
01:07:04,653 --> 01:07:07,556
I had two eggs this morning
and another one with my cup <i>ramyeon.</i>

1829
01:07:07,623 --> 01:07:10,059
-In total, three.
-Three.

1830
01:07:10,126 --> 01:07:11,560
Someone had three eggs.

1831
01:07:11,627 --> 01:07:13,529
I had one too.

1832
01:07:13,596 --> 01:07:15,498
-I'll come forward.
-Stop stealing others' feed.

1833
01:07:15,564 --> 01:07:18,234
The eggs are there mainly for Jong-won,

1834
01:07:18,300 --> 01:07:20,770
but some animals
feed on anything and everything.

1835
01:07:20,836 --> 01:07:23,239
But I do take pride

1836
01:07:23,305 --> 01:07:25,674
in that I can eat a lot.

1837
01:07:25,741 --> 01:07:27,610
-Yes.
-I see. All right.

1838
01:07:28,544 --> 01:07:30,212
WEBTOON ARTIST POONG'S
INGREDIENTS

1839
01:07:30,279 --> 01:07:32,615
MILK, LEMON JUICE,
SHINE MUSCAT, BALSAMIC VINEGAR

1840
01:07:32,681 --> 01:07:34,784
Here's the name of my dish.

1841
01:07:35,384 --> 01:07:37,053
Mr. Sonshine.

1842
01:07:37,820 --> 01:07:39,789
-Mr. Sonshine.
-Mr. Sonshine.

1843
01:07:39,855 --> 01:07:41,590
Not sunshine, but Sonshine.

1844
01:07:41,657 --> 01:07:44,393
I will stray away from fusion,
bootleg, or bizarre dishes I have made

1845
01:07:44,460 --> 01:07:47,163
and make a traditional French dessert.

1846
01:07:47,229 --> 01:07:49,932
-Really? Not a bootleg version?
-Traditional?

1847
01:07:49,999 --> 01:07:51,133
It's a floating island.

1848
01:07:51,200 --> 01:07:52,468
-A floating island?
-A floating island?

1849
01:07:52,535 --> 01:07:53,569
A floating island.

1850
01:07:53,636 --> 01:07:56,472
It's cream made with egg yolk and milk,

1851
01:07:56,539 --> 01:07:59,041
with a floating meringue on top.

1852
01:07:59,108 --> 01:08:01,677
But I'll add shine muscat
and balsamic vinegar

1853
01:08:01,744 --> 01:08:04,180
for a little twist
while sticking to the basics.

1854
01:08:04,246 --> 01:08:06,148
That's the kind of dessert it will be.

1855
01:08:06,215 --> 01:08:08,584
It's called that
because it looks like a floating island,

1856
01:08:08,651 --> 01:08:10,820
and it's a dessert staple in France.

1857
01:08:10,886 --> 01:08:11,854
-I see.
-It won't be easy.

1858
01:08:11,921 --> 01:08:15,191
Is there something
that'll even shock Chef Jong-won?

1859
01:08:15,257 --> 01:08:18,394
-Anything new you'll mix in?
-He's thinking about it now.

1860
01:08:18,661 --> 01:08:20,062
ANTICIPATION

1861
01:08:20,129 --> 01:08:22,431
Isn't it a huge surprise
that I'm going traditional?

1862
01:08:22,498 --> 01:08:24,400
-It's so shocking.
-Orthodox gang.

1863
01:08:24,467 --> 01:08:26,235
-He's going orthodox.
-I'm not so sure.

1864
01:08:27,069 --> 01:08:29,105
CHEF HO-YOUNG'S INGREDIENTS: BONITO
FLAKE, ANCHOVY BROTH PACK, NAPA CABBAGE

1865
01:08:29,171 --> 01:08:31,240
DUMPLING, LAVER, COOKED TOFU, COOKED
BRISKET, BRISKET, GLASS NOODLES

1866
01:08:31,307 --> 01:08:34,243
Chef Ho-young is up against Poong.
What are you making?

1867
01:08:34,310 --> 01:08:36,779
I'm going to use brisket

1868
01:08:36,846 --> 01:08:38,814
to make <i>sundae.</i>

1869
01:08:38,881 --> 01:08:40,883
-I'll use brisket as the casing…
-Brisket <i>sundae?</i>

1870
01:08:40,950 --> 01:08:44,620
…and fill it with glass noodles
and dumpling fillings.

1871
01:08:44,687 --> 01:08:47,323
-You seemed to miss your mom's cooking…
-The mittens are so cute.

1872
01:08:47,389 --> 01:08:49,658
…so I'll make soup
with <i>doenjang </i>as the base,

1873
01:08:49,725 --> 01:08:52,061
put the <i>sundae </i>in,
and let you mix it with some rice,

1874
01:08:52,127 --> 01:08:54,630
making you finish the entire bowl,
and say,

1875
01:08:54,697 --> 01:08:55,931
"Rawr."

1876
01:08:55,998 --> 01:08:57,433
That's the soup dish I want to make.

1877
01:08:57,500 --> 01:08:58,667
-All right.
-Rawr.

1878
01:08:59,168 --> 01:09:00,102
RAWR!

1879
01:09:00,169 --> 01:09:01,003
Where did you get those gloves?

1880
01:09:01,070 --> 01:09:02,671
-These are oven mitts.
-Oven mitts?

1881
01:09:03,806 --> 01:09:04,707
AMAZING

1882
01:09:05,307 --> 01:09:06,909
It differs depending on who wears it.

1883
01:09:07,276 --> 01:09:09,445
FULL MARKS FOR UTILIZATION

1884
01:09:09,512 --> 01:09:11,413
And now, let us begin the next round

1885
01:09:11,480 --> 01:09:14,817
for Chef Jong-won,
"I'm Letting Myself Go Today."

1886
01:09:14,884 --> 01:09:17,987
Here's a man who wants to lead Jong-won
into the world of binge eating,

1887
01:09:18,053 --> 01:09:21,190
the binge eating fairy,
Chef Jung Ho-young.

1888
01:09:21,257 --> 01:09:24,293
But this man is here
to work his Kim Poong magic,

1889
01:09:24,360 --> 01:09:27,363
the bizarre food fairy, Kim Poong.

1890
01:09:27,429 --> 01:09:30,432
Which one will help Jong-won let loose?

1891
01:09:30,499 --> 01:09:33,269
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1892
01:09:34,703 --> 01:09:37,506
BINGE EATING FAIRY
VS. BIZARRE FOOD FAIRY

1893
01:09:37,573 --> 01:09:39,341
<i>Gukbap</i> versus dessert.

1894
01:09:39,408 --> 01:09:40,509
BINGE EATING FAIRY
STARTS WITH BROTH

1895
01:09:40,576 --> 01:09:43,045
-Their aims are completely different.
-Bonito broth.

1896
01:09:43,112 --> 01:09:44,313
-It's so good.
-One bag.

1897
01:09:44,380 --> 01:09:45,314
What's that?

1898
01:09:45,381 --> 01:09:47,149
-Bonito flakes.
-Bonito flakes.

1899
01:09:47,216 --> 01:09:48,684
The broth looks good.

1900
01:09:48,751 --> 01:09:49,985
1. BOIL BROTH

1901
01:09:50,252 --> 01:09:51,387
EGG

1902
01:09:51,687 --> 01:09:52,588
STARTS WITH THE MERINGUE

1903
01:09:52,655 --> 01:09:54,256
He needs to make nice meringue.

1904
01:09:54,823 --> 01:09:56,525
He separates egg yolks from whites.

1905
01:09:56,592 --> 01:09:59,128
Three yolks and two egg whites.

1906
01:09:59,195 --> 01:10:01,530
It'll take at least seven minutes
to whip up meringue.

1907
01:10:01,797 --> 01:10:02,865
MAKING MERINGUE

1908
01:10:03,399 --> 01:10:04,300
By hand?

1909
01:10:04,366 --> 01:10:05,534
He's making meringue!

1910
01:10:05,601 --> 01:10:07,336
Kim Poong isn't just a bootleg chef.

1911
01:10:07,403 --> 01:10:08,237
FINISHED?

1912
01:10:08,304 --> 01:10:11,073
-He has learned a lot from everyone.
-Why is he stopping?

1913
01:10:11,140 --> 01:10:13,842
It's much easier to do it with sugar.

1914
01:10:13,909 --> 01:10:15,044
Why are you whipping it like that?

1915
01:10:15,110 --> 01:10:16,579
-Is that milk?
-He forgot.

1916
01:10:16,845 --> 01:10:18,347
CAREFUL

1917
01:10:18,414 --> 01:10:19,481
It's milk.

1918
01:10:19,548 --> 01:10:21,917
-Did you add sugar?
-I did.

1919
01:10:21,984 --> 01:10:23,552
He'll probably add it in batches.

1920
01:10:23,619 --> 01:10:25,654
-He's making French meringue.
-I am.

1921
01:10:25,721 --> 01:10:26,555
It's orthodox.

1922
01:10:26,622 --> 01:10:28,257
-It's a French dish.
-He's going traditional.

1923
01:10:28,324 --> 01:10:32,861
Poong always says he'll go traditional,
but I've never seen him do it.

1924
01:10:32,928 --> 01:10:34,530
I already expected the result

1925
01:10:34,597 --> 01:10:36,432
to have nothing to do with his pitch.

1926
01:10:36,498 --> 01:10:37,566
Is that so?

1927
01:10:37,633 --> 01:10:38,934
Like that kouign-amann?

1928
01:10:39,001 --> 01:10:39,902
Yes.

1929
01:10:39,969 --> 01:10:42,538
He often failed after talking big.

1930
01:10:42,605 --> 01:10:46,909
On the other hand,
Ho-young quietly continues.

1931
01:10:46,976 --> 01:10:48,911
ONION - GREEN ONION

1932
01:10:48,978 --> 01:10:49,812
GARLIC

1933
01:10:49,878 --> 01:10:51,947
Ho-young gets the veggies ready.

1934
01:10:52,014 --> 01:10:53,148
MAKES SOUP WHILE FRYING VEGGIES

1935
01:10:53,983 --> 01:10:55,918
COOKED BRISKET FROM THE FRIDGE

1936
01:10:56,285 --> 01:10:59,355
2. STIR-FRY BRISKET, NAPA CABBAGE,
ONION, GARLIC, AND GREEN ONION

1937
01:10:59,922 --> 01:11:02,124
Poong's arm strength is outstanding.

1938
01:11:02,191 --> 01:11:03,959
CHEF WITH THE FROZEN SHOULDER
IS JEALOUS

1939
01:11:04,026 --> 01:11:05,661
Yes, he's fast.

1940
01:11:05,728 --> 01:11:07,529
He switches hands.
He's now on his right hand.

1941
01:11:07,596 --> 01:11:09,932
He whips with both
his right hand and left hand.

1942
01:11:09,999 --> 01:11:11,634
He's losing speed.

1943
01:11:11,700 --> 01:11:13,535
It's a task that makes you sweat.

1944
01:11:13,602 --> 01:11:16,238
-Poong has come a long way.
-He's slowing down.

1945
01:11:16,305 --> 01:11:17,306
AGING CURVE

1946
01:11:17,473 --> 01:11:18,674
PANT

1947
01:11:18,941 --> 01:11:20,109
KEEP IT UP!

1948
01:11:20,175 --> 01:11:22,678
-Poong's also 50 soon.
-I know.

1949
01:11:23,245 --> 01:11:24,780
ONLY 40 SECONDS INTO STIRRING
AND IT'S A CRISIS

1950
01:11:24,847 --> 01:11:28,817
The meringue has to be perfect
for it to float on top.

1951
01:11:28,884 --> 01:11:29,952
A FEROCIOUS SCREAM

1952
01:11:30,019 --> 01:11:32,421
It shouldn't fall out of the bowl
when you flip it.

1953
01:11:32,488 --> 01:11:33,622
-You're right.
-Yes.

1954
01:11:33,689 --> 01:11:34,890
How thick does it have to be?

1955
01:11:34,957 --> 01:11:36,792
-It has to be like marshmallow.
-To get to that stage…

1956
01:11:36,859 --> 01:11:38,093
About 90%?

1957
01:11:38,160 --> 01:11:39,728
…it has to be very thick.

1958
01:11:39,795 --> 01:11:43,499
He's trying too hard right now,
using up lots of energy in the beginning.

1959
01:11:44,066 --> 01:11:45,167
Oh, dumplings?

1960
01:11:45,234 --> 01:11:47,836
Chef Ho-young is peeling the dumplings

1961
01:11:47,903 --> 01:11:49,004
and mixing it with cabbage.

1962
01:11:49,071 --> 01:11:50,606
-Just the filling.
-No, with green onion.

1963
01:11:51,340 --> 01:11:52,675
He's using just the filling.

1964
01:11:52,741 --> 01:11:55,144
I think it's for the <i>sundae.</i>

1965
01:11:55,210 --> 01:11:57,179
What will you do
with the dumpling filling?

1966
01:11:57,246 --> 01:12:00,282
I'll turn it into <i>sundae </i>filling.

1967
01:12:00,683 --> 01:12:01,650
GROUND PEPPER

1968
01:12:01,717 --> 01:12:02,685
<i>Sundae.</i>

1969
01:12:02,751 --> 01:12:04,887
You wanted that gone,
so that's great news for you.

1970
01:12:04,953 --> 01:12:06,355
-I'm so grateful.
-He's grateful.

1971
01:12:06,422 --> 01:12:07,256
SALT

1972
01:12:07,323 --> 01:12:10,793
Ho-young gets extra points
for getting rid of the dumplings.

1973
01:12:11,360 --> 01:12:13,329
LEMON JUICE

1974
01:12:13,395 --> 01:12:15,898
-It's too early to use lemon juice.
-Lemon juice?

1975
01:12:15,964 --> 01:12:16,999
Lemon juice.

1976
01:12:17,066 --> 01:12:18,967
It gets rid of the flavor of raw egg.

1977
01:12:19,034 --> 01:12:20,703
He has to put it in when it's almost done,

1978
01:12:20,769 --> 01:12:24,073
after the meringue becomes thick.

1979
01:12:24,139 --> 01:12:26,975
-Wasn't this too early?
-That acid can ruin the batch.

1980
01:12:27,042 --> 01:12:28,477
Man. This is hard.

1981
01:12:28,677 --> 01:12:30,179
A BIZARRE ROAR!

1982
01:12:30,746 --> 01:12:32,448
I can do this for Jong-won!

1983
01:12:34,650 --> 01:12:38,554
He throws in the shine muscat
into boiling water while making meringue.

1984
01:12:38,620 --> 01:12:40,989
I think it's syrup. He put it in syrup.

1985
01:12:41,056 --> 01:12:42,891
It's syrup? It's not hot water?

1986
01:12:42,958 --> 01:12:44,793
-Is the meringue ready?
-Okay! All done.

1987
01:12:44,860 --> 01:12:46,528
It looks almost done.

1988
01:12:46,595 --> 01:12:48,197
-That was quick.
-It was.

1989
01:12:48,263 --> 01:12:49,798
Flip it over.

1990
01:12:49,865 --> 01:12:51,700
CONFIDENT KIM POONG

1991
01:12:51,767 --> 01:12:53,602
He did it.

1992
01:12:53,669 --> 01:12:54,837
What are you doing?

1993
01:12:54,903 --> 01:12:56,038
THE FLEXIBILITY OF A DANCER

1994
01:12:56,105 --> 01:12:57,106
He's showing it off.

1995
01:12:57,172 --> 01:12:58,040
What?

1996
01:12:58,107 --> 01:12:59,074
HOW IS HE SO FLEXIBLE?

1997
01:12:59,141 --> 01:13:01,076
-That's Poong.
-I knew it.

1998
01:13:04,580 --> 01:13:05,981
What's that? Batter?

1999
01:13:06,048 --> 01:13:07,516
-Frying batter.
-Frying batter.

2000
01:13:07,583 --> 01:13:08,851
He must be frying something.

2001
01:13:08,917 --> 01:13:11,854
I'll deep-fry <i>sundae</i>
like laver and glass noodle fritter.

2002
01:13:11,920 --> 01:13:13,088
That sounds so good.

2003
01:13:13,155 --> 01:13:15,157
-That can't be bad.
-It sounds great.

2004
01:13:15,224 --> 01:13:17,393
Are you putting everything
into the <i>gukbap?</i>

2005
01:13:17,459 --> 01:13:18,861
-Yes.
-I see.

2006
01:13:18,927 --> 01:13:21,430
-He lays out brisket on the laver.
-Just like that?

2007
01:13:21,497 --> 01:13:23,265
-It looks good.
-It looks good.

2008
01:13:23,332 --> 01:13:25,701
He lays out brisket on the laver.

2009
01:13:25,768 --> 01:13:26,935
It looks good.

2010
01:13:27,002 --> 01:13:28,537
-It looks good.
-It looks good.

2011
01:13:28,604 --> 01:13:29,772
-It looks good.
-That is…

2012
01:13:30,406 --> 01:13:32,574
the brisket he had labeled

2013
01:13:32,641 --> 01:13:35,077
and kept in a tub inside his freezer.

2014
01:13:35,144 --> 01:13:36,812
Does your mother
make good <i>doenjang-jjigae?</i>

2015
01:13:36,879 --> 01:13:38,614
Yes, she does.

2016
01:13:38,680 --> 01:13:40,149
She's a great cook.

2017
01:13:40,215 --> 01:13:42,384
His mom is a great cook
and makes delicious <i>doenjang-jjigae.</i>

2018
01:13:42,451 --> 01:13:43,519
This is bad.

2019
01:13:43,585 --> 01:13:44,987
-Why?
-What's bad?

2020
01:13:45,053 --> 01:13:46,488
Hearing that his mom is a great cook.

2021
01:13:47,289 --> 01:13:50,559
I thought she wouldn't be
as good of a cook as her son.

2022
01:13:50,626 --> 01:13:52,728
Poong is doing something
with just the yolk.

2023
01:13:52,795 --> 01:13:54,596
-He's whipping it with sugar.
-The whisk…

2024
01:13:54,663 --> 01:13:56,331
The whisk is too big for the bowl.

2025
01:13:56,398 --> 01:13:58,834
-What's that for?
-This is the cream on the bottom.

2026
01:13:58,901 --> 01:14:00,736
-The cream?
-There's a French custard cream

2027
01:14:00,803 --> 01:14:05,007
that's so thin
that you can probably even drink it.

2028
01:14:05,073 --> 01:14:07,643
-Is that soy milk? You're pouring it in?
-Milk.

2029
01:14:07,709 --> 01:14:08,644
It's milk.

2030
01:14:08,710 --> 01:14:11,580
-He has to keep it thin.
-He must keep it thin.

2031
01:14:11,647 --> 01:14:12,915
Isn't the whisk too big?

2032
01:14:12,981 --> 01:14:14,950
The whisk is too big,
and the bowl is too small.

2033
01:14:15,017 --> 01:14:17,052
The way he stirs…

2034
01:14:17,119 --> 01:14:18,587
-It's so sloppy.
-Something's odd.

2035
01:14:18,654 --> 01:14:20,889
-It's odd.
-How will he win a star by doing that?

2036
01:14:20,956 --> 01:14:21,824
The yolk might get cooked.

2037
01:14:21,890 --> 01:14:23,625
-It's not odd.
-It's not?

2038
01:14:23,692 --> 01:14:27,095
-He tells himself that this isn't odd.
-"It's not odd."

2039
01:14:27,162 --> 01:14:29,731
You have 9 minutes and 40 seconds left.

2040
01:14:30,766 --> 01:14:31,834
DUMPLING FILLINGS ON BRISKET!

2041
01:14:31,900 --> 01:14:33,368
Ho-young tops the brisket

2042
01:14:33,435 --> 01:14:36,505
with lots of dumpling filling
and glass noodles!

2043
01:14:36,572 --> 01:14:39,475
That's how he's making it like <i>sundae.</i>

2044
01:14:39,541 --> 01:14:41,677
That's how it becomes <i>sundae.</i>

2045
01:14:41,743 --> 01:14:43,979
-And you'll deep-fry it, right?
-Yes.

2046
01:14:44,046 --> 01:14:46,482
You can see
the glass noodles sticking out.

2047
01:14:46,548 --> 01:14:50,486
But that's not <i>sundae. </i>It's like <i>gimmari,</i>
laver and glass noodles fritter.

2048
01:14:50,552 --> 01:14:52,020
-Yes, you're right.
-It's like <i>gimmari.</i>

2049
01:14:52,087 --> 01:14:55,023
-He doesn't have any casing, so…
-That's true.

2050
01:14:56,925 --> 01:14:59,161
SHINE MUSCAT BOILED IN SYRUP

2051
01:15:00,562 --> 01:15:01,563
It's hot.

2052
01:15:01,630 --> 01:15:03,031
It's so hot!

2053
01:15:03,098 --> 01:15:04,733
-Why didn't you peel it first?
-It's hot.

2054
01:15:05,667 --> 01:15:06,668
It's hot.

2055
01:15:07,236 --> 01:15:09,705
-What is that? Is it hot?
-Is it hot?

2056
01:15:09,771 --> 01:15:13,308
Those were dipped in syrup,
so they must be quite hot.

2057
01:15:13,375 --> 01:15:15,644
Why did you put it in syrup
if you were going to peel it?

2058
01:15:15,711 --> 01:15:16,545
Right?

2059
01:15:16,612 --> 01:15:19,114
-It won't seep inside.
-Wait, why the iced water?

2060
01:15:19,181 --> 01:15:20,349
Right? He only wasted time.

2061
01:15:20,415 --> 01:15:22,551
That'll wash away the syrup.

2062
01:15:22,618 --> 01:15:23,719
Because they're hot.

2063
01:15:23,785 --> 01:15:25,854
He had to save himself first.

2064
01:15:28,790 --> 01:15:30,025
MERINGUE INTO WARM MILK!

2065
01:15:30,092 --> 01:15:32,060
He's putting meringue in there.

2066
01:15:32,127 --> 01:15:33,896
-He's boiling it.
-And that cooks it?

2067
01:15:33,962 --> 01:15:36,932
If it's too hot, it'll fall flat.

2068
01:15:36,999 --> 01:15:40,435
It'll start sinking
just like how rice gets soaked in soup.

2069
01:15:40,502 --> 01:15:42,671
I don't know how that'll turn out.

2070
01:15:42,738 --> 01:15:44,206
I don't think the yolk is working.

2071
01:15:45,707 --> 01:15:47,042
Is he out of energy?

2072
01:15:47,109 --> 01:15:49,244
-Poong.
-Don't leave the bowl up there!

2073
01:15:49,311 --> 01:15:50,445
LEMON JUICE

2074
01:15:50,512 --> 01:15:52,047
He licks his lips.

2075
01:15:52,114 --> 01:15:54,816
<i>If the yolk gets cooked,</i>
<i>he gets cooked too.</i>

2076
01:15:55,918 --> 01:15:57,519
I have to get rid of the foam.

2077
01:15:57,586 --> 01:15:58,654
Yes, the foam.

2078
01:15:58,720 --> 01:16:00,989
Use a torch!
That'll get rid of everything.

2079
01:16:01,056 --> 01:16:02,791
-Really?
-They'll all disappear with a torch.

2080
01:16:02,858 --> 01:16:04,526
POONG'S BEST QUALITY?
HE TAKES IN EVERY ADVICE

2081
01:16:04,593 --> 01:16:05,861
See? All gone.

2082
01:16:05,928 --> 01:16:08,096
-Whoooa.
-Use a torch.

2083
01:16:08,463 --> 01:16:10,699
LEMON CURD
MADE WITH LEMON JUICE!

2084
01:16:12,000 --> 01:16:12,868
DOENJANG

2085
01:16:12,935 --> 01:16:13,902
And the <i>gukbap.</i>

2086
01:16:13,969 --> 01:16:15,203
It looks so good.

2087
01:16:15,270 --> 01:16:16,672
Man! That looks so good!

2088
01:16:16,738 --> 01:16:19,508
The soup seems like
it's turning out great.

2089
01:16:19,575 --> 01:16:20,676
6. ADD ALL TO SOUP AND BOIL MORE

2090
01:16:20,943 --> 01:16:22,110
BRISKET POINT

2091
01:16:22,477 --> 01:16:23,312
SOY SAUCE

2092
01:16:24,112 --> 01:16:25,981
You only have six minutes, <i>gukbap.</i>

2093
01:16:26,048 --> 01:16:27,849
BEGINS TO DEEP-FRY HIS SUNDAE!

2094
01:16:27,916 --> 01:16:30,752
-He's deep-frying!
-That's going to be so good.

2095
01:16:30,819 --> 01:16:32,754
-That looks really good.
-Fritters are always good.

2096
01:16:32,821 --> 01:16:33,889
That's just insane.

2097
01:16:33,956 --> 01:16:36,325
-It's bound to be good.
-It's hard to mess that up.

2098
01:16:36,391 --> 01:16:39,127
I didn't think Ho-young would…

2099
01:16:39,194 --> 01:16:40,762
EMERGENCY

2100
01:16:40,829 --> 01:16:41,863
It's an emergency.

2101
01:16:41,930 --> 01:16:43,298
The oil is overflowing!

2102
01:16:43,365 --> 01:16:45,167
The temperature will drop.

2103
01:16:45,233 --> 01:16:47,636
The temperature will change then.

2104
01:16:47,703 --> 01:16:49,304
-Ho-young's fritters.
-The fritter…

2105
01:16:49,371 --> 01:16:50,339
It's not an emergency.

2106
01:16:50,405 --> 01:16:51,873
It's overflowing!

2107
01:16:51,940 --> 01:16:54,142
-The meringue!
-It's an emergency!

2108
01:16:54,209 --> 01:16:57,613
EMERGENCY
ON POONG'S SIDE THIS TIME

2109
01:16:57,679 --> 01:16:59,014
It's overflowing!

2110
01:16:59,081 --> 01:17:00,749
What's that? Are you boiling a dishcloth?

2111
01:17:01,850 --> 01:17:02,918
What's in there?

2112
01:17:02,985 --> 01:17:06,188
-Isn't it a dishcloth?
-It swelled up as it cooked.

2113
01:17:06,254 --> 01:17:08,657
Is that the meringue he made?

2114
01:17:08,724 --> 01:17:11,026
-Really?
-I thought he was washing his dishcloth.

2115
01:17:11,093 --> 01:17:12,094
A failed poached egg?

2116
01:17:12,160 --> 01:17:14,596
-No, be quiet.
-He got it out.

2117
01:17:14,663 --> 01:17:16,331
Let him focus.

2118
01:17:16,398 --> 01:17:18,200
-It looks like meringue.
-It looks good.

2119
01:17:18,634 --> 01:17:21,403
SHINE MUSCAT
CHILLED IN ICED WATER

2120
01:17:21,470 --> 01:17:24,406
I think Poong will lose all his time
trying to peel the fruit.

2121
01:17:24,473 --> 01:17:26,375
If you were going to peel it,

2122
01:17:26,441 --> 01:17:27,909
-why use the syrup?
-Why did you use it?

2123
01:17:27,976 --> 01:17:29,945
-Why did you put it in ice?
-To keep the sweetness in.

2124
01:17:30,012 --> 01:17:33,715
It's even harder to peel
because it's been cooked already.

2125
01:17:33,782 --> 01:17:35,884
I had to keep the sweet juice in!

2126
01:17:35,951 --> 01:17:36,785
To keep the juice in?

2127
01:17:36,852 --> 01:17:38,553
THE LEMON CURD
TO FLOAT THE ISLAND

2128
01:17:38,620 --> 01:17:39,921
Okay.

2129
01:17:40,489 --> 01:17:41,690
Five minutes.

2130
01:17:41,757 --> 01:17:44,359
Five minutes! You're up, Jung-hwan.

2131
01:17:44,426 --> 01:17:45,560
I'll go.

2132
01:17:45,627 --> 01:17:49,031
Which one of them
will make Jong-won let himself go?

2133
01:17:49,097 --> 01:17:50,565
The fritters are done.

2134
01:17:50,632 --> 01:17:52,801
Look at that thing. Wow.

2135
01:17:52,868 --> 01:17:55,337
-It looks like a deep-fried tiger prawn.
-It does.

2136
01:17:55,404 --> 01:17:58,874
-Hey, look at that soup.
-That looks so good!

2137
01:17:58,940 --> 01:18:00,642
I can let myself go with that.

2138
01:18:00,709 --> 01:18:02,077
That's a proper late-night snack.

2139
01:18:02,144 --> 01:18:05,247
-Let me try the soup.
-Okay.

2140
01:18:05,981 --> 01:18:08,283
That soup looks so delicious.

2141
01:18:08,350 --> 01:18:10,919
-That calls for two bottles of soju.
-Will it make him let himself go?

2142
01:18:10,986 --> 01:18:12,187
Can he let himself go?

2143
01:18:12,254 --> 01:18:14,089
No, not yet.

2144
01:18:14,156 --> 01:18:16,324
-It's a bit bland.
-You have to let it boil down more.

2145
01:18:16,391 --> 01:18:17,359
You've got time.

2146
01:18:18,260 --> 01:18:19,461
<i>Ramyeon</i> soup base?

2147
01:18:19,528 --> 01:18:21,496
-What the heck?
-<i>Ramyeon </i>soup base!

2148
01:18:21,563 --> 01:18:23,065
What just happened?

2149
01:18:23,131 --> 01:18:24,266
AHAHAHAHAHA

2150
01:18:24,332 --> 01:18:26,435
CENSORED FOR SECURITY

2151
01:18:26,501 --> 01:18:28,270
He has to let himself go,
so he needs <i>ramyeon.</i>

2152
01:18:28,336 --> 01:18:30,706
Ho-young throws in some <i>ramyeon </i>soup base.

2153
01:18:30,772 --> 01:18:31,673
It was bland before.

2154
01:18:31,740 --> 01:18:32,574
HOW EFFECTIVE WAS IT?

2155
01:18:33,575 --> 01:18:35,577
It's complete now.

2156
01:18:35,644 --> 01:18:37,779
-A taste made by professionals.
-Is it done?

2157
01:18:37,846 --> 01:18:39,581
-It found its place.
-With <i>ramyeon </i>soup base!

2158
01:18:39,915 --> 01:18:41,583
"SOME PEOPLE
THINK I'M A COMEDIAN"

2159
01:18:41,650 --> 01:18:43,118
THAT'S MY BRO

2160
01:18:43,185 --> 01:18:45,520
-What are those?
-They look insane.

2161
01:18:45,587 --> 01:18:46,955
It's so fascinating.

2162
01:18:47,022 --> 01:18:49,324
It looks like a huge deep-fried prawn.

2163
01:18:49,725 --> 01:18:51,626
AND HE NEEDS RICE FOR GUKBAP!

2164
01:18:51,693 --> 01:18:52,994
-Emergency.
-Rice.

2165
01:18:53,061 --> 01:18:54,129
It's an emergency.

2166
01:18:55,197 --> 01:18:56,965
POONG BREAKS EVERYTHING

2167
01:18:57,265 --> 01:18:59,267
5. COOL LEMON CURD
OVER ICED WATER

2168
01:18:59,334 --> 01:19:03,438
It's taking Poong a long time
to peel the shine muscat.

2169
01:19:03,505 --> 01:19:05,907
I have to do this
to make them look prettier.

2170
01:19:06,408 --> 01:19:07,809
THE CROSS-SECTION
OF THE FRITTER!

2171
01:19:07,876 --> 01:19:11,413
-He works hard on this yellow sauce.
-It looks good!

2172
01:19:11,480 --> 01:19:12,948
-What is it?
-That's amazing.

2173
01:19:13,014 --> 01:19:14,382
The cross-section.

2174
01:19:14,449 --> 01:19:15,951
Look at that.

2175
01:19:16,017 --> 01:19:17,452
And it goes into the pot.

2176
01:19:17,519 --> 01:19:19,788
So these will act as the <i>sundae</i>
that goes into the <i>gukbap.</i>

2177
01:19:19,855 --> 01:19:21,823
THE SUNDAE-GUK
TO MAKE YOU BINGE!

2178
01:19:21,890 --> 01:19:23,992
Ho-young captures everyone's attention.

2179
01:19:24,059 --> 01:19:25,193
PEELS GRAPES FOR OVER A MINUTE

2180
01:19:25,260 --> 01:19:26,962
Hey, Poong.

2181
01:19:27,028 --> 01:19:28,396
-Poong.
-Poong.

2182
01:19:29,064 --> 01:19:29,965
NODS

2183
01:19:30,031 --> 01:19:32,033
-This…
-That sauce is important.

2184
01:19:32,100 --> 01:19:33,802
Now, so?

2185
01:19:33,869 --> 01:19:35,070
THE SEA TO FLOAT
THE MERINGUE ISLAND

2186
01:19:35,137 --> 01:19:37,773
Will it make Jong-won turn into Son-Shine?

2187
01:19:40,142 --> 01:19:42,310
-He will turn into Son-Shine.
-He will?

2188
01:19:43,211 --> 01:19:44,546
-He will turn into Son-Shine!
-I knew it!

2189
01:19:44,613 --> 01:19:45,447
Hold on.

2190
01:19:45,514 --> 01:19:47,682
-He had something up his sleeve.
-Of course.

2191
01:19:47,749 --> 01:19:48,750
It's good.

2192
01:19:48,817 --> 01:19:51,453
-He's doing it again?
-He knew he could trust in himself.

2193
01:19:51,520 --> 01:19:53,455
-It's nice.
-I see.

2194
01:19:53,522 --> 01:19:55,323
THE PUNCH, BALSAMIC VINEGAR!

2195
01:19:55,390 --> 01:19:57,025
I can do this.

2196
01:19:57,092 --> 01:19:58,226
-Jung-hwan!
-Yes?

2197
01:19:58,293 --> 01:20:01,062
-Can you try the soup again?
-Should I do that?

2198
01:20:01,129 --> 01:20:03,331
You tried it first at four minutes,
and we're at two now.

2199
01:20:04,266 --> 01:20:06,401
Now, what's it like?

2200
01:20:06,468 --> 01:20:09,204
Rawr! It's good!

2201
01:20:09,938 --> 01:20:11,673
-He got it!
-Rawr!

2202
01:20:11,740 --> 01:20:13,275
-He got it!
-Rawr! He got it!

2203
01:20:13,341 --> 01:20:14,676
He got it to taste rawr-ly well.

2204
01:20:14,743 --> 01:20:16,378
Ho-young has rawr-ly got
the taste on point!

2205
01:20:16,444 --> 01:20:17,913
-He has.
-Two minutes left.

2206
01:20:17,979 --> 01:20:19,748
-Two minutes.
-It worked.

2207
01:20:19,815 --> 01:20:20,715
Two minutes?

2208
01:20:21,483 --> 01:20:23,451
Wait, what? It looks pretty legit.

2209
01:20:23,518 --> 01:20:25,587
-It actually looks good.
-It does.

2210
01:20:25,654 --> 01:20:27,489
-He put it in the dish.
-That's good.

2211
01:20:27,556 --> 01:20:28,423
-Was it good?
-Yes.

2212
01:20:28,490 --> 01:20:31,526
-It looks fluffy like soft tofu.
-It doesn't look half bad.

2213
01:20:31,593 --> 01:20:32,594
+SHINE MUSCAT

2214
01:20:32,661 --> 01:20:34,029
-Wait.
-Topped with shine muscat.

2215
01:20:34,095 --> 01:20:35,630
You should pour the sauce first.

2216
01:20:35,697 --> 01:20:37,899
Why are you doing that?
It's the other way around.

2217
01:20:37,966 --> 01:20:40,268
You're right. It's going to sink!

2218
01:20:40,335 --> 01:20:42,404
-He'll pour it from the side.
-From the side.

2219
01:20:42,470 --> 01:20:44,139
-Will it float?
-Will it float?

2220
01:20:44,206 --> 01:20:47,342
-That's not how it's done.
-Will the meringue float?

2221
01:20:47,409 --> 01:20:50,045
-It's floating!
-It's floating!

2222
01:20:50,111 --> 01:20:51,346
What? It turned out nice.

2223
01:20:51,413 --> 01:20:52,447
It's floating!

2224
01:20:52,514 --> 01:20:53,815
Why is he so good?

2225
01:20:53,882 --> 01:20:56,084
-Poong's island is floating!
-Why is he so good?

2226
01:20:56,151 --> 01:20:57,419
His meringue floats!

2227
01:20:57,986 --> 01:20:58,854
-Whoa.
-It's as if…

2228
01:20:58,920 --> 01:21:01,122
-That's not so bad.
-…it's an iceberg inside the soup.

2229
01:21:01,189 --> 01:21:02,490
Why is he good?

2230
01:21:02,557 --> 01:21:04,492
-"Why is he good?"
-Why does it look pretty?

2231
01:21:04,559 --> 01:21:05,493
Why is he good?

2232
01:21:05,560 --> 01:21:07,963
-What's that?
-Balsamic vinegar?

2233
01:21:08,029 --> 01:21:09,497
-To add a strong flavor?
-What?

2234
01:21:09,564 --> 01:21:11,132
I don't think he should.

2235
01:21:11,199 --> 01:21:13,602
So? How should I drizzle this?

2236
01:21:13,668 --> 01:21:14,569
Do whatever you want.

2237
01:21:14,636 --> 01:21:15,837
-Slightly on the side.
-The side?

2238
01:21:15,904 --> 01:21:18,039
It has to top the meringue.

2239
01:21:18,106 --> 01:21:19,374
Isn't it better to leave drops?

2240
01:21:19,441 --> 01:21:20,775
A few drops with a heart shape.

2241
01:21:20,842 --> 01:21:22,510
Drops with a heart? Okay.

2242
01:21:22,577 --> 01:21:23,845
-Here goes the heart.
-Yes.

2243
01:21:23,912 --> 01:21:24,846
Jong-won's…

2244
01:21:25,180 --> 01:21:27,315
AN ACCIDENT!

2245
01:21:27,749 --> 01:21:29,684
AHAHAHAHAHA

2246
01:21:30,285 --> 01:21:31,887
He ruined it while trying to make dots!

2247
01:21:31,953 --> 01:21:34,289
-Is that mold?
-It looks like cough syrup!

2248
01:21:34,356 --> 01:21:35,824
No, some dots on the yellow part.

2249
01:21:35,891 --> 01:21:38,093
-The yolk part.
-It was for the yolk!

2250
01:21:38,159 --> 01:21:39,961
Make dots on the yolk!

2251
01:21:40,028 --> 01:21:41,830
-No, just stop.
-Just stop it.

2252
01:21:41,897 --> 01:21:43,832
PLEASE STOP…

2253
01:21:44,399 --> 01:21:46,034
-It's like caviar.
-Frog eggs.

2254
01:21:46,601 --> 01:21:48,770
ANYWAY, HE'S DONE!

2255
01:21:48,937 --> 01:21:49,771
IT LOOKS GOOD

2256
01:21:49,838 --> 01:21:51,373
-Thirty seconds.
-It's fine if it tastes good.

2257
01:21:51,439 --> 01:21:53,541
-That looks good.
-That soup looks insane.

2258
01:21:53,608 --> 01:21:54,809
THE SOUP TO MAKE HIM BINGE!

2259
01:21:55,377 --> 01:21:59,881
9. POUR SOUP OVER THE FRITTER
AND TOP WITH GREEN ONION

2260
01:22:00,649 --> 01:22:03,285
AND ADD MORE DEEP-FRIEND SUNDAE!

2261
01:22:03,351 --> 01:22:05,253
You'll have an advantage
if you finish first.

2262
01:22:05,320 --> 01:22:07,322
Should he have him eat the dessert first?

2263
01:22:07,389 --> 01:22:09,624
-Then that soup won't be delicious.
-No, right?

2264
01:22:09,691 --> 01:22:11,693
I want to fight this round

2265
01:22:11,760 --> 01:22:12,694
fair and square.

2266
01:22:12,761 --> 01:22:14,963
I'm going orthodox today.

2267
01:22:15,664 --> 01:22:17,032
You can do this! You got it!

2268
01:22:17,098 --> 01:22:18,333
You got it, fatty!

2269
01:22:18,400 --> 01:22:21,136
-You can do this, fatty!
-Five. Four. Three.

2270
01:22:21,202 --> 01:22:23,838
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

2271
01:22:23,905 --> 01:22:25,307
-Time's up.
-Time's up.

2272
01:22:25,373 --> 01:22:26,708
TIME OVER

2273
01:22:26,775 --> 01:22:29,811
Poong waits until Ho-young rings the bell.

2274
01:22:29,878 --> 01:22:33,548
He's going to be an orthodox chef today,
not a bootleg chef.

2275
01:22:33,615 --> 01:22:34,449
WOW

2276
01:22:34,516 --> 01:22:36,017
He made this happen?

2277
01:22:36,084 --> 01:22:38,887
THE FLOATING ISLAND
DOESN'T LOOK HALF BAD!

2278
01:22:39,487 --> 01:22:40,488
FRIED SUNDAE-GUKBAP
THAT MAKES YOU BINGE!

2279
01:22:40,555 --> 01:22:42,357
-It looks insane.
-It does.

2280
01:22:42,424 --> 01:22:44,759
-It looks good.
-This is totally legit.

2281
01:22:45,360 --> 01:22:47,963
THE DISHES
THAT'LL MAKE HIM LET GO!

2282
01:22:48,029 --> 01:22:48,964
It looks fantastic.

2283
01:22:49,030 --> 01:22:52,067
-It looks awesome when it overflows.
-I've seen that at restaurants.

2284
01:22:52,634 --> 01:22:54,703
Chef Jong-won, if you finish all these,

2285
01:22:54,769 --> 01:22:56,905
you'll be too bloated
to open your eyes tomorrow.

2286
01:22:56,972 --> 01:22:57,806
I can eat a lot.

2287
01:22:57,872 --> 01:22:59,507
How much frozen pork belly can you eat?

2288
01:22:59,574 --> 01:23:00,408
-Frozen pork belly?
-Yes.

2289
01:23:00,475 --> 01:23:01,443
Frozen pork belly?

2290
01:23:01,509 --> 01:23:02,744
-It's not filling.
-Like eight portions?

2291
01:23:02,811 --> 01:23:04,312
Right. I lost.

2292
01:23:04,980 --> 01:23:07,082
-Frozen pork belly doesn't fill you up.
-I can do three.

2293
01:23:07,148 --> 01:23:10,185
-It's only 120 grams per serving.
-Right.

2294
01:23:10,251 --> 01:23:12,387
-That sounds good right now.
-You digest it as you eat.

2295
01:23:12,454 --> 01:23:15,957
The dishes are finished
for Chef Jong-won to try.

2296
01:23:16,024 --> 01:23:18,526
First, Chef Ho-young's dish.

2297
01:23:19,027 --> 01:23:21,896
YOU NEED TO EAT GUKBAP
TO LET GO OF YOURSELF

2298
01:23:22,197 --> 01:23:25,433
CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG'S LET GO,
LET GO, LET GO, LET GO, RAWR

2299
01:23:25,500 --> 01:23:28,737
I'm sure you usually do not eat this much.

2300
01:23:28,803 --> 01:23:30,638
Do you like <i>sundae-guk?</i>

2301
01:23:30,705 --> 01:23:32,374
Actually, it's my favorite dish.

2302
01:23:32,707 --> 01:23:34,609
GREAT NEWS

2303
01:23:34,676 --> 01:23:36,945
Someone must've leaked that information.

2304
01:23:37,012 --> 01:23:39,681
-That's my master.
-It has been somewhat deep-fried.

2305
01:23:39,748 --> 01:23:41,783
-I'll try it.
-I'm curious.

2306
01:23:41,850 --> 01:23:43,184
-Dip it in the soup.
-Dip it.

2307
01:23:43,251 --> 01:23:44,819
Will it help him let go?

2308
01:23:44,886 --> 01:23:46,554
LOOKING DELICIOUS

2309
01:23:46,621 --> 01:23:50,692
I think it's quite a luxury to dip
deep-fried food in soup before eating it.

2310
01:23:51,559 --> 01:23:53,161
I think it's a momentary happiness,

2311
01:23:53,228 --> 01:23:55,130
so let me indulge in it.

2312
01:23:55,196 --> 01:23:57,265
I hope it's not too hot.

2313
01:23:57,332 --> 01:23:58,566
Careful.

2314
01:23:58,633 --> 01:24:01,036
It's even better
if you eat it as you burn your tongue.

2315
01:24:01,102 --> 01:24:02,270
Burn the entire roof of your mouth.

2316
01:24:02,971 --> 01:24:06,074
He made it with briskets, glass noodles,
dumpling filling, and laver.

2317
01:24:06,141 --> 01:24:07,475
I guess it's not too hot.

2318
01:24:07,542 --> 01:24:09,878
A FROWN?

2319
01:24:09,944 --> 01:24:12,514
He's staring intently at the <i>sundae-guk.</i>

2320
01:24:12,580 --> 01:24:14,649
-It must be hot.
-Something you don't like about it?

2321
01:24:14,716 --> 01:24:15,750
He tilts his head.

2322
01:24:15,817 --> 01:24:17,919
-A head tilt.
-Is there something missing?

2323
01:24:17,986 --> 01:24:19,687
-What is it?
-You know,

2324
01:24:19,754 --> 01:24:21,456
I must let loose and start digging in.

2325
01:24:21,756 --> 01:24:22,724
LET GO, LET GO, RAWR

2326
01:24:22,791 --> 01:24:24,059
He unties his bow tie.

2327
01:24:24,125 --> 01:24:26,861
-Sexy!
-It's been suffocating him.

2328
01:24:26,928 --> 01:24:27,829
That's so sexy.

2329
01:24:27,896 --> 01:24:29,664
-I'll let go.
-It's the outfit.

2330
01:24:29,731 --> 01:24:32,434
You need to feel that swallow.

2331
01:24:32,500 --> 01:24:35,270
He's showing respect for the dish.

2332
01:24:35,336 --> 01:24:37,505
It keeps sliding in smoothly.

2333
01:24:37,572 --> 01:24:38,606
He's enjoying it so much.

2334
01:24:39,174 --> 01:24:40,508
I can't stand it anymore.

2335
01:24:40,575 --> 01:24:41,776
LOSING HIS MIND

2336
01:24:41,843 --> 01:24:43,278
Sorry, Nam-no.

2337
01:24:43,344 --> 01:24:44,446
"Sorry, Nam-no."

2338
01:24:44,512 --> 01:24:46,047
Let's share!

2339
01:24:46,114 --> 01:24:50,685
<i>Chef Nam-no usually eats the leftovers</i>
<i>when a dish is served in a bowl or a pot,</i>

2340
01:24:50,752 --> 01:24:52,387
but I may not leave anything today.

2341
01:24:52,454 --> 01:24:53,922
No!

2342
01:24:54,289 --> 01:24:55,924
ABOUT TO CRY

2343
01:24:55,990 --> 01:24:58,393
I'll be Son Nam-no today.

2344
01:24:58,460 --> 01:24:59,928
-Son Nam-no?
-Son Nam-no?

2345
01:24:59,994 --> 01:25:01,596
SON NAM-NO EATS ANOTHER SUNDAE

2346
01:25:02,263 --> 01:25:03,865
IT'S HOT

2347
01:25:03,932 --> 01:25:05,433
It's hot, isn't it? It is.

2348
01:25:05,500 --> 01:25:07,936
-But you have to eat it hot.
-Yes, while burning your mouth.

2349
01:25:08,002 --> 01:25:12,073
It's like eating your mom's <i>sundae-guk</i>
at home after a hard day.

2350
01:25:12,474 --> 01:25:14,576
SINCE HE CAN'T EAT IT,
HE'LL AT LEAST RECORD A VIDEO

2351
01:25:14,642 --> 01:25:16,044
Is the soup not spicy?

2352
01:25:16,111 --> 01:25:18,279
A HUGE BITE

2353
01:25:18,346 --> 01:25:21,683
This is a man who just drinks water here.

2354
01:25:21,749 --> 01:25:24,686
Someone who snacks on cucumbers or apples.

2355
01:25:24,752 --> 01:25:26,654
Ho-young picked the perfect dish for him.

2356
01:25:26,721 --> 01:25:27,989
Chef Jong-won just had

2357
01:25:28,056 --> 01:25:31,092
more sodium than the total amount
of sodium he had consumed

2358
01:25:31,159 --> 01:25:34,996
-in the past year on this show.
-That's so true.

2359
01:25:35,063 --> 01:25:38,199
-How does he keep it under control?
-He must've been craving it.

2360
01:25:38,266 --> 01:25:39,934
You'll see soggy <i>sundae</i> pieces

2361
01:25:40,001 --> 01:25:41,503
<i>deep inside the pot.</i>

2362
01:25:41,569 --> 01:25:44,439
-It'll taste different from the others.
-Way down low.

2363
01:25:44,506 --> 01:25:45,440
That's the best piece.

2364
01:25:46,040 --> 01:25:48,943
-The one that's completely soaked.
-It's completely soaked.

2365
01:25:49,010 --> 01:25:51,212
-That's it.
-It was in there.

2366
01:25:51,279 --> 01:25:54,149
-That's it.
-Even better when it burns your throat.

2367
01:25:54,215 --> 01:25:56,451
The twins are so excited to see <i>gukbap.</i>

2368
01:25:56,518 --> 01:25:58,486
-Yes, they're quite noisy.
-They're excited.

2369
01:25:58,553 --> 01:26:00,655
Can you share just one piece with us?

2370
01:26:00,722 --> 01:26:04,259
-We usually leave this out to cool.
-Yes, that's right.

2371
01:26:04,325 --> 01:26:07,462
When I eat soup and rice
or something like <i>gukbap,</i>

2372
01:26:07,529 --> 01:26:09,497
I usually stay away from rice.

2373
01:26:09,564 --> 01:26:12,300
But this is making me
want to mix it with rice.

2374
01:26:13,067 --> 01:26:14,736
It makes him crave rice.

2375
01:26:14,802 --> 01:26:16,638
Can you taste the <i>ramyeon </i>soup base?

2376
01:26:16,704 --> 01:26:18,840
Honestly, I can't.

2377
01:26:19,908 --> 01:26:22,877
<i>The balance of bonito flakes</i>
<i>and anchovy broth is amazing.</i>

2378
01:26:22,944 --> 01:26:25,280
Bonito and anchovy broth is the base,

2379
01:26:25,346 --> 01:26:27,949
and I only added
about one milligram of the soup base.

2380
01:26:28,516 --> 01:26:29,951
Didn't you throw in an entire packet?

2381
01:26:30,018 --> 01:26:32,754
-No, there's a lot left here.
-Is there?

2382
01:26:32,820 --> 01:26:33,988
You used just a bit.

2383
01:26:34,055 --> 01:26:36,224
-The last bite.
-The soaked <i>sundae.</i>

2384
01:26:36,291 --> 01:26:38,560
-This is it.
-The edge pieces are always the best!

2385
01:26:38,626 --> 01:26:40,528
That one with glass noodles.

2386
01:26:40,929 --> 01:26:42,664
OH, MY

2387
01:26:43,064 --> 01:26:44,232
NOM

2388
01:26:44,299 --> 01:26:45,400
It's over.

2389
01:26:45,466 --> 01:26:47,302
IT'S SO HOT

2390
01:26:47,368 --> 01:26:48,836
He doesn't have any kimchi.

2391
01:26:48,903 --> 01:26:50,538
-He could cool it down with some.
-Don't drink water.

2392
01:26:50,605 --> 01:26:52,507
It dilutes the flavor. Push through.

2393
01:26:52,574 --> 01:26:54,676
I wonder what the taste is like?

2394
01:26:54,742 --> 01:26:56,044
I also love <i>tteokbokki,</i>

2395
01:26:56,110 --> 01:26:58,112
and I'm someone
who soaks fritters in the sauce

2396
01:26:58,179 --> 01:27:01,516
-until they soak up all the sauce.
-That's so good.

2397
01:27:01,583 --> 01:27:03,017
That's how I like my fritters.

2398
01:27:03,084 --> 01:27:04,986
-And this tastes just like that.
-He knows how to do it.

2399
01:27:05,053 --> 01:27:08,423
The fritter soaks up the sauce
and releases it in your mouth.

2400
01:27:08,489 --> 01:27:11,392
Meanwhile, the floating island
is slowly sinking.

2401
01:27:11,459 --> 01:27:13,461
-It's sinking.
-It's going down.

2402
01:27:13,528 --> 01:27:16,231
Next, Webtoon Artist Poong's Mr. Sonshine.

2403
01:27:17,732 --> 01:27:21,102
KIM POONG'S TRADITIONAL
FRENCH DESSERT

2404
01:27:22,570 --> 01:27:25,940
FLOATING SHINE MUSCAT
AND MERINGUE

2405
01:27:27,575 --> 01:27:31,412
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
MR. SONSHINE

2406
01:27:31,479 --> 01:27:35,950
Please scoop up the meringue
with the balsamic sauce

2407
01:27:36,017 --> 01:27:37,685
and have it with a grape.

2408
01:27:37,752 --> 01:27:40,288
Your instructions
are rather detailed today.

2409
01:27:41,155 --> 01:27:43,124
SINCE TODAY IS A SPECIAL DAY

2410
01:27:43,191 --> 01:27:46,294
Actually, by the way this dish looks,

2411
01:27:46,361 --> 01:27:49,197
including the dishware he chose,
makes me think I underestimated him.

2412
01:27:49,530 --> 01:27:51,099
HAD HIDDEN TALENTS?

2413
01:27:51,833 --> 01:27:54,168
He could actually make
an unscathed dish like this.

2414
01:27:54,235 --> 01:27:55,470
Everything looks unscathed.

2415
01:27:55,536 --> 01:27:56,404
NODS FOR NOW

2416
01:27:56,471 --> 01:28:00,008
He must've been trying
to make everyone laugh before.

2417
01:28:00,074 --> 01:28:01,175
I'm getting curious.

2418
01:28:01,676 --> 01:28:03,211
The floating island.

2419
01:28:03,878 --> 01:28:05,480
-Did it turn out well?
-It's fluffy.

2420
01:28:05,546 --> 01:28:06,381
It's fluffy.

2421
01:28:09,150 --> 01:28:11,719
-The texture looks really nice.
-It's such a wonder.

2422
01:28:11,786 --> 01:28:14,188
-How did he do that?
-Have it with the balsamic sauce.

2423
01:28:14,255 --> 01:28:15,156
Please try it.

2424
01:28:15,757 --> 01:28:16,991
TAKES A BIG BITE OF FAITH

2425
01:28:17,058 --> 01:28:18,393
Goodness.

2426
01:28:19,627 --> 01:28:20,762
It's a traditional dessert.

2427
01:28:21,996 --> 01:28:23,564
WIDE-EYED

2428
01:28:23,631 --> 01:28:25,600
-His eyes widened.
-What does that mean?

2429
01:28:25,667 --> 01:28:27,368
-He's surprised.
-Yes.

2430
01:28:27,969 --> 01:28:30,738
It feels as if I'm the one floating.

2431
01:28:31,472 --> 01:28:33,441
-He feels like he's floating.
-It's an emergency.

2432
01:28:33,508 --> 01:28:35,443
-It's an emergency.
-This is an emergency.

2433
01:28:35,510 --> 01:28:37,679
We expected Ho-young to seize
an overwhelming victory.

2434
01:28:37,745 --> 01:28:40,515
-He flirted with the floating island.
-Yes, it's flirting.

2435
01:28:40,581 --> 01:28:42,417
It's a flirting island.

2436
01:28:42,483 --> 01:28:43,584
"A flirting island"?

2437
01:28:43,651 --> 01:28:45,019
-He tries the sauce.
-It looks good.

2438
01:28:45,086 --> 01:28:48,356
It's not the texture I expected
from crème anglaise,

2439
01:28:48,423 --> 01:28:50,091
but this is even more refreshing and good.

2440
01:28:50,358 --> 01:28:51,693
THAT'S EXACTLY IT

2441
01:28:51,759 --> 01:28:53,895
It's different from his expectation,
but in a good way.

2442
01:28:53,961 --> 01:28:55,463
HE WON'T STOP EATING

2443
01:28:56,030 --> 01:28:58,166
I have nothing else to let go of, so…

2444
01:28:58,232 --> 01:29:00,134
-The button.
-I can undo the button.

2445
01:29:00,201 --> 01:29:02,036
He's probably getting full.

2446
01:29:02,103 --> 01:29:05,173
-It looks good.
-I always thought he was a light eater.

2447
01:29:05,239 --> 01:29:07,542
The shine muscat… That looks amazing.

2448
01:29:07,608 --> 01:29:08,943
-It looks good.
-He eats so well.

2449
01:29:09,010 --> 01:29:10,645
-Take a breather.
-I've never seen him like this.

2450
01:29:10,712 --> 01:29:12,413
The moment a dessert is delicious,

2451
01:29:12,480 --> 01:29:15,216
my head blanks out, and I keep eating
without considering the calories.

2452
01:29:15,283 --> 01:29:19,887
When the dessert is delicious,
you don't even remember the main dish.

2453
01:29:20,188 --> 01:29:21,889
MY WORLD IS CRASHING DOWN…

2454
01:29:21,956 --> 01:29:23,057
-He's finishing it.
-In the end…

2455
01:29:23,124 --> 01:29:24,726
he can't escape from him.

2456
01:29:24,792 --> 01:29:25,827
STUCK ON THE ISLAND
THAT IS KIM POONG

2457
01:29:25,893 --> 01:29:27,595
How's the shine muscat?

2458
01:29:27,662 --> 01:29:29,664
It tastes like shine muscat.

2459
01:29:29,731 --> 01:29:32,400
-It just tastes like itself?
-The raw ingredient?

2460
01:29:32,467 --> 01:29:33,801
<i>Why did you work so hard on them?</i>

2461
01:29:33,868 --> 01:29:36,604
<i>The texture I wanted to create</i>

2462
01:29:36,671 --> 01:29:40,942
was something soft all around
that would melt in your mouth.

2463
01:29:41,008 --> 01:29:42,310
That was your plan.

2464
01:29:43,144 --> 01:29:44,712
When he was torn

2465
01:29:44,779 --> 01:29:47,315
<i>whether or not to add balsamic vinegar,</i>

2466
01:29:47,382 --> 01:29:48,683
No, don't do it.

2467
01:29:48,750 --> 01:29:50,685
<i>…I thought he shouldn't use it,</i>

2468
01:29:50,752 --> 01:29:53,654
but it adds some acidity,
making me go back for more.

2469
01:29:54,222 --> 01:29:56,891
Since shine muscat is a grape,

2470
01:29:56,958 --> 01:29:58,426
I thought it'd go well
with balsamic vinegar.

2471
01:29:58,626 --> 01:29:59,694
SURPRISED!

2472
01:29:59,761 --> 01:30:01,262
-Wait.
-He had a plan.

2473
01:30:01,329 --> 01:30:04,031
That was a pretty good line
for something he made up just now.

2474
01:30:04,098 --> 01:30:05,833
I do not think this was intended.

2475
01:30:06,100 --> 01:30:06,934
GROAN

2476
01:30:07,001 --> 01:30:09,737
-Why not?
-It's the cherry on top he always adds

2477
01:30:09,804 --> 01:30:11,873
when things begin to go well.

2478
01:30:11,939 --> 01:30:14,175
We're hearing him
scraping the bottom of the dish.

2479
01:30:14,242 --> 01:30:16,277
-Poong should open a cafe.
-Yes.

2480
01:30:16,344 --> 01:30:18,346
He scraped the entire bowl of dessert.

2481
01:30:18,946 --> 01:30:20,848
IT MUST BE THAT GOOD

2482
01:30:20,915 --> 01:30:23,184
He's done. He finished it.

2483
01:30:23,251 --> 01:30:24,752
-Yes.
-It's hard to tell.

2484
01:30:24,819 --> 01:30:26,020
Was it not too sweet?

2485
01:30:26,087 --> 01:30:29,056
-The balance was great.
-The balance.

2486
01:30:29,123 --> 01:30:30,158
I was really surprised.

2487
01:30:30,224 --> 01:30:32,493
-Do you have some more?
-I do.

2488
01:30:32,560 --> 01:30:33,728
Let's try some.

2489
01:30:35,163 --> 01:30:37,331
-I mean, this is good.
-Right?

2490
01:30:38,699 --> 01:30:40,902
Well, it's the texture.

2491
01:30:40,968 --> 01:30:42,036
I'm torn.

2492
01:30:43,104 --> 01:30:43,938
What do I do?

2493
01:30:44,005 --> 01:30:45,473
I was sure this would win.

2494
01:30:50,111 --> 01:30:51,312
This is driving me crazy.

2495
01:30:52,346 --> 01:30:55,216
All right.
Let's try Chef Ho-young's dish first.

2496
01:30:55,283 --> 01:30:56,317
The <i>sundae-gukbap.</i>

2497
01:30:56,884 --> 01:30:59,153
ULTIMATELY MANAGED
TO SECURE A POT

2498
01:30:59,220 --> 01:31:00,688
Hey, man. Let's get started.

2499
01:31:00,922 --> 01:31:02,757
EXCITED

2500
01:31:02,824 --> 01:31:04,559
This is why I come to the show.

2501
01:31:04,625 --> 01:31:07,328
Do you have anything for me?

2502
01:31:08,029 --> 01:31:09,230
Nam-no has everything.

2503
01:31:09,297 --> 01:31:11,566
-But I'm a guest today.
-Oh, right.

2504
01:31:11,632 --> 01:31:12,767
GUEST THAT DOESN'T GET TO EAT

2505
01:31:13,134 --> 01:31:15,603
THE TWIN FATTIES HAVE NO IDEA
THAT THE GUEST WANTS SOME

2506
01:31:15,670 --> 01:31:17,505
Do you two eat well outside the studio?

2507
01:31:19,307 --> 01:31:22,577
I'll remember this taste
for a very long time.

2508
01:31:23,144 --> 01:31:26,848
This <i>sundae </i>he made turned out so nice.

2509
01:31:26,914 --> 01:31:28,182
It's so good.

2510
01:31:28,249 --> 01:31:29,417
SO HOT

2511
01:31:29,484 --> 01:31:33,020
I'd buy like 20 of these
if this were a meal kit

2512
01:31:33,087 --> 01:31:34,922
-and eat it every day.
-I see.

2513
01:31:34,989 --> 01:31:37,258
-It isn't too spicy.
-Right.

2514
01:31:37,325 --> 01:31:38,459
It feels like a mix

2515
01:31:38,526 --> 01:31:42,463
of <i>doenjang-jjigae</i> with rice
and <i>sundae </i>inside <i>sundae-guk</i>.

2516
01:31:42,530 --> 01:31:45,500
-No one can hate this.
-Right.

2517
01:31:45,566 --> 01:31:49,036
That was a perfect, hot,
and hearty meal in every way.

2518
01:31:49,604 --> 01:31:52,273
It would be nice as a bar snack
and even for children.

2519
01:31:52,340 --> 01:31:54,342
-Can anything beat this?
-It's hard to beat.

2520
01:31:54,408 --> 01:31:56,277
Yes, how can he beat this?

2521
01:31:56,344 --> 01:31:58,312
-Next, Poong's dish.
-It's dessert.

2522
01:31:58,379 --> 01:32:00,114
-Poong's dessert.
-Can this win?

2523
01:32:00,181 --> 01:32:01,949
Gosh, this is good.

2524
01:32:02,650 --> 01:32:04,252
-He said to eat it with the grape, right?
-Yes, all at once.

2525
01:32:04,886 --> 01:32:06,187
Has it begun again?

2526
01:32:06,254 --> 01:32:07,655
POONG'S MAGIC AT IT AGAIN?

2527
01:32:08,256 --> 01:32:09,423
Why is this good?

2528
01:32:11,392 --> 01:32:13,995
I would believe it
if someone said Jong-won made it.

2529
01:32:14,629 --> 01:32:15,663
RUBBING OFF ON EACH OTHER

2530
01:32:15,730 --> 01:32:18,633
I would believe it
to be one of Jong-won's dishes.

2531
01:32:19,200 --> 01:32:21,469
The texture had zero crispness.

2532
01:32:21,536 --> 01:32:23,471
The shine muscat didn't taste raw.

2533
01:32:23,538 --> 01:32:26,741
<i>-Like sous vide.</i>
<i>-It changed into something soft.</i>

2534
01:32:27,074 --> 01:32:28,309
KEEPS EATING

2535
01:32:28,376 --> 01:32:30,912
It looks like
you don't want to give him the credit,

2536
01:32:30,978 --> 01:32:32,847
-but you have to.
-Let me elaborate.

2537
01:32:32,914 --> 01:32:34,215
He's like the town dunce

2538
01:32:34,282 --> 01:32:37,451
that actually turns out
to be a martial arts expert.

2539
01:32:37,518 --> 01:32:40,688
Like some kind of freedom fighter
who actually kicks butt.

2540
01:32:40,755 --> 01:32:43,257
But he has to act stupid
to hide his identity.

2541
01:32:43,324 --> 01:32:44,625
QUITE CLICHÉ
HIS TALENTS ARE NOW EXPOSED

2542
01:32:44,692 --> 01:32:46,160
Maybe he's actually a chef.

2543
01:32:46,227 --> 01:32:48,229
Is he acting like a fool,
although he's a chef?

2544
01:32:48,296 --> 01:32:49,664
I'm surprised.

2545
01:32:49,730 --> 01:32:51,532
The egg whites

2546
01:32:51,599 --> 01:32:55,469
<i>usually smell like eggs when you eat it,</i>
<i>and you expect that.</i>

2547
01:32:55,536 --> 01:32:59,840
But it somehow turned into a latte
with the flavor of milk.

2548
01:32:59,907 --> 01:33:02,209
It's ultimately a top quality dish.

2549
01:33:02,276 --> 01:33:04,579
He's looking more troubled.

2550
01:33:04,645 --> 01:33:08,382
I'm sure this round got you thinking.

2551
01:33:08,449 --> 01:33:11,052
-Right?
-I finally understand the guests.

2552
01:33:11,118 --> 01:33:13,521
-It's much easier to cook.
-Is that so?

2553
01:33:13,588 --> 01:33:15,089
<i>Press one for Ho-young</i>

2554
01:33:15,957 --> 01:33:17,224
<i>and two for Poong.</i>

2555
01:33:18,426 --> 01:33:20,461
To whom will you give your star

2556
01:33:20,528 --> 01:33:22,396
as a judge with a chef's perspective?

2557
01:33:22,463 --> 01:33:25,333
Please make your decision
and press the button!

2558
01:33:25,399 --> 01:33:28,769
Both of them have one win and one loss,

2559
01:33:28,836 --> 01:33:30,738
so who's going to win their second star?

2560
01:33:30,805 --> 01:33:33,240
-He looks so cool when he thinks.
-Yes.

2561
01:33:33,307 --> 01:33:35,876
The fun part is over.
You were so happy eating the food.

2562
01:33:35,943 --> 01:33:38,145
He grabs the remote control again.

2563
01:33:38,212 --> 01:33:40,147
He has pressed a button.

2564
01:33:40,214 --> 01:33:43,784
-Jong-won pressed the button.
-Who is it?

2565
01:33:44,185 --> 01:33:45,353
TORMENTED

2566
01:33:45,419 --> 01:33:47,154
And Jong-won covers his face.

2567
01:33:47,221 --> 01:33:48,289
-But why?
-Yes.

2568
01:33:48,356 --> 01:33:50,224
I'm sure he feels bad for one of them.

2569
01:33:50,291 --> 01:33:52,860
Let's find out the result. Show us!

2570
01:33:53,661 --> 01:33:56,497
Will it be Ho-young's <i>gukbap</i>

2571
01:33:56,564 --> 01:33:58,332
or Poong's dessert?

2572
01:33:58,399 --> 01:34:01,736
Who will you give your star to, Jong-won?

2573
01:34:01,802 --> 01:34:03,671
They're both fighting
for their second win.

2574
01:34:03,738 --> 01:34:05,072
Who did the chef choose?

2575
01:34:05,740 --> 01:34:07,742
Who did the chef choose?

2576
01:34:07,808 --> 01:34:09,010
Who is it?

2577
01:34:10,878 --> 01:34:11,712
Who is it?

2578
01:34:11,779 --> 01:34:14,048
KIM POONG WINS

2579
01:34:14,115 --> 01:34:16,217
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
MR. SONSHINE WINS

2580
01:34:16,283 --> 01:34:17,318
Kim Poong wins!

2581
01:34:17,385 --> 01:34:18,719
YAHOO

2582
01:34:18,786 --> 01:34:20,588
Kim Poong wins the round!

2583
01:34:20,655 --> 01:34:21,489
Great work, Poong.

2584
01:34:21,555 --> 01:34:24,425
He's currently tied for first place.

2585
01:34:24,492 --> 01:34:26,260
I feel like the choice was out of love.

2586
01:34:26,327 --> 01:34:27,395
SIGH

2587
01:34:27,461 --> 01:34:29,363
-Poong takes his second star.
-It was good.

2588
01:34:29,430 --> 01:34:33,167
I'm sure some viewers are going,
"I knew he'd choose him."

2589
01:34:33,234 --> 01:34:36,070
I think Poong often wins
by shooting down the expectation,

2590
01:34:36,137 --> 01:34:40,675
only to let the guest think,
"It's not so bad" when they try it.

2591
01:34:40,741 --> 01:34:42,576
But today, that wasn't the case.

2592
01:34:42,643 --> 01:34:45,813
<i>I'm curious to know</i>
<i>if he'll ever make a dish like this again.</i>

2593
01:34:45,880 --> 01:34:47,581
Also, it was the order too.

2594
01:34:47,648 --> 01:34:51,252
If I had the dessert first
before trying the <i>gukbap,</i>

2595
01:34:51,318 --> 01:34:52,787
-I would've forgotten about it.
-Yes.

2596
01:34:52,853 --> 01:34:56,123
But after eating a delicious bowl
of Ho-young's delicious food,

2597
01:34:56,190 --> 01:34:58,259
<i>I got to clean my palate with this,</i>

2598
01:34:58,325 --> 01:35:00,227
<i>which left a longer impression.</i>

2599
01:35:00,294 --> 01:35:04,665
Also, I have a love for dessert,
so that nice finish was memorable.

2600
01:35:04,732 --> 01:35:06,467
-I see.
-A different type of dopamine rush.

2601
01:35:06,534 --> 01:35:09,770
My gosh. That was an unexpected result.

2602
01:35:09,837 --> 01:35:14,275
I knew I couldn't win
if I did my thing as usual.

2603
01:35:14,341 --> 01:35:16,377
-I see.
-So I came up with the strategy

2604
01:35:16,444 --> 01:35:18,112
to use a traditional recipe,

2605
01:35:18,179 --> 01:35:19,847
because I knew he'd be strict.

2606
01:35:19,914 --> 01:35:22,116
If it works, it works. If not, so be it.

2607
01:35:22,183 --> 01:35:23,884
It was an attempt to make a winning move.

2608
01:35:23,951 --> 01:35:28,289
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong
receives a star from Chef Jong-won.

2609
01:35:28,355 --> 01:35:29,290
Congratulations!

2610
01:35:30,024 --> 01:35:31,959
Poong now has two wins.

2611
01:35:33,027 --> 01:35:35,629
He's getting ahead of Ho-young.

2612
01:35:35,696 --> 01:35:37,665
Congratulations, Poong!

2613
01:35:37,732 --> 01:35:39,834
He made a wonderful dessert.

2614
01:35:41,001 --> 01:35:43,738
<i>You're watching a special</i>
<i>Lunar New Year Episode,</i>

2615
01:35:43,804 --> 01:35:45,172
<i>a party for our chefs.</i>

2616
01:35:45,239 --> 01:35:46,474
THE CHEFS' PARTY

2617
01:35:46,540 --> 01:35:48,375
We got our hands on your childhood photos.

2618
01:35:48,442 --> 01:35:49,610
How cute. Who's that?

2619
01:35:49,677 --> 01:35:51,078
You were always blessed with food.

2620
01:35:51,145 --> 01:35:53,080
We got black-and-white pictures.

2621
01:35:53,147 --> 01:35:54,315
Was that during the famine?

2622
01:35:54,381 --> 01:35:55,783
SUDDENLY BRINGS UP THE FAMINE

2623
01:35:55,850 --> 01:35:57,384
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Cup Thigh Wrestling.

2624
01:35:57,451 --> 01:35:58,652
I can beat you.

2625
01:35:59,053 --> 01:36:00,821
HIGH COMPETITIVE SPIRIT

2626
01:36:01,222 --> 01:36:04,492
WHO'S THE THIGH WRESTLING
CHAMPION?

2627
01:36:04,558 --> 01:36:07,661
This time, I want them
to exchange each other's cuisines.

2628
01:36:07,962 --> 01:36:09,163
A BOLT OUT OF THE BLUE

2629
01:36:09,230 --> 01:36:11,065
<i>He immediately grabs</i>
<i>a Chinese kitchen knife.</i>

2630
01:36:11,265 --> 01:36:12,099
STRIKE

2631
01:36:12,166 --> 01:36:13,300
Slap!

2632
01:36:13,367 --> 01:36:14,435
He can't chop as well.

2633
01:36:14,502 --> 01:36:16,637
-It's an emergency.
-I have to <i>mantecare</i>!

2634
01:36:16,704 --> 01:36:18,072
That's not how you do it!

2635
01:36:18,139 --> 01:36:19,440
BACK TO HER OLD CUISINE

2636
01:36:19,507 --> 01:36:21,375
<i>You're asking the two top chefs in Korea</i>

2637
01:36:21,442 --> 01:36:23,210
to reinterpret your dishes?

2638
01:36:23,277 --> 01:36:24,879
That's how you peel a melon?

2639
01:36:24,945 --> 01:36:25,913
THE BOOTLEG CHEF LEARNS

2640
01:36:25,980 --> 01:36:27,948
He's making the loaches!

2641
01:36:28,015 --> 01:36:29,250
Someone flush the pan.

2642
01:36:29,316 --> 01:36:30,785
Someone left without flushing.

2643
01:36:30,851 --> 01:36:32,019
My gosh. Really?

2644
01:36:32,086 --> 01:36:33,721
He said he'd upgrade the dish.

2645
01:36:35,723 --> 01:36:37,458
A MAKEOVER FOR THE BOOTLEG DISHES?!

2646
01:36:40,494 --> 01:36:42,563
Doesn't he look like a shaman
named Young Napoli Boy?

2647
01:36:42,630 --> 01:36:43,731
Napoli Matboy.

2648
01:36:43,798 --> 01:36:45,800
<i>-Chef & My Fridge </i>will do well.
-I see.

2649
01:36:45,866 --> 01:36:47,902
-It'll do well in 2026.
-Really?

2650
01:36:58,712 --> 01:37:03,717
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
